animal.description:
Bella (2008-1504) - Bella is a beautiful 2 year-old girl with a lovely fawn and white coat and
yellow eyes. She is a pitbull, spayed, close to 50 lbs., and house trained. No cats, older or no
children, fearful of men. It's currently recommended that she be an only dog or be matched with
a dog of similar size with a calm, mature personality.

Bella is loving, very smart, and wants to please. She is also very young, energetic but not hyper,
and has a strong prey drive. She is being fostered because she was very nervous in the
shelter. The foster noted that from the first moment outside the shelter Bella showed confidence
and calm. She is affectionate and wants to be close to you, so she prefers to be next to you on
the furniture and sleeping in bed with you; however, if you indicate to her that you need some
space she will go to her own bed or comforter.

Bella should have long and/or plentiful walks and loves car rides. This dog can't just be a yard
dog; she needs movement and stimulation. Her foster believes she may tend towards
depression without regular outdoor activity. Please note that Bella is a big backroller. Currently
she gets at least four walks a day because she is in the country without a fenced-in yard. There
have been no accidents. She also likes to look out the window and some space should be
allowed for that.

When it comes to other dogs, Bella generally does well. But whether it's because Bella has
never been socialized with other dogs or she just has a pushy streak when she gets excited or
playful, it's recommended that she be paired with a resident dog who is a similar size, calm, and
on the submissive side.

Because of Bella's strong interest in odors, movement, and noises, she may make quick moves
towards or away from something (squirrels, toads, crickets, odd-shaped leaves). The good thing
is that within a few times of being redirected by the leash, being told to sit, stay, or leave it, she
stops the pulling and will come back, but the adopter would have to be on the alert for these
moves.

Bella has a hearty appetite. The foster found that two large and two small meals worked best
for her. She loves treats and takes them gently and treats along with praise, of course, speeds
up the training process.

Bella needs major league chew toys. She can tear up Kongs. So far nylabones are working.
She spends time with them everyday. And she seems to understand the difference between
what is okay and not okay to chew.

Bella accepts being left alone whether in the house at large, in a room, or in the garage. Her
foster has left her with a soft spot, water, treats, and a chew toy for hours while guests were in
the house or when she was out for the day without incident. Bella doesn't whine, bark, or
scratch at the door.

Bella is a dog who listens and wants to make you happy. An adopter who loves time outdoors,
who has some physical strength and confidence when it comes to sudden redirecting, and who
can honor the personality of a smart and sensitive dog will be blessed with Bella.
animal.name: 2008-1504 Bella (Off Site Foster)

animal.description:
I'm Ludwig! Ain't I cute? I'm sooo sweet and cuddly once I get to know you. I have some reservations if you reach over my head -- maybe someone hurt me a long time ago? I roamed the streets eating any place that would feed me. Now I need someone to love me forever! I'd prefer a home with no children. Once I warm up to you, I let my true personality shine. I love going on walks at the shelter with the humans who taught me it was okay. I need a human who will love me enough to respect my boundaries and patient enough to work with me over time so I can learn how to trust again. Do you think it can be you?

We suggest a meet and greet with anyone interested in adopting Ludwig. He is a very sweet boy, but has some quirks. We believe he would fit best in a one person home with no other animals, as he becomes possessive of the person closest to him and will try protect them.
 
Come meet me at the City Of Taylor, Texas Animal Shelter or call 512-352-5483 for more information.

Temperament:
NO OTHER ANIMALS

MY DEETS:
- male
- terrier mix
- about 15 pounds

animal.description:
LOGAN RED
DOB: 11.12.2019*

Red was in a bad situation. He was wondering in the fields when a good samaritan working in those fields took him and Jackson home but kept them outside 24/7 in triple digit heat. Paw Printz convinced the good samaritan that was not good for them so they surrendered the two dogs to Paw Printz. Now they are happy in the air conditioning after a good play in the yard. They tend to get a little rough in their play so need to be supervised carefully. Placing them in separate home would be best at this point.

Red is still a bit skiddish around people but has come a long way. Listens well and learns fast. Logan Red is about 50 pounds.  neutered, housebroken, crate trained, current on vaccinations and microchipped.

If you think Red would be the perfect addition to your home, send an email to: PawPrintzRescue@gmail.com and request an application.

Adoption Fee: $200
Adoption Requirements: Application, Interview, Homecheck

THIS DOG IS LOCATED NEAR FRESNO, CA

*Age is always a guess with rescue dogs but here at Paw Printz we believe everyone should have a birth day so when the vet guesses at their age, we work out what would be a good birthday for each dog and make it so!

Here's a little senior lambchop sure to please an owner who would like a small, quiet, loving senior lapdog. Vieja is blind and mostly deaf. She has recovered from an injury that caused some diminishing paralysis and seems to be doing well getting around. 

She is soft, silky, friendly and calm with other animals, and she love, love, loves to be quietly held. This girl is your TV companion, your work-from-home partner, your study buddy. If she could be in a lap 100% of the time, she would. Well, 98% of the time, because the other 1% she would be eating (healthy appetite) and attending to her duties outside. She is beautifully housebroken and woofs to signal she needs to go out. (She will also woof if she wants to be with someone. Not a demanding dog, but she does like interaction with others and to be in the thick of the action, rather than removed to a quiet guest space.) Recommend a family without small or boisterous children or pets who could tumble her. With calm dogs, cats, people -- shes chill, baby. Did I mention she LOVES sitting in laps, sleeping snuggled next to you, and adores ear rubs? Rewards you with a tiny hummingbird-fast twitch of her tail. She walks with some wobbliness and quick fatigue, but walking. She is a calm girl who wags when you pick her up. Very stable at the groomers, so whatever her history, at some point in the past she became familiar with being groomed. We got her tidied up, mat free, bathed, neat feet and ears and eyes. She seems happy that shes about to have a little snack! 

All Dallas DogRRR adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon finalizing adoption. The standard minimum donation for puppies is $325 + 8.25% tax = $351.81, for dogs over 12 months the adoption fee is $225 + 8.25% tax = $243.66 and for our senior dogs 8 years and up is $100 + 8.25% tax = $108.25; this increase includes sales tax recently required by the State of Texas to collect. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. 

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process.

animal.description:
Dune is a 7 year old precious little Shih Tzu who weighs 14.8 lbs. Dune had to have both eyes removed earlier due to ulcerations. He’s such a sweet little guy, and being blind doesn’t slow him down one bit!  
Here’s how his foster mom describes him:
“ He is very cuddly. He loves belly rubs. He sleeps on the bed with me. During the day when I am at work he is free to explore the house. He does a good job of waiting for me to return to potty unless I'm late. I carry him out to the yard and tell him to potty and he walks around does his business and then explores. I call his name and he will come to me. He knows how to sit up and ask for a treat. He is a happy boy!”
If you’d like to meet Dune, the first step is to complete and submit an adoption application on our okwestirescue.com website and we’ll get the process started. 
Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 
Dune’s adoption fee is $150 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.
We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 
We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support.

animal.description:
Meet Storm!
Storm is an honorary doberman in a Weimaraner body!
 He is a owner surrender that was bounced around 3 different homes because no one could keep up with his energy. Storm needs a very active owner that is willing to exercise him for several hours a day. He does have anxiety when he can't see his people but is not destructive but will bark constantly when left alone, due to this he would not be ideal to be in an apartment. Storm will need a privacy fenced back yard of at least 6ft as he is a jumper. 
 Storm loves people but he can not be in a home with other animals as he doesn't get along with other male or female dogs and he has a high prey drive for the small animals. He will need a very special home that can give him what he needs. 

 On a good note this boy absolutely loves to jump on trampolines and loves playing fetch and will return the ball. He does know several basic commands but does pull on leash but if you use the sit command to make him stop he does pretty well. He is a strong boy so no children should be taking him for walks alone. He would cuddle all day on a couch and bed with you. He is not a fan of storms ironically or fireworks. Storm is very protective of his family he will bark at people when passing in cars, drive through and on walks. After proper meetings are done he is fine with people coming up to him. He has been with children from ages new born to 13 and never had any issues. 

If you are an active family with no other pets Storm will be the best addition to your home!

All animals adopted from us are fully vetted including spay/neuter, vaccines, microchip, heartworm test and deworming. Please email us at HookedOnDobies@gmail.com, visit our Facebook page www.facebook.com/savingdobermankind or webpage https://www.savingdobermankind.org to request an application, inquire about an adoption fee, or to learn more! 

We do require a completed adoption application to be submitted before discussing details of a specific Doberman. 

We DO NOT have a central location, out foster homes are located throughout our geographic region including CO, WY, NM and TX.

We strive to PROTECT the privacy of out fosters. ALL Doberman meet and greets are conducted in a neutral meeting location made by appointment only.

animal.description:
Hi! My name Kiki! I am 8 years old, purebred Labrador, weighing 110 pounds. I have all of my vaccinations and am neutered (and I also got my teeth cleaned).
Here is my story:
I was born in the Mexican state of Sonora, but my owner left me temporarily with a relative in Mexicali when he moved to Tijuana. Once he was able to, he brought me home. However, I am a friendly boy and would wonder around, visiting people I didn’t know, so my owner decided it was best if a better home were found for me. My previous owner and his family all took really good care of me and I was well fed and treated.  Eventually a rescue person took me in until I could adopted to a good home.  You won’t believe this, but I went to the store with her one day and while she was inside a gentleman walked by, thought I was a stray and took me home.   My rescuer immediately put out flyers, so when the gentlemen saw the posters he contacted my rescuer and here I am back with her.   I had a really good time with the gentlemen that took me in and was also treated very well.  
If you’re getting tired reading this… you can imagine how I feel!  As you can see, I’ve been bounced around 6 times now! Seriously! I really need to get it together and find a forever home in the USA.  I am a very laid back guy, love to play, am very very loving and a great companion for anyone and I really love children, love to take walks (with or without leash).  I am a big beautiful boy and would love to come live with you and your family.

animal.description:
Chonks is a chunky meatball who will waddle his way into your heart! He was found as a stray and ended up at Animal Control. Luckily, his stay there was short-lived as his friendly demeanor and constantly wagging tail quickly landed him in a foster home. 

Chonks does great with dogs his size or bigger but is too much for smaller dogs. He’s also not a fan of cats.. or rather is a bit too MUCH of a fan of cats (and not in a good way). Generally, he seems to think he’s a herding dog and maybe even has some herding in his genes but he is in training now and we are working to manage his herding tendencies. Because of these tendencies, however, it would be best for him to be placed in a home with older children who can get themselves out of herding situations easily. 

Chonks is a happy, enthusiastic, and playful boy who is looking for an experienced adopter who can continue his training. He is a total goofball who loves toys, especially tug toys and balls! He LOVES to cuddle, but attaches to people quickly, so he will need a strong leader who can help him work on his manners and reach his full potential. 

If interested in Chonks, fill out a survey at www.playersforpits.com/adoptionsurvey!

animal.description: Meet Romeo! Romeo for four years was seen on a chain every day and always in the same space. After years of seeing this the owner was finally approached and Romeo was freed off the chain, medically vetted and now in need of a forever home. Romeo is a Lab mix with a smooth silky coat, 63 pounds, 4-5 years old, sweet as can be and a good boy that is so worthy. Romeo does great with small dogs and cats. Cats can be all around him and he doesn’t mind or bother them. He is intimidated by bigger male dogs and best to go to a home where there are small dogs or cats. He does have energy and will play and has done well around a 35 pound alpha male. He likes hugging you with his front legs wrapped around your waist even though we discourage jumping up. He has had limited experience with kids but has been good. His size and energy leads us to believe he is best around older kids or teens versus young children only because he may knock one down. Romeo spends his days now laying in a home office with his foster dad lying next to him enjoying the cool floor. He is learning to walk on a leash and seems to be improving, does bark at strangers as they approach, but quickly warms up to people after being introduced. He hasn’t had a single accident in the house considering he was a chained dog. He would love a home with a male buddy and definitely a fenced in yard he could roam around freely when he has to go potty. Romeo will still require patients and love. Romeo is fully medically vetted and tested negative for heartworms (Yeah!) and will be microchipped before going to a forever home. If you are wanting to make a difference in rescued dogs life Romeo is your boy! Go to complete the online pre-adoption application.

animal.description:
CoCo
Coco was adopted in 2018 BUT on April 20,2020 I received a message from Petlink that Coco had been found.( The SafeHouse stays on all id chips as guardian) I called the number and was stunned to see it was the city pound. I immediately went to get him and discovered he had been hit by a car and was injured(this happened on Saturday he had been there for 3 days with NO PAIN meds) Cocoa was in dire pain when I finally got him . He immediately went to AMC. He stayed there 2 days on iv with lots of pain meds to get his pain under control. He is now 3 weeks into the kennel rest stage of his recovery for a fractured right hip and cuts and road rash. Coco will want a new home when he is recovered. He is kind, loving, wants companionship and delights in tummy rubs. The FORMER owner never returned any of my calls or emails!  A certified letter terminated her rights to this sweet boy!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.All of the animals posted on our site have been temperament tested. While not all are in the immediate area, once we have processed and approved your application, we will move the dog to our adoptive area for you to meet, greet and hopefully adopt. Sometimes we will have more than one application on a dog. That does not mean it automatically goes to another family but you should be aware of the fact that until you are approved and set up for the meet/greet.. the dog could get adopted by another applicant.NOTE- PETE IS LISTED AS A COURTESY FOR ANOTHER RESCUE ORGANIZATION. PLEASE SEE CONTACT INFO BELOW.In 2012 Pete was at the Raleigh County Humane Society . I was on the Board of Directors there and quickly fell in love with him. He had too much energy for a shelter environment and basically went crazy any time he was taken out of the kennel. I was one of the only people that would spend time with pete due to his high energy. Pete was eventually put on the euthanasia list. The shelter was still a gassing shelter and he was set to head to the gas chamber. On the day he was scheduled to be killed , we , Operation Underdog, got him into an environment with a trainer. The guy took a liking to Pete and said that he would just adopt him. Fast forward to 2020, we see pete posted on facebook needing a home. Come to find out the adopter moved and had chosen not to take his faithful companion of 8 years with him. So now Pete is 9-10 years old. He is currently in a foster home on a farm. He is with pigs , cows and donkeys . He doesn't mind them at all. He is house trained, crate trained , does not try to escape a fence, does well with dogs and doesn't mind the cats. He is a very happy dog and loves everyone. Pete's smile is contagious. He loves attention and back scratches. I would suggest a home without children because pete is very strong and will jump when over stimulated. Pete also displays some resource guarding on things he determines is his. I have seen it with toys, food, a bed, or a chair. This does not happen all the time, 95% of the time he could care less. However, it is there and for that reason, I would suggest an experienced owner to adopt Pete so that when he does display that behavior it is safely managed and he is easily redirected. He is happy to swap a toy for a toy. He is a perfect combination of playtime and relaxing . He would prefer a fenced yard over walks. Pete is a very easy dog and deserves his FOREVER home. He is up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative, on heartworm and flea prevention, and neutered.

Anyone interested in learning more about Pete can email opundo@operationunderdog.org

animal.description:
Like all of us, Muffin has her quirks. 
When Muffin loves, she loves hard, with allll 60 lbs of her! She would love to just lay on your lap on the couch all day long. 
She does not understand how to play with other dogs despite being in a foster home with other dogs. 
While she has never been introduced to a cat, it is suspected she will need a home without cats as she does not like small animals (rabbits, squirrels, opossums).
She can be picky about her people, having had some problems with certain males. 
Preferably her humans are home more often than they are away as she has some separation anxiety, which has thus far been able to be treated with natural liquid remedy. 
Like most teenagers, she has proven to have selective hearing. She knows her basic commands but occasionally blatantly ignores then depending on who the command is coming from. 
She is good about not jumping, but sometimes out of happiness (usually before eating) she can get rather bouncy, which could prove problematic for a home with small children. 
She’ll deny it, but she SNORES like a freight train!

So please, in this new year, please please PLEASE help Muffin find her forever family. This girl will love you twice as hard as you love her. She just wants to love and be loved. It took months for Muffin to trust her foster mom, so we know she will need a home that is willing and able to be patient with her to earn her trust. 
Though it took her time to warm up to her foster parents, she is an absolute love. Her ideal day would be filled of cuddles on a fluffy surface with her hooman. Since completing her heart worm treatment she has gotten far more energy but should still be considered more on the chill side.

Ideally Muffin’s new home should be/have:
? PATIENT (this is a must!)
? Clear routine
?? No small children
?? No other animals
? Cuddles
? Fluffy surfaces - couch, bed, etc

Muffin is free to adopt to the right home  If you are interested in adopting any of our animals, please fill out an application at www.clevelandareapoundpals.com

Zoey came to rescue through no fault of her own. She was sadly surrendered by her owner, who did not have the means to care for her. Zoey really needed a fenced yard, and the installation of a fence was just not possible. 

Zoey has had a rough life and it's not going to get too much easier in the near future. She was recently vetted and found to be heart worm positive. The good news is that we have raised the money to pay for her treatment and give her the life that she so deserves. Paws crossed for Zoey's speedy recovery!

If you would like more information about Zoey, or would like to schedule a time to meet her, please contact us at 920-293-8885 or wooflodge@yahoo.com. Zoey will need to have a fenced yard. All of our dogs are current on vaccinations and are spayed or neutered.

animal.description:
Hi! Remember me? I’m Nikki. You’ve seen me around RCHS for a bit but I’ve been working with my foster mom and she told me that it was time for me to tell everyone how wonderful I am. For starters, I’m a really good girl -- I stand quietly twice daily for my insulin injections and then afterwards I give my foster mom a kiss. I'm also super adorable and love to jump up on laps and provide dog-slobber facials. Haven’t you heard – they are the latest thing and great for wrinkles! I also really like soft stuffies and will play fetch with them if you throw them for me.  

Now for the stuff that we still need to work on. I don’t like cats – at all. And I don’t really think that I’ll like children, though my foster mom has never tried that. I am house trained but since I am diabetic, I occasionally can’t hold my pee. My mom puts my in a doggie diaper when she goes out and overnight and most of the time it is clean when she takes it off – but sometimes I just can’t help it. I look really cute in the diaper!

I have 4 foster dog siblings about my size and we all get along just fine. I am a bit possessive over my food, though (I’m just so hungry!), so my mom just feeds me separately. I will need to have a fenced yard in my forever home.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our application here: http://www.rchsks.org/our-animals/adopt-a-pet/adopting-a-dog.  By filling out the application you are not committing yourself to adopting; it's a screening process that must be completed before you meet the dog. Please do this BEFORE calling. Our voicemail is only checked periodically and you can reach us much faster via dog-coordinators@rchsks.org.  Thank you!

animal.description:
This 3 1/2-year old male German Shepherd loves to have his belly rubbed, and just look at those big brown appreciative eyes! 

Cairo is taking supplements for what our Veterinarian partner determined is the beginnings of hip dysplasia. This should slow down the process and there is no need to add prescription medications at this time. He has a different gait but it sure doesnt slow him down and he is not in any pain. In fact he gets around quite well!

Cairo is settling into his foster home, and loves being part of the family. He is house trained, crate trained, and non-destructive. We will be introducing him to his foster siblings very soon, but what we can tell so far, is that he appears to be a real Ladies man, even with his cute little bobtail from an unknown prior injury!! 

This handsome boy hasnt shown any interest in toys, as he prefers to lounge in the sun. He walks well on leash, and loves car rides. He will make a great companion for a lucky adopter.

We anticipate that he would do best in a low to moderate activity home with an adopter who is willing to address his medical needs as they change. Only older children in an adoptive home will be considered.

His reaction to cats or other small creatures is unknown at this time, but we suspect they would not be a good match.

It will be necessary for an adopter to have experience in raising a GSD, or other large breed working dog. An adopter who will begin basic obedience training based upon positive reinforcement is recommended to ensure Cairo remains on the path of a well-behaved canine citizen, although he is pretty well behaved in the home.

animal.description:
Eli is a sweet beagle. We sometimes call him “little” because compared to our other beagles he is tiny. He was extremely timid when he first came to us, but he has warmed up to us now. He still is timid when you reach out your hand, which leaves me to believe he was abused at some point.

He is tough and will do a little grunt/growl if one of the other dogs comes too close when he is sleeping, but in general seems to really like being around the other dogs. He has never gritted his teeth or even seemed a bit aggressive. He is all beagle. He has a mischievous streak. He likes to sneak the kitchen towels outside and bury them. He will also sneak socks. If you see him with the towels/socks he will bring them to you and give them up if you ask. It’s somehow naughty and cute at the same time.

He had heartworm treatment, so he has a large patch of shaved hair on his back. He still has some problems with going potty in the house. He knows to use our doggy door, but sometimes he is lazy or stubborn.

He is so sweet and very soft. He loves to be scratched on the chin. He doesn’t mind being picked up and was very good in the car on the way to the vet’s office. He, like all beagles, really loves his food, and will gobble it up. He uses special prescription kidney food. He is currently finishing up his medication for heartworm treatment and should be done in a few days.

Eli's Webpage - http://beaglemaryland.org/brsm_ms/vIndividualCurrentDog.aspx?dogid=69833
Adoptable Dog Webpage - http://beaglemaryland.org/brsm_ms/vCurrentDogs.aspx

If you'd like to adopt one of our beagles:
*Go to our Website - href="http://beaglemaryland.org
*Review our  Standards for Adoption - http://beaglemaryland.org/Home.aspx?pg=standardsforadoption.htm
*Fill out an Adopter Profile - 
http://brsmbeagles.org/new_site/documents/BRSM_profile_secure.pdf
 and email it to us (or print it off, fill it in and send it via regular mail, if you prefer)
*A BRSM volunteer will contact you to guide you through the rest of the process!

We hope to hear from you, and so do the beagles!

All AAF cats and dogs are vaccinated, spayed or neutered and microchipped. All cats receive a FelV/FIV combination test while dogs over the age of 8 months are tested for heartworms. All pets are also treated for both intestinal parasites and fleas. The AAF is proud of the medical attention that is given to each and every pet as their health and well-being is of the utmost importance to our organization.

Kittens: $85

animal.description:
IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN JOJO RABBIT, PLEASE GO TO OUR WEBSITE TO READ ABOUT THE PROCESS AND FILL OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION. www.furkidrescue.org 

Jojo Rabbit was a stray in Memphis. He came to us underweight and with heart worm. He’s completed heart worm treatment, is at a great weight and is overall a healthy boy! 

Jojo is a bit anxious, and would do best in a suburban or country environment. Little things scare him on a daily basis- such as a bike going by on our walks. He is a flight risk, and will dart out a door, or would run if something scared him. I guess you can call him a bit of a spaz. However he has some charming qualities as well. He is very affectionate and cuddly, loves to go for rides in the car and gets so excited when you pull his harness out for his walks. He is eager to please. House trained. He loves hiking in the woods! No couch potatoes please. 
Jojo is a messy drinker. He sticks his entire face/muzzle into the bowl, making a huge wet sloppy mess multiple times a day. If this grosses you out- he’s not the dog for you. If you don’t mind keeping a towel by the water bowl for your floor- keep reading. 
A home with a fenced in yard would be ideal. He’s not the type of dog that will do well on a tie out. Jojo loves other dogs. He actually won’t eat his breakfast without his dog friends. He shares his bowls of food. He loves breakfast time. He would love to have a dog companion, but it’s not a must.

animal.description:
Double the cuddles, double the fun! That’s what you’ll get when you adopt me, April, and my best friend and bonded partner, Andy! I’m 7 years old and weigh only 5 pounds, and I’m spayed, fully vetted, microchipped, vaccinated, and taking heartworm preventative. I’ve had a rough start in life, but now I’m looking for my forever home so I can make up for lost time!

My nickname is “Cookie” because I’m black and white like an Oreo, and I’m just as sweet! I love to cover you with kisses and sleep snuggled up tight with you under the covers. Despite my age, I still act like a puppy, racing around the yard, wrestling with my friends, and playing with toys with my foster siblings. My pal Andy likes to sound off at other dogs sometimes, and I chime right in with him for a good bark! Andy makes me feel safe, so I’ll need a home where we’ll both be welcome.

Andy and I used to be kept in a barn and used for breeding. We didn’t get much socialization, so we are a bit nervous around new people, but once we get to know you, we’ll make up for it by being super snuggly. We’re also a bit timid when it comes to leashes, so we’ll need a fenced-in yard, extra secure due to my bad habit of digging under fences. I’m working on that! We’re also working hard on our potty training, but occasionally I get caught up in the fun and forget to wait until I’m outside to go.

Andy and I have been waiting a long time for our forever home because we need to stay together, but we can’t understand why anyone would prefer just one dog when they could have TWO great dogs like us in their lives! Are you ready for twice the snuggles, twice the kisses, and twice the love? We’re ready to bring it!

If you are interested in adopting April and Andy, please DO NOT SEND A MESSAGE TO OUR RESCUE GROUP.  We are too busy placing dogs in great homes to answer messages and inquiries through the listing site.  

PLEASE GO TO THE LINK BELOW TO COMPLETE AN ADOPTION APPLICATION.
 
www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application
 
CRT requires an approved adoption application and a home visit for all adoption applicants.  CRT transports to OH, KY, IL, MI, MN, WI.

Instant Party Kit! Just add me, Andy, and my best friend, April! I’m 5-7 years old, weigh 10 pounds, and am fully vetted, neutered, microchipped, up to date on my vaccinations, and taking heartworm preventative. I’m ready to celebrate my new lease on life with you and my bonded partner, April, who needs to come along with me. We’ll bring the cuddles!

I’m a laidback, low energy kind of guy, happy to snooze in the sun and snuggle with my friends, but I do love chasing squirrels and playing with toys with my foster siblings! I get along great with them and even with my cat stepsister. New people do make me a little nervous, but I am always on my best behavior with the vet and groomer. I am the life of the party when I do my one trick, standing up on my back legs to get a tasty treat!

My friend April and I have spent most of our lives living in a barn as part of a breeding operation. Because of that, we didn’t get much socialization or training. I’ve gotten much better with my potty training, but I confess that at times I still get excited and want to mark my territory. Walking on a leash is a bit scary to me, so I need a fenced in yard so I can run around and do my business, not to mention chasing those squirrels. Do you have other pets already? I don’t mind sharing my space at all--the more the merrier!

April and I will be watching for our invitation to join your family, and we can’t wait to RSVP with a big YES!

They were both ready to pop with pups so we placed them in a foster home. They were out of touch on socializing but allowed us to pet them and care for their puppies. Their pups all found homes now its their turn.

They have been with a trainer Joe at Bed Bath and Biscuit for a few months and they are making great progress and ready for a forever home or a foster home.

They are beautiful girls and will make wonderful family additions. Please consider meeting them and giving them the chance they deserve for a loving home.

The right person(s) who show them patience and love will be rewarded with true companionship.

Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, microchip and rabies and other core vaccinations.

animal.description:
Jax is a spunky, yet snuggly young dog looking for a very special and patient forever family to love and care for him.  Jax is just under two-years old, and he is a little guy weighing in at about seven pounds.  Jax has been working hard at his potty training and manners, and needs a family that is willing to continue working with him on this training.  In his foster home, Jax wears a belly wrap because when he gets excited and busy playing, he has an occasional accident.  He needs a family that is patient, understanding and both able and willing to meet his medical needs...  Jax's front, left leg was broken when he was very young and left untreated so it did not heal properly. His old injury does not impede his mobility, and the leg does not cause him pain. While in foster care with Friends of SCAC Jax was treated with antibiotics for a persistent bacterial infection of his GI tract, which has been resolved. He suffers from occasional bouts of colitis. He is currently eating prescription food for allergies, and taking a daily probiotic; the prescription food and probiotic costs ~$40/$45 a month..  

Jax would probably do best in a home where his human(s) could spend most of their time with him.    

***We will not adopt Jax out as an only dog; he requires canine companionship with one (or at most two) other dogs of a similar size and age (younger, active, and small).***

Jax has lived with both dogs and cats, and has spent time around younger children.  Jax LOVES to play, and he would love to have a canine companion to spend time with; he would do best in a home with dog(s) of a similar size and with a similar activity level.  Jax has also lived with cats, and wants to play with them too; he tends to chase the cats in order to entice them into a play session.  Jax has also spent time playing with younger children who know how to properly respect and interact with dogs.

Jax favorite things include playing (with other dogs and toys!), napping and snuggling, and spending time playing outside with his human and dog friends when the weather is nice.

If you are interested in meeting Jax, please fill out the online adoption application found here (please copy and paste this URL into your browser):  https://forms.gle/ufXh7QCko6EYZga4A

Jasper would not be a good fit for a family who has never had a dog before as he is nervous around new people.

Jasper does go on pack walks and has made some canine friends who he plays well with, he has lived in a home with other dogs and we know for sure he does not like cats. He has also not really had experience around children, and younger kids would probably give him unneeded stress. Jasper is very smart and can take on new tricks and lessons well. He is crate trained. Jasper is hoping to find a FURever home out there somewhere, a family who is willing to take a chance on this sweet boy.

app@aarfhouston.org

You can apply online by clicking on

Application

. Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events.

Thank you for considering a rescue!

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

Raisin adores playing fetch, soft toys and some excellent scratches, Raisin's hair is starting to grow back in too, this peach fuzzy boy had mange and some allergies but he is recovering wonderfully! Sometimes he will get spooked but new things, like trash bags, moving a chair and of course the vacuum. He recovers well but will need a hug after the trauma. Raisin currently bunks with three chihuahuas, he adores them but they can be overwhelmed by him which he does his very best to respect. Raisin should have an owner experienced with bigger high energy dogs, due to his energetic enthusiasm he should go to a home with older children 10+

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi Everybody! My name is Peneli and I'm a smaller sized rottweiler but I'm pretty muscular!! I came from a shelter in Boise, ID where I didn't have a very good life and I was picked up by Animal Control there and taken to the shelter. It was pretty scary and I was really apprehensive about all the people around me. I just bonded with a very few people and would growl at the others so it was just me and my few peeps I made friends with. My new friends worked with me and tried to help me understand that not all people are bad. I've gotten better about being around new people and have figured out that most of you humans have awesome treats in your pockets. My foster mom calls me a little stinker and says I remind her of "Daisy" another foster she had. Daisy and her new Dad must be really cool because mom talks about them a lot. I hope when I grow up I can be just like Daisy - she rides in helicopters, and jet boats, sniffs out bombs and does all kinds of cool doggy stuff! Anyway, my foster mom thinks I would make a great law enforcement dog - I have a good prey drive and am always sniffing and getting into everything. I'm not destructive, I'm just well .. I guess you could say I'm nosey! Mom says because I wasn't exposed to lots of dogs when I was little I'm now a little reactive to other dogs, especially when I'm out walking. And, because of that darn prey drive, I don't like cats and other small animals. I'm not real comfortable with small children because I know they are just waiting to steal my treats and prized toys! I would like to have a brother that likes me but he can't try and take all my toys or I won't like him. Mom says I'm a really active little stinker so I definitely need a good fenced yard and a human that will see that I get to have lots of exercise and continue to help me understand what is right and wrong. What I tell my foster mom I want is a job to do, just like Daisy has. I think I would be really good at it but know I have a lot to learn. Because I'm not good about sharing food, toys and all my prized possessions Mom thinks I would thrive in a home with maybe just a couple or a single person who works from home and could spend lots of time with me. Most of all, Mom wants me to go with a very experienced rottweiler owner who knows my breed characteristics and can understand the type of training I need to live a full and happy life. I know there is a special person out there for me that fits everything Mom wants for me, we just need to fine them and see how we do together!!

Good with small dogs?: Yes

9/4/20: Hey, Niko here. I've just about finished my resting time after my last set of heart worm shots. Its been a long journey since I've been rescued by CBR, I'll be ready soon for a fur-ever home. My foster dad is very proud of me because I learned how to drool and have a gassy butt like other boxers do. I love to snuggle, be a silly boy with my sisters and still let foster dad know when someone walks by the house. I'm not sure about thunderstorms and fireworks, I will snuggle close and tight next to you till its over. You will have to tell me its going to be ok. I've not been by myself (except 2 stays at the vet) since being rescued. I always had my sisters around or mom and dad. Dad has left me out of my kennel for several hours at a time with 1 or 2 of my sisters and I do great. You will have to help me get better with boy dogs I still get little too excited. I can do it, with your help. I don't know what a cat is so I don't know how I will do. I sure will miss my foster mom and dad, they have been great to me.

____________________________________________________________________________

8/17/20: Hey everyone it's Niko. I've had to settle down since getting my first HW shot but I still have another 30 days of rest after my last shots later this month. Im not looking forward to the shots they make me sick to my stomach and I don't feel well for a couple days after. One good thing is I've learned to cuddle and I love it. When I was sick from my shots my foster dad snuggled with me and told me the stories from his other Boxers and he would rub my belly till I fell asleep, snoring and all. I went to work with foster dad till I started feeling better. I love laying on the floor while my foster dad watches youtube and rubs my belly, sometimes he is on the couch but most of the time he is on the floor next to me. Im not a big fan of toys but I do love frozen beef bones and rawhides till they get too small for me. My sister Izzy showed me how to play with a kong that is filled with treats. It took me awhile to figure out that my kong had treats in it, I would just eat my sisters treats from her kong while she played with it. I love blueberries, dried pineapple but most of all I LOVE, LOVE, LOVE cheese puffs. Foster dad has been using these treats to help me learn stay and come and sometimes he just tells me how great I am and kisses my head for being an A-MAZE-ING boy. I follow him around all over the house, he has been teaching me to stay while he leaves the room till he gets back. He says it will help me not to follow around the house and that he will come back. My buddy Mason comes to see me a lot and we watch wrestling on TV. One day he brought his brother Luke over. Luke and I became the WDW (world diaper wrestling) undisputed intercontinental tag team cage match champions of the world. We beat the former champs (Woody, Buzz Light year and Mason) in a handicap one fall no time limit match. That was a lot of fun. Check on me soon, I'll be ready soon after my last HW treatment. NIKO, out.

6/23/20: Hey, it's Niko checking in on Father's Day. My foster dad is the best dad EVER!! When I thought it could not get any better, just sayin'. I met a couple new boys since I last wrote, Alston (12) and Luke (3). Even though Alston is not a dog person (I don't know why) he helped me learn by letting me sit in the same room with him and not pet or rub me. Foster dad said not all people like dogs and its ok, I need to practice my manners anyway. Luke was a hand full with all his squealing and running around, I did my best to keep up with him. I had to help save my foster dad when he rides this thing that sounds like a dinosaur. He brings it out in the yard to feed it, it chews up the grass. It must be very powerful cause it goes around in circles with FD on top of it. I run to help him by nipping on its black feet its ferocious and growls back at me while it eats, but I'm not afraid of it. FD tells me that he is ok. He let me sniff it when he put it back in its cage FD calls it a shed. Its belly must have been full cause it made no more dinosaur noise. We have another loud animal I've never seen before- this one is kept in the house in a smaller room, Its not as loud as the shed dinosaur. FD fights with this one everyday, they start on the kitchen and work their way into the living room. It lunges forward and FD pulls it back it lunges forward and he pulls it back, this goes on for 20 minutes. I go into hero mode and try to nip at its one eye in the middle of its head. It must not see to well cause this thing has a bright light for a eye. FD fights that thing all by himself, FD always wins. Then he puts it back in its cage he calls it a closet. My foster sisters are doing well, thanks for asking. Since going to daycare I get to play with all 3 in the backyard. They get in a kiddy pool when they get hot, I'm not too sure about doing that just yet. I'm eating with all of my sisters at the same elevated food bowl station. FD is teaching us all to wait till he places the food down, sometimes I just can't wait. Daycare is a BLAST, I can't believe we just get to play all day. I have to work on playing well with other boy dogs, sometimes I get too excited. I just finished some medicine for my heart worms, soon I'll have to go get some shots. 2 shots will be back to back with no break. I'll have to keep calm for a couple weeks after the first one. Wish me luck, FD says we will be working on my listening, staying, down and come here commands during that time. He says we are going on some field trips before the shots, he is going to take me in some stores around town. Check me out soon, have a great doggy fathers day. Maybe this time next year I'll have a mom and dad to celebrate with. NIKO OUT!

6/1/20: Hey!! Its Niko, BUSY, BUSY, BUSY! It sure is nice to get out and do things, I didn't know how great life was as a D-O-G! I have had a lot of new experiences since last time. Foster dad has taken me to work on the Army base funny place though, they all wear the same clothes and have the same haircuts thats weird. They all love to rub me and tell me how smart I am. They let me watch their classes while my foster dad talks and teaches them how to fix boo boos and ouchies. The car rides are awesome, I love to look out the window and see things pass by, never a dull moment. I get to play with my foster sisters in the house, they are a BLAST to play with. Lucy and Izzy are bigger and younger than me while Bella is a older and smaller than me. Life has been so great with them in it, thats for sure!! My foster dad puts me on a leash and he lets me take him for walks, then I take him home and he rubs me telling me I did great! I get to sleep at night with everybody and I have no accidents,oh yea! Im learning how to sleep in my own comfy bed, 3 words A-MAZE-ING I sleep like a baby. I like when they put me and my foster sisters in our kennels during the day, I get to catch up on naps till foster dad or mom comes home. The Doctors who take care of me are great Im not afraid of them at all, I thought I would be. They look at me with bright lights and listen to me breath and I think its just fun. Ive got to play with some kids and make new friends too, Mason who is 10 loves to play with me. Naomi who is 16 isn't afraid of me AT ALL, imagine that. I get to take her for walks too, WHAT! Foster dad says Im gonna meet some more kids soon. Im learning to share water and food with my sisters, thats one thing I never had to do by myself is share, so its baby steps for me. I had my neuter today and feel little lost if you know what I mean. Foster dad says I'll be just fine as he kisses my head and scratches my belly. I'll get to go to daycare and play with a bunch of dogs soon, ALL DAY! Im excited. Well you can see I've been busier than a one legged cat in a litter box. Im learning, thats for sure. Anyway, just checking in. Check up on me soon, I'll have more great adventures and pictures too.

5/24/20: Hi everybody!! My name is Niko. The kindness of one special person got me out of a bad place and in the loving care of CBR. Her children said you can't save every dog and she told them I can save this one. To that special person, THANK YOU I won't let you down. My new start in life is because of YOU!! My nub has not stopped wagging since I left that place. I am brand new at being a family member and I'm trying my best to see and try new things every day. I want to run and play with all 3 of my foster sisters but I get so excited I can only play with one at a time while on a leash. Foster dad says I'll get better after I'm... neutered? Anyway, I'll be ready for my FUR-ever family soon. I have scars on my face and neck that tells my past but not my future. Watch for my updates to see what new things and experiences I learn!!

_____________

Dog's Approximate Age: 5-6 years old

Gender: Male

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's weight: 52 pounds

Good with big dogs?: No

8/4/20: Hey guys, it's Tonks, back with an update! Sorry for the delay, my new foster dad keeps saying the world is a crazy place these days. All I know is life is good as long as I get treats and a peanut butter filled Kong.

Anyway, I'm finally settled in with my new foster dad. The first week was a little scary because there were so many new smells and places. But I checked everything out and I really like my new home! Theres a big yard to run in when I get the zoomies and a couple sprinklers I can jump through when it's really hot outside. And I LOVE all the attention I'm getting being the only dog in the house.

When my foster dad leaves during the day I get to take a nap in my crate with my Kong. He says I've learned to be a really good boy when he goes to work. Among other things, there's just so much to learn. While I may be a little slow, I'm really good at listening and following directions once I've learned something. Especially if there are treats involved!

That's it for now. I'll continue to work on my good behavior and try to not let my curiosity get me in trouble. I can't wait to meet more Hoomans because they all love me so please come visit! Stay tuned for more progress updates in the near future and stay safe.

6/8/20: Hello everyone! My name is TonksI'm a stocky fella that loves being with my people. When I jump on the dog bed my favorite thing to do is roll around and rub myself on everything. I love napping, but I also love finding new things- I'm curious! When I came from the shelter, they thought I was around 3 years old, but the folks at CBR think I'm more of a middle aged guy. I like chasing the tennis ball but they say that's not great for my arthritis- I'm on some great supplements that are helping that some, but I'm not a guy that will need to be your running buddy. They think I spent a lot of my life before CBR by myself, so I'm looking for a home without any other pets- I like to have the attention of humans all to myself! I also sometimes like to give cats a run for their money (can you blame me?), so I need folks who can keep me calm on the leash or pick me up if I try to bolt for the kitties (I'm a smaller guy, so that's not too hard to do). The folks I'm with are working on teaching me manners and basic commands- they say I'm sort of a slow learner- they aren't sure if maybe in my past life I got a little injured in my head. Once I learn something though, I'm golden! I'm just looking for people who will be patient with me. I'm pretty good in the crate and housetrained, and apparently when I get excited I make little snorting piggy noises which the humans say is really cute.

Tonks is looking for a forever home with a family that will continue his training and will be patient, firm, and consistent with him to help him learn his manners. We know his family is out there!

_____________________________________________________________________________

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Rosie

Dog's Approximate Age: 4 Years

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 64

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Yes

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?:

Crate trained?: Working on it

House trained?: Working on it

Heartworms?: No

7/19/20: Rosie here. I'll bet you thought I was lost. Well I was kind of hiding because I had eye surgery and had to wear a very annoying necklace that covered my face. I just refused to be seen in public like that but I'm great now and ready to Rock & Roll!

Since I was kinda just learning before my surgery I forgot how to play but my FB is trying to remind me and I'm remembering how much fun that was. My FM says she's so proud of me because I remembered it's ok to go out on a leash, ride in the car, and sit or down for treats. I love being smart so FM only has to say "outside" once and I go right to the door. I wait patiently for my meals and I go out right after I finish so I don't have any accidents in the house. I also know the word "out" means I can't go in the kitchen when FM is cooking or in the toy room when the kiddies are eating. I love kids too. When kids visit my FM I like to stay in the playroom. My favorite thing is lying around with my FB. He lets me steal his bones and his crate too. I love having a sibling. I nap in my own crate during the day and sleep in it at night if FM is too wiggly in the bed. Oh, and I just love when someone says my name. I get so wiggly that my tail goes so fast it almost disappears. I'm still shy but when people don't rush up to me I like to smell their back and then I make friends with them. I even let them pet me and I wag my tail. I'm still afraid of sudden noises but I'm so much better. I know Airplanes, leaves and compressors are not going to harm me. Not so sure about traffic and skateboards. I don't mind the broom or sweeper anymore but I like to go in the crate if that big vacuum comes out. FM still tells me I'm one of the smartest dogs she's ever met. When FM goes out I usually go get one of her shoes and maybe a slipper or two but it's just to keep me company. I don't chew on it. I LOVE chewing on Kongs with canned food or veggies though. I chew and bury, then chew and bury some more. I like burying my favorite things in my crate. I haven't worked on anything new this week because I'm just relaxing after having that awful head gear but I remembered all my manners I learned before my eye surgery. I know you have the perfect place for me. At least 1 FM and 1 sibling. More is fine as FM has lots of visitors but I am most comfortable when it's pretty quiet. I really need a crate for when I need to build courage but other than that I'm pretty easy going. I'm not fussy about food but my tummy needs changes to be slow.

Well, I just wanted you to know I'm all healed up and hope you weren't too worried. The scavenger hunt we went on was so fun and now it's your turn to come find me. Ready, set, go!

5/23/20: I know it's taking a while for you to find me, what with the way everything's upside down now, but I'm taking advantage and practicing to be the best friend I can be for you. In just the last few weeks I've learned how to walk on the leash and the last few days I found out there's some pretty good smells out there too! FM is proud that I walk so nicely on the leash; I don't pull at all unless you count the times I freeze when something scares me. At first it was all real scary but now I'm interested in scouting out some more of those smells, I'm still working on ignoring the noises. I love my FB and we play hard when we first wake up and right before supper. He's teaching me how to squeak toys and we play tug of war. FM says I'm like a cuddly lap dog because when she sits down I want to be right next to her. While I'm waiting for you I'm also practicing manners and FM says I'm a really smart girl. She told me my furever family will be so happy they found me because I'm the best girl, so funny and so smart, yup, that's what she says.

5/9/20: Rosie here, checking in. The last couple weeks have been very exciting for me. FM is so proud of me because I didn't have any accidents in the house. She did tell me it would be nice if I could alert her when I have to go out so she didn't have to open the door to check and I just looked at her and said, "I am" you just don't know my language yet! I love playing with my FB, I have a den I can go sleep in where it is safe and cozy. Sometimes I just sleep on my FB's beds during the day but at night when FM says, "night night time" I run right in my crate. This week FM said I had a major accomplishment because I walked a little bit in the neighborhood. Truthfully I didn't like it very much but FM says if we keep practicing I will learn to love it just as much as my FB. I also am curious about school time. My FB and his GSD look at FM and position when she says a word. FM says it won't be long before I have to perform too or I won't get free treats because she says I'm so very smart. This week I learned that "Leave it" means I have to stop doing what I'm doing. It's hard because those treats FM has on her table look so tempting but I love to see my FM happy and tell me what a good girl I am so I just walk away. She said I am going to be an A+ for someone who wants a comfy pal to cuddle with, silly girl to laugh at and best friend for their other pet. I can't wait to meet you.

4/26/20: Hi all, Rosie here again. I just wanted to let you know how well I'm doing. I love my FB and we play boxing every day, especially when we wake up. FM laughs at us and says we look like kangaroos, I don't know what a kangaroo is but I know I love wrestling with my FB. Well I finally learned that the back door isn't as scary as I first thought and now I even go out the door all by myself when FM says, "Rosie, outside?" It's a little scary if the wind blows but my spot outside is nice and small so I feel safe as long as I can see the open door. FM gets so excited when squat and I get extra wet food. I tried fooling her a few times by just sitting down but it didn't work. FM said, "Rosie you are such a smart girl but no treat for that." I get treats for letting FM put a leash on my collar too as long as she takes it right off I don't try to run in my crate when I see it. FM said just keep practicing and it'll be ok just like the back door. My FB had a play date so I met his German Shephard friend when her Mom needed a sitter for an hour. We made friends right away and we played outside on the patio. I even forgot I was afraid when a truck went by. FM said when that Covid-19 goes away all the grandkids will come play with me too. I'm so excited for that. I like to watch some animals on T.V and even on FM's phone. I especially like to watch myself play. When the wind broke the T.V. a man came to the house and I didn't run and hide, I just watched him. A new man had to come the next day so I thought I'd just follow him around and lie by his feet when he was sitting on the floor to make sure he fixed it right this time. FM was so happy for me. She said, "Rosie, you sure are practicing so well it won't be long before your furever family finds you.

4/13/20: That nasty covid thing interrupted my settling in so I had to go to another foster home with a new FM and a new FB. To tell you the truth the first few days were kinda rough, but I am getting used to the new environment. I'm still resting a lot so I can put on some weight but I heard FM on the phone telling the vet that my stomach issues are resolved. I think that's good because I feel so much better. I'm still shy and not sure it's safe outside my crate but my FB keeps encouraging me to come out and sniff around. I'm beginning to follow him a little more and I wag my tail really hard when FM says good morning. I'm trying hard to learn that the back door is a safe place and I watch my FB run in and out trying to get me to follow him. Maybe tomorrow? FM keeps telling me I'm practicing to go to a forever home. I wag my tail and imagine a home with at least one sibling and even a kid or two, the more the merrier right? Now that my tummy issues are gone and they say I'm fixed up so I won't have puppies I'll just keep practicing until you find me.

2/28/20: Rosie here! I'm still very timid. Foster mom and dad still have to pick me up to take me outside. I lived a really rough life before and I'm still learning to trust. I stay in one room and don't like to come out, but when my foster family comes to me, I get really excited and wiggle my whole body now!!! I am learning to play a bit. My foster fur sister and I have gotten into a couple tiffs over high value items like special toys and chew bones (mom now doesn't let us have those unless the other is not around - insert sad face). She doesn't think it was me causing the problem, my foster fur sister is a bit spoiled and doesn't like to share much.

I need a family who will take time to show me I'm loved. I am not going to immediately be a big cuddle bug, but I think in

12/17/20: Charlotte is a super sweet girl. She loves all people and hasn't meet a stranger yet. Her favorite things are going for walks, car rides and snuggling on the sofa. She is completely house trained and has never had an accident. We are working on her getting used to the crate. She is also working on her leash reactivity towards other dogs while on walks. She is able to be redirected with guidance. She does great in car rides and loves to go to with the family to the beach and trails.

Charlotte would do best to have a 6' privacy fenced yard so she has a safe place to play- she has come a very long way but is still quite reactive on a leash when she sees other dogs. She also has some separation anxiety when left alone, so she would love a forever home where there are people home with her a lot of the time.

9/16/20: Charlotte loves cuddling, riding in the car and walks. She is a sweet girl with lots of love to give, wants to be where the action is. Scared of thunder, be prepared to have her in bed with you when there is a storm brewing.

7/8/20: Loves people, attention and snuggles. We love her already and we have had her only one day- more updates to come

5/30/20: Charlotte is the kindest most loving 5 year old. My kids 7 and 1 and 1/2 yrs old love on her and she just eats it up. She loves to walk great on the leash, and loves human company. She's not great with other dogs yet but manages a few barks and moves on with you. Charlotte is her new name and she's learning it slowly!

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Delilah

Dog's Approximate Age: 2 years

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Pocket Boxer (under 50lbs as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 47 pounds

Good with small dogs?: No

Good with big dogs?: No

Good with cats?: No

Good with kids?: Yes, older only (12 and over due to being too rambunctious)

Any medical issues?: Heartworm Positive - being treated with slow kill method

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: Yes

10/26/20:
Delilah has come so far since this summer and we're very proud of her progress! We realized quickly she would act out from anxiety which amped her up and she didn't have the skills or confidence to calm and soothe herself. We also found that she had underlying allergies that were making her irritable and itchy. Zyrtec has been magic for her and while she no longer gets hives, we have noticed she'll chew her paws so consider wiping them down as needed. With some medicine, firm rules, and a whole lot of patience Delilah has come a very long way in just a few weeks. She is showing us a very sweet loving and playful personality. As a super chewer, antlers, Kongs and tough toys have really helped her relax. She LOVES having her own blankets to making nests in, and they are the one item we allow her to chew on as needed for comfort. By doing so we found her need to chew our soft furnishings drastically decrease. Having a crate will always be important for Delilah; it's her safe space and she sleeps there overnight. With time, we've been able to leave her out during the workday downstairs without worry; she just sits on the couch or on her bed. On the weekends we venture to Umstead or the Art Park for long walks. She does very well in the car when in the backseat; she will lean against the chair or curl up. It's important to know that in the trunk or way back she will get car sick. Delilah is learning how to tell us her needs and while she's getting better everyday there are times she gets "stuck" or when she steals shoes for attention if we ignore her too long. She also shows some separation anxiety and isn't quite sure what to do if she's super tired but everyone else is busy doing interesting things. Delilah's interest in other dogs is complicated. While she wags her tail and wines at other dogs passing by, she has had consistently negative introductions with them. She walks beautifully and other than sometimes "sinking" her body, she doesn't bark or lunge at other dogs so long as you're passing by. We have many dogs in our neighborhood and she couldn't care less when they bark through their windows or doors. But it is important Delilah is your only pet. She really needs a family who is willing to be patient, firm and flexible in the beginning. It's worth it to get to the big doe eyed sweet girl we've come to know.

_____________________________________________________

7/28/20: Hey! It's me, Delilah! I'm just loving these sunny summer days! Even if it's 90 degrees, I want to be outside laying in the sun or watching people walking by. My humans even put sunscreen on my nose! My favorite is when my people are outside with me. I'm right by their side at all times because I don't want to miss out if they stumble upon some treats. While they're working in the garden, I stand nearby and guard em. I also like when they're grilling because anything that drips on the ground is mine!

We also go for walks which help me get my energy out, but I get tired quickly. After 20 minutes, I can't keep my tongue in my mouth. I don't want to brag but I'm really good at walking on a leash. I stay right next to my human and don't pull. I used to get excited when I saw rabbits and charge after them but I don't do that anymore. I'd love to catch one someday but I know that our walks are not the time to do that.

I'm happy with any people who love being outside, just like I do! It's supposed to rain later so I'm heading outside to work on my tan!

6/12/20: Hey friends! This is Delilah a.k.a Deedee a.k.a Lil' D and I wanted to give everyone an update on all the fun stuff that's been happening in my life! I'm starting to learn the rules of the house and I'm getting better at following them. These humans have a magic mat and every time I lay on it, I get a treat! I'm talking good stuff like hot dogs, apples and peanut butter. I'm even picking up some new tricks too. I've mastered "shake" and "twirl," but I'm still getting the hang of "fetch" and "drop." If I come home with you, what tricks are you gonna teach me?

Delilah shows a lot of friendly interest in our neighbor's dog (Husky), and may do well with a dog who is OK with a pushy, energetic sibling. She would just need opportunities to calm back down between playtimes, as once she gets overexcited, it's hard to bring her back down.

5/4/20: Little Delilah here, reporting for doodie! 3 weeks have flown by at my new foster home! I'm the sweetest girl looking for a family that will be consistent in rules, give me lots of outdoor time, and has a sunny spot where I can nap. Inside, outside, doesn't matterif I can find a spot of sun, I'm going to nap there! I'm VERY good on a leash, especially if I know who's boss. I get a little over excited at times (who doesn't?!) but after some time to settle down in my kennel, I'm just fine. Other dogs and young kids might find me a bit much - I just want to go go go and don't understand when it's time to stop. I love toys, and dinner time is my favorite time of day. I'm perfectly happy to hand out and sleep in my kennel, I'm perfectly potty trained, I like to sleep in and am not picky about a morning routine; it's just my evenings that need to be a little more structured. Not to brag, but I think I'm pretty smart. I'm a quick learner! In just the three short weeks here, I've learned some fun new tricks, like how to wait patiently for my dinner, "tough", and "down".

2/25/20: Very energetic happy girl. She loves walking, running and exploring. Absolutely loves her stuffed animals and loves to play. Great with people and seems very fond of men.

12/25/19: Delilah is a 2 year old high energy dog who is looking for a home where she can play a lot in a fenced backyard or go on nice long walks. She would also make a good running buddy! Because she has a lot of energy, we think she would be best in a home with kids 12 and over. She is selective about dogs, so she would like to be the "queen bee" of your house. She is crate and house trained, rarely barks, and knows basic commands. She's wondering... could you be her forever family?

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

_____________________________________________________________________________

animal.description:
Bilbo is a little mix dog that came to our rescue with two of his siblings.  Our best guess is he is some form of beagle/hound/pointer mix, but we're not certain.  They were left as strays with several other dogs in central Arkansas, and as such have been very shy and are slowly learning how fun living in a home can be.  

Bilbo is a sweet guy who is around 25lbs.  He is probably around a year old, but that was just a guess.  He has been fully vetted and is microchipped.  He has been introduced to dogs and cats.  He has not met any children yet, but we feel he would do ok around children 5 and up (because he is still building his confidence around people).  

Bilbo is available to a very special home ready to give him all the time he needs to acclimate.  He needs a home with secure fencing and friendly dogs.  He is very frightened by people and has taken months to warm slightly to his foster home.  He is not a take everywhere love everyone kind of dog.  He will not be a social butterfly pal around dog.  He was never socialized or worked with in his early life and that greatly affects how he reacts and the fear he feels now.

His adoption fee is $150.  He is fostered in Rogers, AR.  You can find our application at www.makrescue.org  Our website works best from a computer rather than phone or tablet.

animal.description: Renegade came to us in 2015 as a 4-6 month old pup. She was on the urgent list at the Kansas City shelter: "***Rescue Only - Pup was brought to the shelter by animal control. It appears that she has had no previous human socialization and is very defensive when staff attempts to interact with her." Most ferals you work with will shut down, and curl up, and not really think about biting the thing scaring them. Renegade was different (hence her name). She will defend herself and will try to scare strangers away before they ever get near her. She eventually bonded to us and we could handle her and pet her and she'd curl up in a ball and allow the touching without defending herself. She'd wag her tail for us, and get excited to see us but then if you reached for her she'd run to her safe spot (an open wire crate) and curl up. With time, patience, and consistency she will now just cower down for petting, not run away. She WANTS the petting. She's so happy with us, dances around wagging her tail, gives us little kisses, loves treats, but when you reach for her she'll cower down and wait for the petting. The feral dog in her. With strangers, she acts like she's a guard dog and tries to scare them away...but with treats, time, and love she'll warm up to you. Renegade loves it here, she's safe here, but if a skilled, special person was interested in her...she is available for adoption. In the wrong home Renegade would bite someone. So we will be thorough in our screening of potential homes. Because of her trust/fear issues the potential adopter would need to come to our property to meet her 2-3 times a week for 3-6 weeks in a row to build a bond with her. Socially Imperfect...but still worth it. Renegade is a happy dog, who loves life, loves to play with other dogs, and deserves to live. She's a perfect example of why we do what we do. Just because she's not a 'normal' dog doesn't mean she doesn't deserve to live. Check out this video of her playing: https://www.facebook.com/AutumnAcres/posts/3285192524848339 Renegade doesn't have a sponsor. Want to help provide toys, treats, and routine medical care for her? Become her sponsor! $50 a month is all we need to help provide for her. At Autumn Acres Animal Rescue we believe each individual animal matters. We take in special cases some of which will stay with us as a sanctuary dog.If the animal is listed as a Socially Imperfect Dog this means they have special needs and special requirements for potential adopters.If the animal is listed as a Socially Imperfect RESIDENT this animal is NOT available for adoption and is one of our sanctuary residents. We list them on our sites because they still matter and they still need donations to help with their long term care.Check out our website for more information: http://www.autumnacres.org

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Meet Abby
Age: 2 years

Welcome Abby!  Abby was trapped by a local rescue and transferred to SPR due to our dedication to rehoming Belgian  Malinois dogs.  Abby did well in her foster home. Abby is very shy, but will warm up to you and other dogs when you take things slowly with her. We are still getting to know her, but she seeks attention and wants to be loved.  With all that, she is still a Malinois, so we always recommend having experience with the breed and a plan for mental and physical stimulation.  She will not be a good dog to have in an apartment or a condo.  She is not a dog for protection work either.  We are looking for an experienced handler willing to take it slow and let her learn to trust and thrive in a loving stimulating environment.  


*****Belgian Malinois Adoption requirements*****

The dog you have selected is a Belgian Malinois.  This is a breed that has very specific needs for an adoptive home.  Because of their need for a high level of exercise, both mentally and physically and their need for ongoing training, only applicants with demonstrated owner/handler experience with this breed will be considered.  The vast majority of them are not best suited as family pets, but in homes with experienced handlers knowledgeable of their needs and breed characteristics.  We will not place in homes with small children or small dogs/cats.  

If you can give Abby  an indoor forever home, please fill out our online application on our website at http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.com/adoption-form/  

 We will only schedule meet and greets with an approved application. We are an all-volunteer organziation.  It may take a couple of days to process an application and complete reference checks.

Thank you for your interest in saving a life!
