animal.description: MIMI is a 7 yr old Shar Pei who came to us after her owner died. She was found in the house by a concerned person who went looking for her owner. Her owner had passed away and Mimi had been in a crate for approximately three days. She is understandably missing her person. It seems like it was just the two of them. Mimi is slow to warm up to new people but when she does, she is a complete love and even a playful little clown! Mimi prefers her home where she is the only pet so she can soak up all the love! She loves to go on walks and we are working on her leash skills. Mimi would also love a large fenced yard to explore. She lived in the city and probably didn’t get too much time to sniff about and smell the roses. Mimi is housebroken and crate trained. We are looking for an adult only home thats not too far away so that we can do several extended meet and greets. Shar-Pei experience is a plus or experience with a similar type of dog. Shar-Peis are known for their skin problems and Mimi‘s seems to be at bay currently. Fleas and bad nutrition probably contributed to her hind end hair loss. She has since been treated for fleas, finished a round of antibiotics and is on fish oil for skin support. Mimi has been vaccinated, is presumed to have been spayed and will have a more thorough work up as soon as the vets open up from Covid and we are able to go in with her. Please fill out an application at www.companimals.org if you are the family she is looking for! Adoption $250

animal.description: ARMANI is a stunning 9 yr old American Pit Bull Terrier! If he was a person, he would be a body builder! Armani was purchased as a puppy by a young kid and later dumped on the grandmother who was never able to socialize him. At the age of 7, he was returned to the breeder who feared him, kept him in an outdoor kennel and threw his food over the fence to feed him. Armani spent a year in these conditions while a kind hearted woman slowly got to know him through the fence. Slowly they formed a bond and she was allowed into his heart and eventually into his kennel. We eventually had a spot open up and were able to welcome him into our kennel which at least has heat and AC and backs up to a park so we could work on his socialization and leash manners. With his Arnold Schwarzenegger stature, blind eye (from an injury as a puppy) and general aloofness, Armani can be an imposing figure but if you are allowed into his circle of trust he is the proverbial gentle giant and takes treats oh so softly! Armani prefers to be the only pet in the household as he was never properly socialized with other animals. Armani is available for adoption to that special person who is close enough to have several meet and greets and has had experience with a similar type of dog. Armani is neutered, up to date on vaccines and on heartworm/flea/tick prevention. Apply at www.companimals.org or if you prefer to love Armani from afar, donations for his care can be made through the PayPal link on our website.

animal.description:
Zaiden is a red merle male who is about 4 years old. He has a full tail and weighs about 46 pounds. Zaiden is a very sweet dog who loves his people. He can be shy at first and takes a few minutes to warm up to new people. Zaiden is playful and goofy with his people.

Zaiden is not cat safe but gets along well with most dogs. He is a highly velcro dog, preferring to go wherever you go. He crates well and is fine being left alone while his people are away but will want to follow them around when they are home. Zaiden is crate trained and is progressing with his house training. He is a medium energy dog but still loves to play fetch and chase toys in the yard. Zaiden does ok on leash but he does get nervous in new places at times.

Zaiden was found on a tether in his yard when his humans moved away. He seems to have been an outdoor dog in his previous life. Zaiden has taken some time on his house training skills. He has a high prey drive and should not be around small animals. Zaiden prefers to be fed in his own space, because he was an outdoor dog without reliable food and water he gets worried about other dogs taking these things away from him. Overall Zaiden is a sweet dog looking for a home that can help him continue to grow as a loved pet.

Zaiden is fostered in Wichita, KS

Applications for adoption can be submitted at www.ns4ar.org

animal.description:
Mr. Willie is a male 3 year old, red merle male aussie. He is a little shy at first but he has a big personality once he gets to know you. He weighs around 55 pounds and has a full tail! Mr. Willie loves to curl up with his person. He is very goofy and sweet natured.

Mr. Willie has not been introduced to cats yet. He gets along with dogs of similar size but is uncomfortable with smaller dogs. Mr. Willie is very Velcro and likes to be with you. He is crate and house trained. Mr. Willie would prefer a home without children. 

Mr. Willie tries to play with toys but he doesn't seem to understand how. He walks well on leash but does prefer to be touching you. Mr. Willie likes to place chase with his foster human and they have their own unique way to play games together. 

Mr. Willie is vision impaired and hearing impaired. He does appear to have a little of both but it is limited. This doesn't stop Mr. Willie from being a loving boy with his human and a playful pup with other dogs in his foster home, even if he sometimes play bows in the wrong direction. A fence is required to adopt Mr. Willie.

Mr. Willie is fostered in Wichita, KS.

To apply to adopt visit www.ns4ar.org

animal.description:
Requirements:
- Patience galore
- Fenced yard preferred
- Someone home most of the day
- One other dog
 
Delilah was part of the hoarding dogs you keep hearing Releash talk about. I won’t go into the details you’re probably familiar with them by now.
 
My foster momma tells me she can see my sweet soul through my eyes. Sometimes I catch her just looking right into them smiling and looking...they tell a story for sure. They are the kindest eyes you’ll ever see. I'm very gentle and sweet but I’m also very timid and shy. It took me some time to like the other dogs here at my foster home. They got dogs of all sizes, just like at my old place. At first I barked at them and stayed to myself but now they are my friends!
 
Did you notice my unique ears?! I love getting ear rubs A LOT! I will thank you with the sweetest licks. I’m looking for a home with daily ears rubs. I need someone patient and kind, who will give me lots of space to warm up to you. I’ll let you know I’m happy by wagging my tail but that will have to be enough at least for a little while. I’d like someone who’s home most of the time. I don’t like it when my humans are gone. When I see they are back I whine and bark to let them know I’m happy to see them but no touchy please. I don’t want you to think you can’t rub my belly and give TLC just sometimes I say no by getting up and finding another place to lay. Please don’t be offended.
 
Loud noises can scare me so smaller children might not be for me. I enjoy treats, toys and playing with my doggie friends. I also love just lounging on the couch. I’m completely potty trained and sleep through the night. I like my own bed but I do like to sleep in the same room with my peoples. If you want to be my peoples please apply for me today.








Thank you for your interest in one of our furry kids! Adopting from Releash Atlanta means you will adopt a dog that has been fully vaccinated, spayed/neutered and microchipped! Our adoption fee is $350

**We only adopt to families in/around Atlanta, Ga (about a 1-2 hour perimeter)**

We do not monitor our Petfinder email address so if you are interested in any of our dogs, please visit releashatlanta.com to either view more of their profile or to apply! If you have questions, please email adopt@releashatlanta.com 

Take a moment and like our Facebook Page for updates on our dogs and the first look at dogs coming into the program! www.facebook.com/releashatlanta

Thank you!!

animal.description:
Emma turned one year old on June 6, 2020.  She cannot get enough of being with her people!  We are told she is crate trained.  She did previously live with other dogs, however, she started to demand that she be the only one to get attention from her human mom by being aggressive with the other two dogs.  She has been around children and did well - exuberant children she does shy away from.

Emma knows her basic commands.  She is HIGH energy and needs to burn it off daily.  She also needs help in knowing that jumping up on people is not allowable.  We are looking for an active, strong leader, loving, experienced dog owner who can help round her out - she really does want to please.  I do believe she could live with other dogs with the right training and the right adopter.  Draining her energy daily is key.  She is just a lover!

Emma is negative for heart worm, tick borne illnesses and parasites.  She is also microchipped.  She weighs 50 pounds and is approximately 18-20 inches tall at the shoulder.

animal.description:
Requirements:
At least one other playful confident dog
Fenced backyard
No kids under 14
 
Hi everyone...Skye here. I’m ready to find my forever home. My foster mom thinks I’m the sweetest, gentlest girl ever! I like playing with others dogs a lot but humans are a different story. I haven’t had a great life so far...living outside, scrapping for food, no humans to love me or pet me. But Releash Atlanta saved me from that.
 
My foster home is a whole new experience for me. I have regular yummy meals but I’m so timid I need my own space when I eat. I’m working on leash walking but it’s not my favorite so I’ll need a fenced yard. I would love a playmate or two...or three...haha. I’m housetrained based on routine.
 
If you’re looking for a cute little companion to add to your family, apply for me today!









Thank you for your interest in one of our furry kids! Adopting from Releash Atlanta means you will adopt a dog that has been fully vaccinated, spayed/neutered and microchipped! Our adoption fee is $350.

We do not monitor our Petfinder email address so if you are interested in any of our dogs, please visit releashatlanta.com to either view more of their profile or to apply! If you have questions, please email adopt@releashatlanta.com 

Take a moment and like our Facebook Page for updates on our dogs and the first look at dogs coming into the program! www.facebook.com/releashatlanta

Thank you!!

animal.description: Star is a 9 year old, 70lb female Catahoula/Pyrenees mix. Star is spay, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and house trained. She loves to hang out with other dogs. She is very shy dog with people considering she came from an abusive home. She has skin issues due to the neglect that medicated shampoo has helped a lot and her skin and coat are much better. With her age and size, she does have arthritis and is on glucosamine chondroitin. If you are a patient and caring person, and will let Star relax and get used to you in her own time (maybe a week maybe a month or longer), you will find you have a spectacular dog. Star just needs to know she is safe and loved. Star and Abbie came to Lizzy’s together. They told us they would prefer to be placed together, but is not necessary. If you are interested in two dogs, these two would be a perfect pair to have.

animal.description:
Ameila came to us as a stray very thin and covered in fleas and ticks. She rather looks like a Shepherd/Hound type mix but has the drive and 'mouthiness' of a Heeler so perhaps all three, or who knows. She is about one-year old, not a big girl at only about 30 lbs. She is ACTIVE though - loves to run and run and run some more. She loves toys. Big NO to cats. Good with dogs, because she is a bit Heeler type 'nippy' lets say only older children please.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases or adoptions of two dogs together. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description.This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
You can also expedite the adoption process by filling our Adoption Application which you can find at: http://www.elmorehumane.org/HSEC_FORMS/AdoptionApplication.pdf and sending to us either by scanning and emailing to hselco@bellsouth.net or faxing to 334-567-8774.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Thank you! Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description:
Meet Hazel! She came as a stray in Haines City with Adele + 9 puppies. We were told Hazel was the dad, got her in cage and then realized she was a female but no way she was getting left behind! She's a senior pittie mix, about 55 pounds and 10 years old. In boarding she was sad and down. Just a few days in a foster home and she is playing with the other senior dog and so happy!! She wants a forever home with someone to give her all the love she missed in her life so far with a comfy couch and a yard to sunbathe and play in. She is a bit hard of hearing as an old gal so no kids to be safe. When you stop petting her, she will lift a paw trying to beg for more! She is so sweet and cute and we love this girl! She is house trained and loves belly rubs and a good bone to chew on!

To meet Hazel please fill out an application on www.maxxandme.org. She will be spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is only $125!

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix.  We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our pets based on personality, not breed label.

Hi, I am getting worn out.  I have been on  a Shelter situation for over 3 years, the place is nice, I have an inside outside large place but, all I want for Christmas is to have a home to call my own

.Georgina, is an energetic, curious, happy 6-year old spayed Staffordshire Terrier Mix female dog. At 65 pounds, Georgina is one big love bug. She's easygoing, loves her people, and is looking for someone who will spend some time with her. Georgina was born in 2014, she is house trained and microchipped; she knows her basic commands, sit, stay, down. Georgina is single and loving it, meaning that she would do best as the only dog in the home, she can be unpredictable with other dogs, she will walk quietly by any dog while on leash but she needs to be the only dog in a home, and she cannot live with cats. Georgy isn't too high energy, but she is strong, so she'll need someone who can physically handle a big, affectionate dog.  This sweetheart has been waiting a long time for her forever home, so don't wait, inquire today!


Georgina is up to date on all her vaccinations, she is heartworm negative and in excellent health. If you like to foster or adopt Georgina, call or text Kelly at 817-296-1427 or Miguel at 817-798-8416.

animal.description:
Our handsome young boy, Dodger, is taking applications for his furever home! Dodger was an outside dog who transitioned to inside life when he was surrendered to rescue last summer. He is a neutered, purebred Great Pyrenees who still has some rough edges. Like most Pyrs, he is a loving dog who wants to be with his people. He will sit and stay with you wherever you are and can be quite the goof ball, making you laugh if he invites you to join his special game of fetch. Dodger is okay with cats and other dogs and could benefit from a female companion. He tends to get a little rough when he wants to play with humans, mouthing and jumping. He also has some trauma triggers that need to be understood by his owners who must be willing to work with him. Dodger is okay with new humans once proper introductions have been made. He is a dog for an experienced dog owner who is willing to work with him and our behaviorist. We are limiting his adoption area to Ohio/Pennsylvania so his progress can be monitored as needed. We have no doubt that with a little time and love, this big boy will mature into the most pyrfect companion for some lucky adopter!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

WE WILL NOT RESPOND TO ANY APPLICATIONS FOR PROMISE THAT DO NOT FIT THE CRITERIA LISTED BELOW IN HER BIO.

Promise was given her name by her rescuer b/c we promised for her to have a better life if we had anything to do with it.  Promise at only 6-7 months old and her mom were at a rural shelter both shut down and terrified.  Promise is now with one of our dog trainers and learning to become a dog.  She LOVES other dogs and MUST go to a home with other confident and well mannered dogs.  Dogs make her come out of her shell and trust her human.  She is doing well in her crate and is housebroken.  UPDATE9/14 :  Promise is now 9-10 months old and living in a foster home with multiple other dogs and continuing to trust and flourish.

We will not place Promise in a home with children.  She needs to go to an adult only home who have time to devote to her growth and give her the patience she needs to do so.   She must go to a home that is fully fenced.  ADOPTERS ARE REQUIRED TO LIVE IN LORAIN COUNTY OR LIVE WITHIN 30 MINUTES OF WESTLAKE or WELLINGTON.  Adopters will be required to sign on to training with her dog trainer to smooth the progression of her going into a new home.

animal.description:
Poor Dennis! My heart goes out to this guy. He lived in the country with a single woman and her 6 kids.  He loved those kids! Very friendly and happy with them.  Mom and kids moved and just left Dennis there!  He is heartbroken and has not left the porch waiting for them to return.
A kind neighbor has been taking him some food/water. 

We took him in yesterday, he’s a big boy!! Seems to be a mix of Lab/Great Dane around 1-2 years old. Very scared about all the changes, never touched pavement, rode in a car, had a leash on, air conditioning etc. Look how sad this baby is!

We will have Dennis vetted, and then hopefully he can go into a new loving home! He would adore kids.... 
Well we now call him Dennis the Menace, as we can’t catch him to get him neutered yet!  He’s loving his new life here, has filled out, very healthy and happy and has lots of doggy friends! His day is coming tho!



Adoption fee includes spaying/neutering, shots, micro-chip and heartworm testing.
Please contact Dinesha  at 972-896-6313 or email at adbadoptions@yahoo.com.  To see dogs please download an application from our website, www.adifferentbreed.org and email to foster parents address above. We will arrange a meet and greet. Dogs that have been housebroken may need a refresher course or just learn your new routine.  Maybe they used a doggie door or rang a bell to go out.  Please have patience and give them some time!

Best Home For This Pet: Lily needs fearful dog experience. She is sweet but highly fearful. She is dog friendly, cat friendly, kids unknown.

We do our best to get to know each and every dog at our camp. Their personalities emerge after being with us for a bit and sometimes change. The personality and other information included in the above description is based on what we know currently in the shelter environment. All dogs are up to date on vaccines (Distemper, Rabies, Bordetella), microchipped, spayed/neutered and receive worming, flea & tick medication before they are adopted out. Please note there are some exceptions depending on the condition of the dog. If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application at https://www.camppapillon.org/dog-application.

Once your dog is in your home, they will adjust and relax and could become more playful or show more personality traits as they begin to open up. Once adopted, please allow your dog time to decompress and relax in a stable home environment.

animal.description:
Rocky Balboa
Male
Age: 3 Years old
Weight: 54 lbs
Breed: Boxer/Terrier mix

Hi there! My name is Rocky Balboa! I am a boxer, after all! Im a hunk of energy who LOVES to play ball; in fact, it is the only toy I care for and will play fetch every day! Im even learning how to play volleyball! I can run super fast and will always return the ball for more tosses! My foster parents are teaching me to drop, back (as in step back,) and easy so I dont get too excited and try to take the ball away too fast. Im getting pretty darn good at it too! A couple of good throws and I will be ready for a good nap! I do well with other dogs provided slow introductions are conducted and will require a period where I can get acclimated to them. When Im not wanting to play, Im always wanting to cuddle and sit on peoples laps. I will certainly let you know when I want to snuggle! I hope that is okay, I just love people so much! Sometimes my foster family cannot cuddle with me and ask for me to go lay down and I will head over to my own bed and take a nap. I also have learned to wait until I receive the command from my foster family for meal time and have shown to be very gentle when I receive treats!
Since I do not personally enjoy being home alone, my foster family has figured out if I get a good walk in or have a good play session prior to them leaving, those activities will help keep me napping for a few hours allowing me to have plenty of doggy dreams until they return. Also, I just love people and people seem to like me too! I always get compliments during my walks and how handsome I am! I have gotten better walking on a leash, but truly prefer having the capacity to run around freely! I also love car rides! I am always down for a good adventure! 
A fenced in yard would be even more awesome because then I can show you how fast I am and how I am basically a professional volleyball player! I would love extra space to run around while also exploring freely! I am also house trained and crate trained! I cant wait until I find my forever home so I can dazzle them with my personality and cuddles!

If you are interested in meeting the handsome Rocky Balboa, apply to adopt at www.causeforcanines.org Adoption fee is $250
Children must be 13 years old or older.
Must be 25 years old and an Ohio resident.
Unfortunately, no cats.

DENNIS is a friendly, 8-year-old, 50-pound Plott Hound mix.

He's a delightful friend and companion - friendly, lovable, and affectionate, DENNIS would be a fantastic addition to any family!

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:

animal.description: Hey everyone I'm Lou, better known as BIG LOU! I'm a 9 year old Chihuahua that likes to be where the actions at. I'm a Chihuahua so you all know what that means. I'm not good with kids so please don't ask, I'm more like a piece of furniture with attitude. I would like to be in a home to live out my golden years. I'm 9 so I don't like surprises and you need to speak up a bit so I can hear you. Once I trust you, I like to be picked up and taken outside so I can wander around the yard. I will do my business on a potty pad so a fenced yard isn't necessary but I do like the fresh air. I have a neurological problem that took my gitty up away but I'm hobbling just fine, just need some helpful attention sometimes. Once I trust you, please pick me up and let me sit with you or even better yet, let me in bed with you. I can be very vocal when I want attention so any type of apartment life won't be for me. If you feel like you are dog savvy enough to help me through my Golden years, please speak up so I can hear you. I'll be waiting right here for you. Lou is neutered, up to date on all vaccines, had a heart worm test, on heartworm preventative, had a fecal, had a full blood panel, had a dental, and microchipped. Lou’s adoption fee is $250.00. animal.description:
Sweet Sassy is looking for that special, one-of-a-kind home that will provide a quiet, peaceful environment she can thrive in. The perfect home would be one that provides structure, routine, calm activity inside and where someone’s home most of the day to keep her company.

Don’t get us wrong, she still has plenty of energy to go on long walks, play with her squeaky toys, splash around in her pool and engage in a robust game of tug-of-war with you, but  she gets anxious around noise and chaos. Especially the commotion produced by young children, so if there are children in the home, she prefers them to be older. 

Sassy enjoys the companionship of large, calm dogs, but no small dogs or cats please! Too tempting to chase.

This affectionate girl is friendly meeting new people, has good house manners and loves to snuggle with her people at the end of the day. Sassy’s foster mom is working on loose-leash walking and helping her to be more comfortable in a crate. She has a way of staring at her people and following them around to signal that it’s time for a potty break. So smart! And speaking of smart – she knows most of the basic obedience commands. Sassy needs an
experienced owner committed to continuing with her training on a regular basis. Could that exceptional person be you?

Sassy is 11-years-young and weighs approximately 60 pounds.

animal.description:
Requirements: a home with a secure, fenced yard with direct access from the home, no other animals in the home, no children under 14, needs to be with a semi-retired, or retired family/person

Applications are accepted from Chatham Kent only for review

Name of Foster Dog:   Chicka                                  
Breed: Maltese cross
Age: DOB Approx 2013                                                       
Sex: Female
Colour: White
Length of fur (short, medium, long): Long
Size (small, medium, large): Small
Weight: 12 lbs
Activity level (low, medium, high): medium

Meet Chicka – a tiny little love bug.  She is looking for her one true love, and needs that special person to keep her loved and held for the rest of her life. 

Chicka has some minor special issues that the one true love will be happy to accommodate – 1) she has no teeth left so she’ll need a special high-quality soft food and 2) she has dry eyes so she will need drops every day.  Such minor things when you look at that adorable face!

Our kissy, lovey, give-me-belly-rubs, Chicka is a bit nervous around other dogs, so she will need to be the centre of attention of only one person.  She will bark and become anxious when crossing paths with other dogs, but will move on with some reassurance and redirection.  She doesn’t mind a quick drive in the car now and then, but does prefer to walk, as it can sometimes give her anxiety.  She is also not a fan of grooming, so a professional will need to be on call.  This can change with patience and repetition.  She will also need to be with a semi-retired or retired family/person as she will bark when left alone.  

Walks are a happy thing for this doll – she is good on her harness and will get excited when squirrels or bunnies cross her path.  Redirection away from other dogs is necessary, but doesn’t detract from the fun of the rest of the adventure.  

More than anything, Chicka just wants to find her one true love, her forever person.  She wants all the hugs, attention, and loving she can get.  

If you are the match for this gorgeous, loving companion, please submit the adoption application at www.ckanimalrescue.com

Chicka is up to date with vaccinations, and is spayed.

Adoption fee: $375

animal.description:
Requirements: a home with a secure, fenced yard with direct access from the home, another playful dog of similar age, children age 8+ only 

Applications are accepted from Chatham Kent only for review

Name – Pom Pom
Breed: Pomeranian
Age: 11
Sex: male
Activity level: Medium
Fur: Medium
Pom Pom is a lover.  He loves attention, he loves other dogs, and he loves his people.  He is very vocal and will let you know when someone is coming or going, but is easily corrected if he doesn’t quiet down.  He also loves to be on his walks.  He will pull on the harness from time to time, but again, is super good with being corrected, and a treat makes him super happy to comply.  

Pom Pom needs a playmate, but we have not experienced how he is with cats.  He loves a car ride, he’ll just lay there and be content to travel.  Take him to Timmies for a Tim Bit and he’ll be your BFF forever.   

This fun fella has had quite a few teeth extracted, so he only has a few remaining.  He will require small bits of small food mixed in with canned/wet food.  But it definitely doesn’t stop him from enjoying a good bite to eat!  (He will require soft treats as well.)

Pom Pom needs someone who is willing to work with him and be patient with his barking.  He is just excitable, and has to let you know what’s happening.  Bites of cheese or soft treats work wonders to make him listen.  He will even shake a paw and lay down to have that reward.

If you and your dog are looking for a friendly, lovable and playful companion, please submit the adoption application at www.ckanimalrescue.com

Pom Pom is up to date with vaccinations, and is neutered.

Adoption fee: $300

They are not good with cats as both of them will pick on a cat at the same time, which is not safe. Handsome and Pretty Girl prefer adult owners. They are gentle and will take treats from a person's hand.

animal.description:
This dog is being fostered in Dallas TX and must be adopted within the Dallas, North Central Texas or the southern Oklahoma area.

NAME:             Daisy
GENDER:        Female (Spayed)
AGE:                 10 years old
WEIGHT:         About 7 pounds
DOGS:               Tolerates other small dogs (would be best as an only dog)
CATS:                Unknown with cats
CHILDREN:     All adult home, experienced adopters recommended

Meet Daisy.  This girl has blossomed like a flower with CRT and is now ready to begin her search for a forever home.

Daisy currently holds the distinction of the longest tenured foster in our CRT program.  She has been with CRT since May of 2019.  You heard that right – over a year in our foster program.  Daisy was found as a stray by Burleson Animal Services. She was shy and frightened, and BAS knew her best chance would be with a rescue where she could feel safe, begin to gain confidence, and grow.  So BAS reached out to CRT and asked us to bring this girl into our program.  We were happy to do so, and have been amazed at this girl’s progress.  She is now ready for the next phase of her life – a life filled with love and happiness.

Daisy tolerates the other small dogs in her foster home.  She is MUCH more interested in her people!  This girl loves to go outside and explore the yard.  She enjoys being outside when you have your morning coffee.  Daisy will also lay and sun herself.  There are no cats in her foster home, so we do not know how she would do with cats.  She also does not show interest in playing with toys.

Daisy adores her family.  Daisy is a bit shy when she first meets someone.  We believe this is because of her early years.  She may have been abused, at least verbally, as she is uncomfortable when people tower above her and reach down for her.  The fastest way to get to know her is to sit down and let her come up to you!  She will take some extra patience while she works up the courage to let you pet her. Once she gets comfortable with you, Daisy is a big snuggler.  We are looking for an experienced family who will be patient as she adjusts and gets comfortable in her new home.

Daisy would like to be the only dog whose family cuddles with her day a lot.  She is somewhat of a diva because she loves everything that is soft and luxurious.  She loves soft blankets, a favorite chair, the couch and your bed.  One of her favorite places is napping on the pillows on your bed!  She loves to snuggle with you on the couch when you are watching TV at night.  She will roll over for belly rubs – it is one of her favorite things!  She would love a mellow home where she could be your BFF and snuggle with you daily.

Daisy is about 10 years old.  She weighs 7 pounds, which is a great weight for her.  Daisy needed a dental when we got her.  Because of her neglect in her early years, she lost almost all her teeth during her dental.  She now has one ADORABLE tooth!  She is a great eater though!  She is primarily tan with a white neck and chest.  And her ears are amazing!  Daisy does alert at loud noises, but settles down fairly quickly.

Daisy is housebroken and she knows how to use a doggy door.  Daisy is crate trained and happily goes into her crate at night to sleep.  She is afraid of leashes (probably something in her early life) and therefore we have not taken her for walks.  We are not sure if she will ever learn to like this.  She would not be apartment appropriate for this reason.

Daisy’s ideal home would be a laid back environment where people are home a lot.  She gets joy from just hanging out with her people.  We are recommending an all adult home for her.  We also would like to find an experienced home that will be patient with her as she adjusts, learns that she is safe with you and begins to relax in her new home.  She has SO MUCH love to share.  We have fallen in love with this girl.  We are hoping you will too!

Daisy is being fostered in the DFW (Texas) area. If this sweet girl sounds like the right fit for your home, our CRT adoption form can be found at: http://www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/

Daisy is spayed, micro chipped, up-to-date on shots, HW negative. and on heartworm prevention.  She is ready to join a loving family – could that family be yours?

This dog is a CRT rescue. Reference checks, adoption contract and $250 adoption fee plus Texas Sales Tax required (note: as of 1-1-20, the Texas State Comptroller office is requiring all rescue groups to collect sales tax on adoptions, even though we are all 501c3. We are all fighting this, but for now, have been told it is non-negotiable).

As part of our mission to reduce the number of unwanted and sick dogs, we require that all current pets are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and taking heart worm prevention. Applications will not be considered if one or more of these requirements are not met.

After filling out an adoption application (found at http://www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/), please email DFWCoordinator@chihuahua-rescue.com if you are interested in this dog. Please be sure to read about our adoption process and then fill out an adoption application before emailing the contact person.

Dog's Name: Rosie

Dog's Approximate Age: 4 Years

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 64

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Yes

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?:

Crate trained?: Working on it

House trained?: Working on it

Heartworms?: No

7/19/20: Rosie here. I'll bet you thought I was lost. Well I was kind of hiding because I had eye surgery and had to wear a very annoying necklace that covered my face. I just refused to be seen in public like that but I'm great now and ready to Rock & Roll!

Since I was kinda just learning before my surgery I forgot how to play but my FB is trying to remind me and I'm remembering how much fun that was. My FM says she's so proud of me because I remembered it's ok to go out on a leash, ride in the car, and sit or down for treats. I love being smart so FM only has to say "outside" once and I go right to the door. I wait patiently for my meals and I go out right after I finish so I don't have any accidents in the house. I also know the word "out" means I can't go in the kitchen when FM is cooking or in the toy room when the kiddies are eating. I love kids too. When kids visit my FM I like to stay in the playroom. My favorite thing is lying around with my FB. He lets me steal his bones and his crate too. I love having a sibling. I nap in my own crate during the day and sleep in it at night if FM is too wiggly in the bed. Oh, and I just love when someone says my name. I get so wiggly that my tail goes so fast it almost disappears. I'm still shy but when people don't rush up to me I like to smell their back and then I make friends with them. I even let them pet me and I wag my tail. I'm still afraid of sudden noises but I'm so much better. I know Airplanes, leaves and compressors are not going to harm me. Not so sure about traffic and skateboards. I don't mind the broom or sweeper anymore but I like to go in the crate if that big vacuum comes out. FM still tells me I'm one of the smartest dogs she's ever met. When FM goes out I usually go get one of her shoes and maybe a slipper or two but it's just to keep me company. I don't chew on it. I LOVE chewing on Kongs with canned food or veggies though. I chew and bury, then chew and bury some more. I like burying my favorite things in my crate. I haven't worked on anything new this week because I'm just relaxing after having that awful head gear but I remembered all my manners I learned before my eye surgery. I know you have the perfect place for me. At least 1 FM and 1 sibling. More is fine as FM has lots of visitors but I am most comfortable when it's pretty quiet. I really need a crate for when I need to build courage but other than that I'm pretty easy going. I'm not fussy about food but my tummy needs changes to be slow.

Well, I just wanted you to know I'm all healed up and hope you weren't too worried. The scavenger hunt we went on was so fun and now it's your turn to come find me. Ready, set, go!

5/23/20: I know it's taking a while for you to find me, what with the way everything's upside down now, but I'm taking advantage and practicing to be the best friend I can be for you. In just the last few weeks I've learned how to walk on the leash and the last few days I found out there's some pretty good smells out there too! FM is proud that I walk so nicely on the leash; I don't pull at all unless you count the times I freeze when something scares me. At first it was all real scary but now I'm interested in scouting out some more of those smells, I'm still working on ignoring the noises. I love my FB and we play hard when we first wake up and right before supper. He's teaching me how to squeak toys and we play tug of war. FM says I'm like a cuddly lap dog because when she sits down I want to be right next to her. While I'm waiting for you I'm also practicing manners and FM says I'm a really smart girl. She told me my furever family will be so happy they found me because I'm the best girl, so funny and so smart, yup, that's what she says.

5/9/20: Rosie here, checking in. The last couple weeks have been very exciting for me. FM is so proud of me because I didn't have any accidents in the house. She did tell me it would be nice if I could alert her when I have to go out so she didn't have to open the door to check and I just looked at her and said, "I am" you just don't know my language yet! I love playing with my FB, I have a den I can go sleep in where it is safe and cozy. Sometimes I just sleep on my FB's beds during the day but at night when FM says, "night night time" I run right in my crate. This week FM said I had a major accomplishment because I walked a little bit in the neighborhood. Truthfully I didn't like it very much but FM says if we keep practicing I will learn to love it just as much as my FB. I also am curious about school time. My FB and his GSD look at FM and position when she says a word. FM says it won't be long before I have to perform too or I won't get free treats because she says I'm so very smart. This week I learned that "Leave it" means I have to stop doing what I'm doing. It's hard because those treats FM has on her table look so tempting but I love to see my FM happy and tell me what a good girl I am so I just walk away. She said I am going to be an A+ for someone who wants a comfy pal to cuddle with, silly girl to laugh at and best friend for their other pet. I can't wait to meet you.

4/26/20: Hi all, Rosie here again. I just wanted to let you know how well I'm doing. I love my FB and we play boxing every day, especially when we wake up. FM laughs at us and says we look like kangaroos, I don't know what a kangaroo is but I know I love wrestling with my FB. Well I finally learned that the back door isn't as scary as I first thought and now I even go out the door all by myself when FM says, "Rosie, outside?" It's a little scary if the wind blows but my spot outside is nice and small so I feel safe as long as I can see the open door. FM gets so excited when squat and I get extra wet food. I tried fooling her a few times by just sitting down but it didn't work. FM said, "Rosie you are such a smart girl but no treat for that." I get treats for letting FM put a leash on my collar too as long as she takes it right off I don't try to run in my crate when I see it. FM said just keep practicing and it'll be ok just like the back door. My FB had a play date so I met his German Shephard friend when her Mom needed a sitter for an hour. We made friends right away and we played outside on the patio. I even forgot I was afraid when a truck went by. FM said when that Covid-19 goes away all the grandkids will come play with me too. I'm so excited for that. I like to watch some animals on T.V and even on FM's phone. I especially like to watch myself play. When the wind broke the T.V. a man came to the house and I didn't run and hide, I just watched him. A new man had to come the next day so I thought I'd just follow him around and lie by his feet when he was sitting on the floor to make sure he fixed it right this time. FM was so happy for me. She said, "Rosie, you sure are practicing so well it won't be long before your furever family finds you.

4/13/20: That nasty covid thing interrupted my settling in so I had to go to another foster home with a new FM and a new FB. To tell you the truth the first few days were kinda rough, but I am getting used to the new environment. I'm still resting a lot so I can put on some weight but I heard FM on the phone telling the vet that my stomach issues are resolved. I think that's good because I feel so much better. I'm still shy and not sure it's safe outside my crate but my FB keeps encouraging me to come out and sniff around. I'm beginning to follow him a little more and I wag my tail really hard when FM says good morning. I'm trying hard to learn that the back door is a safe place and I watch my FB run in and out trying to get me to follow him. Maybe tomorrow? FM keeps telling me I'm practicing to go to a forever home. I wag my tail and imagine a home with at least one sibling and even a kid or two, the more the merrier right? Now that my tummy issues are gone and they say I'm fixed up so I won't have puppies I'll just keep practicing until you find me.

2/28/20: Rosie here! I'm still very timid. Foster mom and dad still have to pick me up to take me outside. I lived a really rough life before and I'm still learning to trust. I stay in one room and don't like to come out, but when my foster family comes to me, I get really excited and wiggle my whole body now!!! I am learning to play a bit. My foster fur sister and I have gotten into a couple tiffs over high value items like special toys and chew bones (mom now doesn't let us have those unless the other is not around - insert sad face). She doesn't think it was me causing the problem, my foster fur sister is a bit spoiled and doesn't like to share much.

I need a family who will take time to show me I'm loved. I am not going to immediately be a big cuddle bug, but I think in

12/17/20: Charlotte is a super sweet girl. She loves all people and hasn't meet a stranger yet. Her favorite things are going for walks, car rides and snuggling on the sofa. She is completely house trained and has never had an accident. We are working on her getting used to the crate. She is also working on her leash reactivity towards other dogs while on walks. She is able to be redirected with guidance. She does great in car rides and loves to go to with the family to the beach and trails.

Charlotte would do best to have a 6' privacy fenced yard so she has a safe place to play- she has come a very long way but is still quite reactive on a leash when she sees other dogs. She also has some separation anxiety when left alone, so she would love a forever home where there are people home with her a lot of the time.

9/16/20: Charlotte loves cuddling, riding in the car and walks. She is a sweet girl with lots of love to give, wants to be where the action is. Scared of thunder, be prepared to have her in bed with you when there is a storm brewing.

7/8/20: Loves people, attention and snuggles. We love her already and we have had her only one day- more updates to come

5/30/20: Charlotte is the kindest most loving 5 year old. My kids 7 and 1 and 1/2 yrs old love on her and she just eats it up. She loves to walk great on the leash, and loves human company. 8/4/20: Hey guys, it's Tonks, back with an update! Sorry for the delay, my new foster dad keeps saying the world is a crazy place these days. All I know is life is good as long as I get treats and a peanut butter filled Kong.

Anyway, I'm finally settled in with my new foster dad. The first week was a little scary because there were so many new smells and places. But I checked everything out and I really like my new home! Theres a big yard to run in when I get the zoomies and a couple sprinklers I can jump through when it's really hot outside. And I LOVE all the attention I'm getting being the only dog in the house.

When my foster dad leaves during the day I get to take a nap in my crate with my Kong. He says I've learned to be a really good boy when he goes to work. Among other things, there's just so much to learn. While I may be a little slow, I'm really good at listening and following directions once I've learned something. Especially if there are treats involved!

That's it for now. I'll continue to work on my good behavior and try to not let my curiosity get me in trouble. I can't wait to meet more Hoomans because they all love me so please come visit! Stay tuned for more progress updates in the near future and stay safe.

6/8/20: Hello everyone! My name is TonksI'm a stocky fella that loves being with my people. When I jump on the dog bed my favorite thing to do is roll around and rub myself on everything. I love napping, but I also love finding new things- I'm curious! When I came from the shelter, they thought I was around 3 years old, but the folks at CBR think I'm more of a middle aged guy. I like chasing the tennis ball but they say that's not great for my arthritis- I'm on some great supplements that are helping that some, but I'm not a guy that will need to be your running buddy. They think I spent a lot of my life before CBR by myself, so I'm looking for a home without any other pets- I like to have the attention of humans all to myself! I also sometimes like to give cats a run for their money (can you blame me?), so I need folks who can keep me calm on the leash or pick me up if I try to bolt for the kitties (I'm a smaller guy, so that's not too hard to do). The folks I'm with are working on teaching me manners and basic commands- they say I'm sort of a slow learner- they aren't sure if maybe in my past life I got a little injured in my head. Once I learn something though, I'm golden! I'm just looking for people who will be patient with me. I'm pretty good in the crate and housetrained, and apparently when I get excited I make little snorting piggy noises which the humans say is really cute.

Tonks is looking for a forever home with a family that will continue his training and will be patient, firm, and consistent with him to help him learn his manners. We know his family is out there!

_____________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Delilah

Dog's Approximate Age: 2 years

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Pocket Boxer (under 50lbs as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 47 pounds

Good with small dogs?: No

Good with big dogs?: No

Good with cats?: No

Good with kids?: Yes, older only (12 and over due to being too rambunctious)

Any medical issues?: Heartworm Positive - being treated with slow kill method

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: Yes

10/26/20:
Delilah has come so far since this summer and we're very proud of her progress! We realized quickly she would act out from anxiety which amped her up and she didn't have the skills or confidence to calm and soothe herself. We also found that she had underlying allergies that were making her irritable and itchy. Zyrtec has been magic for her and while she no longer gets hives, we have noticed she'll chew her paws so consider wiping them down as needed. With some medicine, firm rules, and a whole lot of patience Delilah has come a very long way in just a few weeks. She is showing us a very sweet loving and playful personality. As a super chewer, antlers, Kongs and tough toys have really helped her relax. She LOVES having her own blankets to making nests in, and they are the one item we allow her to chew on as needed for comfort. By doing so we found her need to chew our soft furnishings drastically decrease. Having a crate will always be important for Delilah; it's her safe space and she sleeps there overnight. With time, we've been able to leave her out during the workday downstairs without worry; she just sits on the couch or on her bed. On the weekends we venture to Umstead or the Art Park for long walks. She does very well in the car when in the backseat; she will lean against the chair or curl up. It's important to know that in the trunk or way back she will get car sick. Delilah is learning how to tell us her needs and while she's getting better everyday there are times she gets "stuck" or when she steals shoes for attention if we ignore her too long. She also shows some separation anxiety and isn't quite sure what to do if she's super tired but everyone else is busy doing interesting things. Delilah's interest in other dogs is complicated. While she wags her tail and wines at other dogs passing by, she has had consistently negative introductions with them. She walks beautifully and other than sometimes "sinking" her body, she doesn't bark or lunge at other dogs so long as you're passing by. We have many dogs in our neighborhood and she couldn't care less when they bark through their windows or doors. But it is important Delilah is your only pet. She really needs a family who is willing to be patient, firm and flexible in the beginning. It's worth it to get to the big doe eyed sweet girl we've come to know.

_____________________________________________________

7/28/20: Hey! It's me, Delilah! I'm just loving these sunny summer days! Even if it's 90 degrees, I want to be outside laying in the sun or watching people walking by. My humans even put sunscreen on my nose! My favorite is when my people are outside with me. I'm right by their side at all times because I don't want to miss out if they stumble upon some treats. While they're working in the garden, I stand nearby and guard em. I also like when they're grilling because anything that drips on the ground is mine!

We also go for walks which help me get my energy out, but I get tired quickly. After 20 minutes, I can't keep my tongue in my mouth. I don't want to brag but I'm really good at walking on a leash. I stay right next to my human and don't pull. I used to get excited when I saw rabbits and charge after them but I don't do that anymore. I'd love to catch one someday but I know that our walks are not the time to do that.

I'm happy with any people who love being outside, just like I do! It's supposed to rain later so I'm heading outside to work on my tan!

6/12/20: Hey friends! This is Delilah a.k.a Deedee a.k.a Lil' D and I wanted to give everyone an update on all the fun stuff that's been happening in my life! I'm starting to learn the rules of the house and I'm getting better at following them. These humans have a magic mat and every time I lay on it, I get a treat! I'm talking good stuff like hot dogs, apples and peanut butter. I'm even picking up some new tricks too. I've mastered "shake" and "twirl," but I'm still getting the hang of "fetch" and "drop." If I come home with you, what tricks are you gonna teach me?

Delilah shows a lot of friendly interest in our neighbor's dog (Husky), and may do well with a dog who is OK with a pushy, energetic sibling. She would just need opportunities to calm back down between playtimes, as once she gets overexcited, it's hard to bring her back down.

5/4/20: Little Delilah here, reporting for doodie! 3 weeks have flown by at my new foster home! I'm the sweetest girl looking for a family that will be consistent in rules, give me lots of outdoor time, and has a sunny spot where I can nap. Inside, outside, doesn't matterif I can find a spot of sun, I'm going to nap there! I'm VERY good on a leash, especially if I know who's boss. I get a little over excited at times (who doesn't?!) but after some time to settle down in my kennel, I'm just fine. Other dogs and young kids might find me a bit much - I just want to go go go and don't understand when it's time to stop. I love toys, and dinner time is my favorite time of day. I'm perfectly happy to hand out and sleep in my kennel, I'm perfectly potty trained, I like to sleep in and am not picky about a morning routine; it's just my evenings that need to be a little more structured. Not to brag, but I think I'm pretty smart. I'm a quick learner! In just the three short weeks here, I've learned some fun new tricks, like how to wait patiently for my dinner, "tough", and "down".

2/25/20: Very energetic happy girl. She loves walking, running and exploring. Absolutely loves her stuffed animals and loves to play. Great with people and seems very fond of men.

12/25/19: Delilah is a 2 year old high energy dog who is looking for a home where she can play a lot in a fenced backyard or go on nice long walks. She would also make a good running buddy! Because she has a lot of energy, we think she would be best in a home with kids 12 and over. She is selective about dogs, so she would like to be the "queen bee" of your house. She is crate and house trained, rarely barks, and knows basic commands. She's wondering... could you be her forever family?

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Niko

Dog's Approximate Age: 2 years

Gender: Male

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 58 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Don't know yet

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?: FINISHED QUICK KILL SHOTS FOR HEART WORM ON THE 20th OF AUGUST.

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: Yes

Niko would do best with a family that is home more than not because he is extremely insecure.

9/4/20: Hey, Niko here. I've just about finished my resting time after my last set of heart worm shots. Its been a long journey since I've been rescued by CBR, I'll be ready soon for a fur-ever home. My foster dad is very proud of me because I learned how to drool and have a gassy butt like other boxers do. I love to snuggle, be a silly boy with my sisters and still let foster dad know when someone walks by the house. I'm not sure about thunderstorms and fireworks, I will snuggle close and tight next to you till its over. You will have to tell me its going to be ok. I've not been by myself (except 2 stays at the vet) since being rescued. I always had my sisters around or mom and dad. Dad has left me out of my kennel for several hours at a time with 1 or 2 of my sisters and I do great. You will have to help me get better with boy dogs I still get little too excited. I can do it, with your help. I don't know what a cat is so I don't know how I will do. I sure will miss my foster mom and dad, they have been great to me.

____________________________________________________________________________

8/17/20: Hey everyone it's Niko. I've had to settle down since getting my first HW shot but I still have another 30 days of rest after my last shots later this month. Im not looking forward to the shots they make me sick to my stomach and I don't feel well for a couple days after. One good thing is I've learned to cuddle and I love it. When I was sick from my shots my foster dad snuggled with me and told me the stories from his other Boxers and he would rub my belly till I fell asleep, snoring and all. I went to work with foster dad till I started feeling better. I love laying on the floor while my foster dad watches youtube and rubs my belly, sometimes he is on the couch but most of the time he is on the floor next to me. Im not a big fan of toys but I do love frozen beef bones and rawhides till they get too small for me. My sister Izzy showed me how to play with a kong that is filled with treats. It took me awhile to figure out that my kong had treats in it, I would just eat my sisters treats from her kong while she played with it. I love blueberries, dried pineapple but most of all I LOVE, LOVE, LOVE cheese puffs. Foster dad has been using these treats to help me learn stay and come and sometimes he just tells me how great I am and kisses my head for being an A-MAZE-ING boy. I follow him around all over the house, he has been teaching me to stay while he leaves the room till he gets back. He says it will help me not to follow around the house and that he will come back. My buddy Mason comes to see me a lot and we watch wrestling on TV. One day he brought his brother Luke over. Luke and I became the WDW (world diaper wrestling) undisputed intercontinental tag team cage match champions of the world. We beat the former champs (Woody, Buzz Light year and Mason) in a handicap one fall no time limit match. That was a lot of fun. Check on me soon, I'll be ready soon after my last HW treatment. NIKO, out.

6/23/20: Hey, it's Niko checking in on Father's Day. My foster dad is the best dad EVER!! When I thought it could not get any better, just sayin'. I met a couple new boys since I last wrote, Alston (12) and Luke (3). Even though Alston is not a dog person (I don't know why) he helped me learn by letting me sit in the same room with him and not pet or rub me. Foster dad said not all people like dogs and its ok, I need to practice my manners anyway. Luke was a hand full with all his squealing and running around, I did my best to keep up with him. I had to help save my foster dad when he rides this thing that sounds like a dinosaur. He brings it out in the yard to feed it, it chews up the grass. It must be very powerful cause it goes around in circles with FD on top of it. I run to help him by nipping on its black feet its ferocious and growls back at me while it eats, but I'm not afraid of it. FD tells me that he is ok. He let me sniff it when he put it back in its cage FD calls it a shed. Its belly must have been full cause it made no more dinosaur noise. We have another loud animal I've never seen before- this one is kept in the house in a smaller room, Its not as loud as the shed dinosaur. FD fights with this one everyday, they start on the kitchen and work their way into the living room. It lunges forward and FD pulls it back it lunges forward and he pulls it back, this goes on for 20 minutes. I go into hero mode and try to nip at its one eye in the middle of its head. It must not see to well cause this thing has a bright light for a eye. FD fights that thing all by himself, FD always wins. Then he puts it back in its cage he calls it a closet. My foster sisters are doing well, thanks for asking. Since going to daycare I get to play with all 3 in the backyard. They get in a kiddy pool when they get hot, I'm not too sure about doing that just yet. I'm eating with all of my sisters at the same elevated food bowl station. FD is teaching us all to wait till he places the food down, sometimes I just can't wait. Daycare is a BLAST, I can't believe we just get to play all day. I have to work on playing well with other boy dogs, sometimes I get too excited. I just finished some medicine for my heart worms, soon I'll have to go get some shots. 2 shots will be back to back with no break. I'll have to keep calm for a couple weeks after the first one. Wish me luck, FD says we will be working on my listening, staying, down and come here commands during that time. He says we are going on some field trips before the shots, he is going to take me in some stores around town. Check me out soon, have a great doggy fathers day. Maybe this time next year I'll have a mom and dad to celebrate with. NIKO OUT!

6/1/20: Hey!! Its Niko, BUSY, BUSY, BUSY! It sure is nice to get out and do things, I didn't know how great life was as a D-O-G! I have had a lot of new experiences since last time. Foster dad has taken me to work on the Army base funny place though, they all wear the same clothes and have the same haircuts thats weird. They all love to rub me and tell me how smart I am. They let me watch their classes while my foster dad talks and teaches them how to fix boo boos and ouchies. The car rides are awesome, I love to look out the window and see things pass by, never a dull moment. I get to play with my foster sisters in the house, they are a BLAST to play with. Lucy and Izzy are bigger and younger than me while Bella is a older and smaller than me. Life has been so great with them in it, thats for sure!! My foster dad puts me on a leash and he lets me take him for walks, then I take him home and he rubs me telling me I did great! I get to sleep at night with everybody and I have no accidents,oh yea! Im learning how to sleep in my own comfy bed, 3 words A-MAZE-ING I sleep like a baby. I like when they put me and my foster sisters in our kennels during the day, I get to catch up on naps till foster dad or mom comes home. The Doctors who take care of me are great Im not afraid of them at all, I thought I would be. They look at me with bright lights and listen to me breath and I think its just fun. Ive got to play with some kids and make new friends too, Mason who is 10 loves to play with me. Naomi who is 16 isn't afraid of me AT ALL, imagine that. I get to take her for walks too, WHAT! Foster dad says Im gonna meet some more kids soon. Im learning to share water and food with my sisters, thats one thing I never had to do by myself is share, so its baby steps for me. I had my neuter today and feel little lost if you know what I mean. Foster dad says I'll be just fine as he kisses my head and scratches my belly. I'll get to go to daycare and play with a bunch of dogs soon, ALL DAY! Im excited. Well you can see I've been busier than a one legged cat in a litter box. Im learning, thats for sure. Anyway, just checking in. Check up on me soon, I'll have more great adventures and pictures too.

5/24/20: Hi everybody!! My name is Niko. The kindness of one special person got me out of a bad place and in the loving care of CBR. Her children said you can't save every dog and she told them I can save this one. To that special person, THANK YOU I won't let you down. My new start in life is because of YOU!! My nub has not stopped wagging since I left that place. I am brand new at being a family member and I'm trying my best to see and try new things every day. I want to run and play with all 3 of my foster sisters but I get so excited I can only play with one at a time while on a leash. Foster dad says I'll get better after I'm... neutered? Anyway, I'll be ready for my FUR-ever family soon. I have scars on my face and neck that tells my past but not my future. Watch for my updates to see what new things and experiences I learn!!

_____________

animal.description:
Aria was supposed to be a brood momma, but never did end up a mom. She is  6 years old and now retired and looking for the perfect cushy couch just for her.  She is not a good only dog. She has to have some other dogs to keep her busy and a couple human kids would be great.  She is sweet and laid back most of the time.  Only time she is not so laid back is when chaos starts.  She will growl and bark if the atmosphere  gets to wild and crazy.  She loves to play with toys and will motherly keep control of all other dogs in the area.  She likes to take long walks in the park if it is not too hot.  Aria is a "Black Brindle", so she is more black than brindle and does get hot easily in the summer months.  She will love you forever if you get her a kiddy pool to lay in when outside to play.  She would love a quiet scheduled household, and another younger dog that she could boss around.  She loves to take naps and would not mind at all if she had her own special blanket and pillow for sleepovers.  Please feel free to inquire about Aria,  She is a one of a kind girl!
*****Not Good With Cats or small fluffy animals****

animal.description: Chance was transferred to our rescue from Kendall County Animal control. He was not handling life in a kennel very well and needed foster care. Chance is a senior guy estimated to be 10-11yrs old. He is a huge lap dog! Always wants to be by your side or in your lap! He needs a home in which someone is always home as he gets separation anxiety. He has some hearing loss and gets anxious when no one is home, will tip over garbage, get in to things he should not. He has a fear of crates, and needs a home where he will not be crated. He is obssessive with his favorite toys. Might be ok with another calm dog his size or larger. He is not good with small dogs or cats. He still enjoys walks, but shorter walks as his arthritis is starting to slow him down. He loves all people. animal.description:
Born February 9, 2020 Lily aka Lily Bear, Lily Bell is a female German Shepherd mix seeking a forever home! This girl is a huge cuddle bug! She's that old saying Sweet and Spice and everything nice! She is spunky, lots of energy, sassy, and playful. You pick her up to hold her she usually cuddles right into your arms like a baby. She even reaches for you, with her front paws, if she wants you to hold her. Lily’s ideal family would be an active one who would include her in adventures like hiking, running and camping. Lily loves kids and want to be part of the action wherever she goes!

Lily has Megaesophagus which is a medical condition effecting the esophagus, which is the muscular tube that carries food from the mouth to the stomach. She eats her meals in a custom built Bailey chair so she can remain upright 20-30 minutes after each meal. After that, she is right back to her puppy antics! Families who have adopted dogs with Megaesophagus report that the feeding process it is pretty easy and routine after you get the hang of it.

Lily currently lives with several other dogs and one elusive cat. She is kennel trained, and currently learning how to ring a bell to let her people know she wants to go outside. Lily knows basic commands but gets excited and forgets sometimes. She definitely has the German Shepherd smarts and is highly trainable. Lily is leash trained and loves walks and car rides. 

All large and/or active dogs will require a full fenced (6ft) secure yard. 
No children under 5. 

Like all Mikey's Chance dogs, this dog will come to you from a foster home that has provided loving one-on-one attention, socialization and some basic training, as well as quality food and exercise. 

Applications can be found at www.mikeyschance.com and completed on a computer, tablet, and/or phone. Please note that adopters are not chosen on a first come, first served basis, but full consideration is given to the best fit for the dog AND the adopter. Applications can take up to 3 weeks to process. Application submission DO NOT guarantee approval for adoption.

animal.description:
Juliet (aka Chubs) is around 3 years old and weighs approximately 40-45 pounds. She is a small gal. She's shy, skittish even, and will require adopters that are full of patience and compassion to help her work on her confidence. She is under-socialized and not suitable for a home that will require her to be friendly and social with people. She is not aggressive by any means; she is just afraid of new situations and her impulse is to hide. We'd prefer a home that has had experience with dogs and understands her body language when she is uncomfortable; we don't believe she should be a first-time dog. She needs a secure yard with no gaps or holes she can slip out of or underneath. Juliet is as gentle as can be. She is good with other dogs, though doesn't play much with them. She has initiated play, but it will take time. She would be good with kids over the age of 10 years old. She would do best with no kids or with calm kids who won't roughhouse with her, as she is a shy dog. Juliet is loving and doting with her family and will make a great companion with time. She is crate-trained, but will need patience from her adopters to work with her on her leash-training. Juliet was found in the middle of the desert  with her puppies who were around two weeks old at the time, where she had given birth under a pile of rocks. The family's rescue can be viewed on our Instagram page (@poochmatch). All of her puppies have since been adopted. Now it's time for her turn! Her adoption fee is $295 and covers the cost of her spay, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchip and microchip registration. If you’re interested in adopting, the first step is completing an adoption application which is available on our website, Poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab. Please read the following paragraphs for additional information about our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered.

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in, please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

Bear is approximately 15-years-old and does have arthritis in his legs, so he will need a home without stairs, and a yard that he can go for potty breaks and to bathe in the sunshine.

He has a very sweet nature, but craves constant human affection. We ideally would like to find someone who could be with him at home all day, and see him through for the rest of his golden years. Bear may become overwhelmed with children so a home without kids and other pets would be best.

Bear is a very special dog. He was very loyal to his guardian and even waited by him for a week after his passing before he was found. This loss has shattered him, so we know we have to find him a new best friend soon to shower him with love and care.
