animal.description:
Desi is a senior big guy in need of a retirement home. He is a big beefy dude with all of the love and loyalty to match!
He spent the first 9 years of his life as an outside chained dog until his angel rescued him and got him healthy. He's now 10 years old and we are helping him find that low key home made for senior dogs who deserve to be spoiled and loved like there is no tomorrow! Desi definitely deserves to be treated like a king for his golden years!!

Desi is great with kids 10+ and since he has spent no time with children younger than that his entire life we would not recommend him learning to love toddlers or young children at his age. He loves human affection and his ideal home would have no other animals in it and a fenced yard so he doesn't have to be tethered or chained ever again! He is a strong walker and non reactive to other dogs but in his home can be a little jealous or possessive of other animals affection etc... so again... just to give him his absolute best and stress-free senior years we really would love to see him as the only animal in the home.

Once you meet this big guy it will be love at first sight - he is such a goofball with a fun playful personality and just loves to be by people despite not having that for the majority of his life. 

Please contact us if you're interested in discussing Desi :)

Adoption Process: PLEASE READ!
Anyone interested in meeting our adoptables must complete an online application, which is located on our website. This site is updated weekly so if an animal is listed they are available for adoption. Once the application is approved we will set up a meet and greet with the animal to ensure a good fit and then before adoption is complete we will schedule a home check to ensure a safe environment for the animal you are looking to adopt. If you live outside of the Tri-County area we will do our best to accommodate a home visit but it will rely on the availability and volunteers at that time. At this time we cannot do out of the state adoptions. We also do not do on-the-spot adoptions and we do not adopt out animals by a first-come, first-serve basis. We strive to fit everyone of our animals to the best match possible! We pride ourselves in responsibly placing animals in homes that are best fit for their needs.

animal.description:
This strikingly gorgeous young boy is Jesse, a Pyr/Husky mix. He has the typical beautiful looks of a Pyr, complete with a lovely fluffy coat that makes him look even more handsome, and also the piercing blue eyes of a Husky that garners your attention and eternal love. Still young and full of playfulness, Jesse is an energetic boy who prefers to be on the go at all times. These days, he absolutely loves rolling around in the snow with his foster siblings! Jesse will thrive in an active family where his people are dedicated to meeting his needs - training classes where he can learn new skills and channel his energy in a positive manner will ensure that he receives adequate mental stimulation. He will need a patient, experienced owner to work with him on resource guarding, although he will 'trade' if given the opportunity. While Jesse can seem to be an independent boy, there is no doubt that he enjoys the company of his foster siblings and/or favorite people. If you are an outdoor enthusiast, Jesse will be your best buddy to keep you company on all your adventures!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can call 877-739-3582 or email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
I'm Punkin, the BFF you've been looking for. I'm a low-drama girl who is always here to listen, go for joy rides, hang out on the patio or just sleep in and watch Netflix. I'm looking for a mellow family to vibe with!

I'm good around other dogs, especially if they're relaxed and easygoing. Let's do a meet and greet with your pack to make sure we're all happy. I also love kids! I would do best with kiddos who are calm and gentle around dogs. 

I have some crate anxiety, but structure and occasional CBD work wonders for me. I love being around my people, and I feel much better once I know they'll always come back for me.

I love my toys, especially chasing tennis balls! (But you're gonna have to fetch it yourself. I can't be expected to do EVERYTHING around here!) Puzzles are my favorite and I work hard to solve them. I also love to learn new stuff. I got a big brain and I know how to use it!

I can't wait to meet you and give you five million kisses before committing to a life-long snuggle session. Apply to meet me now!

**Punkin's adoption fee has been 100% sponsored by a Good Human**

animal.description:
Hello my name is PeeWee and I am a male, senior poodle mix and I am about 10 lbs in weight. I was an unclaimed stray at a local Shelter. When I arrived I had an enlarged prostate  and I was peeing and pooping uncontrollably. I am now wearing a disposable belly band since I was neutered. Sometimes it seems at times to go through the motions of going to the bathroom but I still am Incontinent. It could improve or not over time, just have no way of knowing how much and or when.  I am a really sweet boy just craving love and attention. I am Good with other dogs and indifferent to the cat. After all I have been through my foster Mom says I am still pretty Peppy and energetic and attentive boy looking for someone to accept him just as I am and love me. 
If you could be that someone for me, please fill out an application on the rescue's website www.floprva.org This rescue gives us seniors a chance for a good life and we are true treasures.
Love, 
PeeWee xo

Sylvester is a silly Doberman Mix, that was born in 2014. He loves walks, belly rubs, laying in the sun, and chasing balls in the yard. If you are interested in adopting, please complete our Pre-application: https://form.jotform.us/asr628/ShortAdoptionInquiry


----------------------PLEASE READ-------------------------------
Our dogs are dogs are fostered in Texas but available for adoption in the Pacific Northwest...With stops in - Lacey, WA  and Portland, OR.
These dogs are transported to a predetermined location agreed upon by the rescue.

Our out of state adoption fee is $500. This fee includes spay/neuter, current vaccinations, a registered microchip, a negative heartworm test, health certificate, and transport costs. 
As an Apollo direct adoption, the adoption interview/meet and greet occurs on video call (Skype, FB Messenger call, Facetime, etc). The adoption application and fee would be finalized prior to transport.

animal.description:
UPDATE - Zoey had her surgery and recovered while in a foster home.  She is now back at HSW looking for forever home.

*FOSTER OR FOREVER HOME WANTED!*

Say hello to Zoey! This 9 year old mystery mix girl came into our shelter as a stray. She is super sweet, loving, and very playful for a senior girl! Zoey does need to be the only animal in her foster or forever home. She has lots of love to give and life left to live, she just needs to find her perfect forever family! 
  
Zoey is in need of a foster or an adoptive home ASAP.  The more we spread the word the more this sweet girl has a chance of finding someone to foster her for 2 weeks - a month.  

Zoey needs a foster to recover from a much-needed surgery for a growth on her chest.  The Vet will perform the surgery on her as soon as she has a foster or adoptive home because unfortunately the shelter environment is not conducive to her recovery.
All vet and other expenses will be covered by the shelter and the very generous souls who made donations towards her surgery and recovery.

After her recovery, she will go back to the shelter and be looking for her FUREVER HOME.  Unless it is a foster-to-adopt...hopefully?

Below is a link to youtube video with shelter Manager Cait explaining in more detail.  (It's 6 minutes ahead if you want to fast forward ahead) But please feel free to watch the whole video and SUBSCRIBE  to the Walden Humane Society's channel.   https://youtu.be/mSexzZX8IGA

animal.description:
Rita is a 6 year old pit bull mix who is a sweet girl.  She lived most of her life out on a chain before she was taken to a high kill shelter where she had 10 days or less to get adopted or rescued.  Older pits who have lived on chains are not in high demand .. but we saw her face and could not let her die.  So we pulled her and that was in November of 2018.

Rita was of course a little unsure of people and other dogs, so we had to put her in our indoor / outdoor kennel.  Over the last 2 years she has blossomed so much.  She was a strong heart worm positive when we pulled her, but she has been treated and is now heart worm negative and on monthly preventions.  She is of course spayed and up to date on her vaccinations.  She is about 60 lbs of solid love!  She has been introduced to other dogs and does well with dogs her size that are not alphas and is happy to run and play in a fenced yard.  She would also do well as an only dog.

We hope there is a special adopter out there who will give Rita the life she deserves and have a lot of time and patience for her as she transitions to living inside a home.  A home with a fenced yard and doggy door access to the yard would be the most ideal or someone who is home who can let her in and out as needed through out the day.  She is a bit of a snuggle butt .. so be prepared for lots of love and affection as well.  A physically fenced yard is a must!  I would think she would be fine with kids 8 or older just because of her size and when she gets excited she can get a bit hyper lol.

Rita is a great dog, she needs a great family to step up and continue to be her rescue hero!  We have done what was needed to get her healthy and ready, now it is time for a family to say “we want to give Rita the life she was always meant to have”. 

You will find videos of Rita on our Facebook page as well if you want to see some of her earlier posts.  She is a happy girl looking or a happy life!  https://www.facebook.com/806737346045826/videos/2269299646644495/?v=2269299646644495

Rita is currently located in Tennessee and the adoption fee is $150.  The first step in our process is submitting the application.  We are happy to set up a meet and greet once an application has been approved. If you would like to adopt Rita please fill out our online adoption application at http://safehaventn.com/ .

Hello Everyone! My name is Gizmo and I am a cute little 8-year-old girl. I am just 5 lbs and my foster believes I am a Shih Tzu mix. I was found alone on the streets and my kind foster took me in, however, I need a home where I will be loved forever. I love going on long fast walks and also staying right next to you. I do bark at other dogs, I'm very small and need them to know not to mess with me. I am very smart and I am potty trained. My favorite activity is cuddling. The vet has given me a clean bill of health except that I have a cataract in one eye. Even so, I manage perfectly and I can see well. I am tiny and sometimes I am afraid of loud noises and other dogs so a home without dogs would be best for me. Adopt me and let's cuddle together!

If you would like to meet me please visit our website at www.bichonrescueoc.org and submit an application to start the adoption process! All our pups are available as long as their listing is up. The adoption process moves very quickly and most families are approved within 48 hours.

animal.description:
Tuspots is a beloved creature living at DCAS. Most individuals that know Tuspots love him for his impressionable quirks, his beautiful smile, and his goofy personality. Once Tuspots feels comfortable around you, he just blossoms, he wants to show off his skills, wants to give and receive affection, and he trusts you. Tuspots has a fun-loving side that enjoys outdoor adventures like flower-filled hikes or playing games with you in the yard (burying toy treasures, tug of war, and chase me are his favorites!). Tuspots has been participating in playgroups here and loves to play with other dogs. He also has a laidback side and enjoys resting on a bench and receiving all the headscratches and bellyrubs he can get! He will sit with you peacefully until you are ready to leave. Tuspots is a great listener, walks well on leash, gives great eye contact, sits for treats, takes treats gently, and has no issues being handled or petted by so many of us that have his trust. Sometimes it takes a handler a couple days to vibe with Tuspots and sometimes it only takes a few seconds for a stranger to feed him a treat and gain his understanding. It will always be best for Tuspots to take introductions and visits with new people slowly, because he does not always feel comfortable right away. Tuspots definitely needs a home that will understand his social needs. Tuspots is doing his best to work through his fears, and needs all the love and patience he can get. This boy has such a deep, beautiful soul and such a zest for life! Tuspots will make your heart melt and your cheeks hurt from smiling!

Meet him at Dekalb Animal Services, 3280 Chamblee Dunwoody Rd, Chamblee, GA OR go to dekalbanimalservices.com

animal.description:
Dante is a handsome Malinois around 3-4 years of age who is full of quirky personality and love.

Dante has mellowed a bit with his age but still does everything in true Malinois fashion with lots of zeal and passion. He enjoys meeting new people and is a generally social boy when out in public or at home. He has always been sweet and affectionate with new volunteers however he can also be vocal and demanding when he wants to play. He is generally more concerned with his toy(s) though and finding someone to throw them for him - if he can't find someone to do it he will do it himself. Asking for what he wants, or just taking it, isn't a problem for Dante who routinely swipes bowls or cooking sheets to play with at his whim - chasing metal objects is his favorite thing in the world and he cause of his very worn teeth. Dante has been living with a child who is very dog savvy and won an unsure Dante over but he has not been exposed to any kids under 6 years of age. We would not recommend him for a home with young children or children that are unsure of big, vocal dogs. Dante is a stereotypical Malinois who will eat the house around him if left to his own devices without boundaries and clear expectations. Although he isn't as intense as some Malinois can be Dante would be best suited to a home that understands working dog breeds.

Dante has been fostered with other dogs with no issues. He is much more concerned with what he can get his mouth on and not so much what the other dogs are doing. He is not one to play with other dogs as they simply aren't his interest. He tends to be non-confrontational and will even move to another toy if one of the other dogs swipes his toy. He is not submissive though and doesn't tolerate being pushed around by other dogs. He is a middle line personality in the play yard and has walked with dogs as small as 12 lbs (puppies) and large as 90 + lb Shepherds without issue. Dante does have a strong drive though and is NOT recommended for a home with cats.

Dante is searching for a home that will appreciate his quirky personality and keep him on track as a well mannered Malinois. If you're the home for Dante email us at Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application or visit tierhaven.rescuegroups.org for FAQs including adoption fee and process.

animal.description:
Bison is approximately 8 years old and weighs around 65 pounds. He is friendly, sweet and sociable. He is loving and embraces affection. He LOVES getting pets and head scratches! He is a gentle giant and very well-mannered. He does well with other large breed dogs, though he tends to get picked on since he is pretty submissive. He would do best as an only dog or with an equally sweet canine companion. He does well when taking walks past other dogs and hasn't shown us any reactivity. He would do great with kids and is very sweet with humans. Bison is wonderful with people and very welcoming. He may bark at the door, but is friendly with visitors. He is well-behaved and non-destructive. He is doing well with crate-training and leash-training, though prefers to explore the yard. He is doing well at using the restroom outdoors. He was relinquished by his owners who couldn't bring him with them to their new home. He came to us with a bump on his eyelid. It was removed an biopsied and came back negative for anything harmful. Bison is feeling much better and is a very good boy and will be the best companion! His adoption fee is $295 which covers the cost of his eyelid procedure, neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchip and microchip registration. If you’d like to be considered for adoption, the first step is completing an application which is available on our website, poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab. Please read the below paragraphs for more information on our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered.

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in, please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

animal.description:
Hi there, my name is Walter! But sometimes I get called 'Sweet Boy' or 'Big Block Head'. I'm a youngin with a lot of pent up energy. You see, I was heart worm positive and I've just been cleared! But that means I've been with my foster mom the last 2 months, going through treatment and I haven't really been able to release my energy. There's some things you should know about me if you're thinking you want to become my FURever home. 
 Firstly, I'm crate and house trained. For a while when I first came to live with my foster mom, she would put me in the crate when she went to work, until we got used to each other. Shortly after that, she began to gate the living room and would let me stay on my FAVORITE couch while she was at work. She would leave my bones and toys to chew if I got bored. (It's recommended to put your shoes up and away so I can't get them because there has been a few times I got curious. And any garbage cans should have lids on them or doors should be closed so I can't put any tissues or anything out of them). I can be alone for long hours in case you have to work late but 10 hours is probably my cut off. When we go on walks, mom puts me in a harness because I'm so strong. I walk pretty well on the leash but BOY OH BOY, if I see a squirrel or a cat, I can move fast so mom recommends you give me your full attention on walks so that if I try to chase anything, you can tell me no quickly. 
 As far as eating, I'm a growing pup so I get 2 cups in the AM and 2 in the PM. I only like to eat when my human is home so even if you left me in my room with my food, I won't eat it. I also try to drink all my water at once so it's suggested not to fill my bowl all the way. I only know 2 commands right now: sit, and paw. But I'm willing to learn if you teach me! 
 I don't bark often, but I can bark at noises outside the home and men when they first enter the home. I'm nervous about men so give me a little time to warm up to them and smell them. I can also be pretty skittish at loud noises too. It may take me time to feel safe so please work with me. I haven't quite mastered the going out thing yet, but my foster mom is trying to get me warmed up to places like breweries and parks so that way if you're social, I can go with you! 
 And last but not least, I am QUITE cuddly once I create a bond with you but don't be discouraged if that takes a few days or weeks. Once I feel safe I'm never going to leave your side. I like other dogs and I would do best if I could have a yard to run around in. 

Contact daviecountyhumane@gmail.com or fill out an application at https://www.davienchumane.org/adopt!
Please visit our website, www.davienchumane.org/adopt to complete an adoption questionnaire, or email daviecountyhumane@gmail.com with any questions.

animal.description: The shelter can be a pretty stressful place for any dog but it is especially stressful when being surrounded by dogs makes you anxious. And that's what is going on with Frasier. He is a total love with people, but when he sees other dogs, he becomes overwhelmed. He desperately needs out of the shelter. We have seen this behavior in dogs before, and we know that when we get these pups out of the shelter and in a quiet home environment, they completely thrive. When volunteers take Frasier to one of the shelter's tiny houses, and it is just him and his person, that's when we see the real Frasier. The one who leans into you for pets, who gazes at you with adoration, who wags his tail softly in appreciation of your attention. At 11 years old, the shelter is no place for Frasier. He is clearly confused to be here, and we don't blame him. What does Frasier's ideal home look like? He needs a home with a fenced yard to call his own. Frasier needs to be the only pet but would love to be doted on by a family - adults only or a family with teenagers. We have no doubt he will seamlessly become a part of your family and you'll wonder what took you so long to bring him home. Frasier has so many strikes against him: He's black. He's a senior. He's a pittie mix. He has some lumps and bumps. He needs to be the only pet. We need someone who will look past all of that and accept Frasier for who he is, which is a loyal and loving dog who deserves a chance. I weigh approximately 81 lbs. Click here to view my paperwork.

animal.description:
**This dog is medium sized around 50 lbs
Thank you for considering adoption of a Milo Foundation Sanctuary dog. Our Sanctuary is where our rescued dogs who have had difficulty in a home in the past, have behavioral issues, or too much energy, or for some, aggression issues with other dogs, or intense stranger danger that make them more difficult to safely and happily live in urban environments. These are not beginner dogs or for the most part nor are they for families with children. IF you are looking for an easy dog to add to your family, we suggest looking at the dogs at our Adoption Center, Milo Pt Richmond. BUT, if you can offer a safe and nurturing home to a dog with some behavioral "quirks" please do send an application today. Thank you.
************************************

Experienced owners only! No children. Ideal home has a yard in a less urban area

Foster notes 7/2/20
"Our family had the pleasure of fostering Crunchy for 10 weeks in the semi-urban environment of Alameda (East Bay). He coped fairly well with the stress of cars, street noise, etc., but we think he'd do best in a more peaceful/rural environment where he can also have more freedom. While he doesn't seem bothered by most loud noises, the exception is fireworks, which scare the heck out of him. (They became a nightly challenge for him during the noisy lead up to July 4th here in the East Bay.)

Everybody who meets him says Crunchy is such a "cool dog." We speculate that he's mostly black lab, along with a "mystery mix - educated guesses are Formosa Mountain Dog, Pibble and/or German Shorthaired Pointer. 

He is sensitive, loving and lovable in so many ways - healthy, agile, smart and super sweet to those he loves and trusts. He's a "people dog and we got very attached to him, very fast! He's fairly mellow and affectionate most of the time, but he really benefits from some freedom and activity. He seems happiest when he can have a good run once or twice a day, or even better, a hike! (He LOVES being out in nature.) 

He was already well-trained when we got him and he enjoyed receiving more training and consistency from us. He's quite a gentleman on walks, especially when using a Gentle Leader. He stops and sits at busy corners, awaiting permission to cross, and he's able to walk with a loose leash most of the time. The only exceptions: he gets reactive with certain other dogs (mostly large ones), and can be very reactive to cats and mailmen. 

Whenever we had the chance to let him off leash, he had a blast chasing squirrels and balls. Sometimes, he was mischievously defiant (not listening when called), especially when he'd been cooped up and didn't want to go back on the leash. (He'd make a game of fetch into a game of keep-away.) This is probably trainable with more time.

He also loves to play tug-of-war and chew - maybe how he earned the name "Crunchy. We got in the habit of giving him a chew treat every night, which seemed to help him relax. (He never chews or rips apart anything but his own toys and treats, and is very well-behaved in the house.) 

The only serious challenge we experienced is that Crunchy can get jealous and possessive - of his people, his territory and his toys/bones. This became an issue with our 25-year-old son, whom Crunchy seemed to see as competition. We kept them separated to prevent a mishap. For this reason, he'd do best in a home with a single person or a couple and no kids (even adult kids) or other dogs. 

In the right situation, Crunchy will be a GREAT companion dog and protector. We really want him to find "his person" (or people), because he's an amazing animal and deserves to be in a happy home! "

Crunchy is now at the Milo Sanctuary having been returned from his adopters who took him home as a puppy. He is housed with other dogs and does great! He is a gentleman and a sweetheart of a dog. He knows lots of tricks, heels on walks, and loves to cuddle. 
Crunchy likes cuddling, practicing his tricks, and long walks to the park. He has a heart of gold, generally very well behaved and so lovable! Crunchy just had a full checkup and found to be in excellent health! He is house-trained as well. 
He needs experienced dog adopters - only - who can work with him on his training. He needs training to work through his fear issues. He needs to be in a home that does not have children. He is making progress with reactions to cats, mailmen, and large dogs. But he does not do well in large groups of people and he has some mild separation anxiety. 
Crunchy needs to go to a home in a mellow, low-key area with experienced dog owners and no children due to his fear. 
Since arriving to the Milo Foundation Sanctuary, he has come to enjoy lots of socializing with other dogs. He is sweet with the staff as he gets more and more comfortable with them. If you think you are ready for some Crunchy in your life, contact Milo!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Clay County Animal Rescue & Shelter is located at 14400 Hwy. 45 in Louisville, IL. Our phone number is 618-665-3005. The shelter is open to the public 1-3 Monday-Saturday. Sundays we are open 1-4 to the public. If those times don't work, please call to set up a time to visit.

The typical adoption fee for dogs is $150. It includes vaccination, deworming , spay/neuter, heartworm testing on dogs of age and microchipping, which is now mandatory by state law. Some dogs we discount to as little as $50 due to sponsorship. Some dogs we ask a higher adoption fee, which helps us recoup expenses on heartworm treatment on other dogs.

All cats are spayed/neutered/vaccinated/flea treated/dewormed and microchipped prior to adoption. Cat adoption fees range from $60-$100. We spay/neuter/microchip/vaccinate and deworm all kittens and cats, prior to adoption. Our shyer/less adoptable cats are classed as "barn cats" and are free with a completed/approved barn cat application, which can be found on our website.

For updates on adoption events and more pics of pets available, go to our website, www.claycountyshelter.com or look for us on Facebook.

She weighs about 40 pounds and appears to have a little Pit Bull Mix in her.  She loves puppies, but is picky about which adult dogs she chooses as her friends.  She would probably do best in a home where she is the only pet.  She has not been cat tested.  She loves people, adores children, and her hobby is playing fetch.  She is crate trained and house broken.  

Hailey's adoption fee of $200.00 includes her spay, 3 DHPP vaccines, deworming(s), rabies vaccine, and a heartworm test (which was negative).  She is on monthly heartworm prevention, as well as flea prevention.

animal.description:
This is Nikki, a beautiful 7 year old greyhound/shepherd mix.  She came one of the sweetest dogs you will ever meet so long as you are a human! This girl loves people and demands almost nothing in return. Her previous owner passed away and Nikki needs someone to love her as much as she will love you.

Nikki is the ultimate companion and wants to be with people all of the time.  She is happy going for a walk and also laying on the couch. She does get sad when her people leave home, and has separation anxiety.  She has been at a positive reinforcement board and train, working closely with a trainer so she can understand that a large, comfy crate can be a safe place when her humans aren’t home.  She is making progress, but is still not a fan of the crate. Additional training will be provided at no cost to help Nikki make a happy transition to her new home.  She knows her basic commands and walks well on a Gentle Leader head collar. 

Nikki will benefit from daily walks, but is not particularly high energy.  She likes to hang out with her people and sometimes play with plushie toys. She will do best with someone who is home a lot that wants a constant companion. Nikki should be an only pet, no other dogs or cats.  She has shown aggression toward small dogs in the recent past, so a home with no furry temptations is a must.  

Nikki has been at a positive reinforcement board and train facility for many months, and is ready to find a foster home.  If you are interested in providing Nikki a soft place to land, please complete our foster application which can be found on our website:  www.roversretreat.org

animal.description:
Apollo is one of our special needs dogs who is thriving in his foster home. He is a super goofy and snuggly boy looking for the right person who will help him navigate some of the more uncertain things in life, especially meeting strangers. In his foster home he gets along great with dogs and cats and loves to play with toys (squeaky toys being a favorite!). Apollo makes a great hiking and jogging companion and has an excellent grasp of commands and a willingness to please (esp. if snacks are involved). He is crate trained for longer periods of time out of the house but otherwise Apollo is most content snuggled next to you on the couch.
He is trained and comfortable with a basket muzzle for vet visits, etc..
Staff and Apollo's foster mom would be happy to discuss Apollo's needs further with interested adopters. Apollo is part of our Sit, Stay, Adopt! program so that he can be matched with an appropriate home.

animal.description:
Bailey is a smart and thoughtful boy who absolutely loves to be petted and adored. He is a typical Pyr in that he will alert you if so much as a leaf drops in the neighbor’s yard! Who knows, one day you may thank him for the protection from the killer leaf :) Bailey loves a good play in the yard followed by lots of good pets from his humans. You’ll know you hit just the right spot when he is sitting up and starts to slowly ‘melt’ onto the ground. Bailey went through a lot in his first few years of life and as a result, he shows resource guarding behavior around his food and high value treats. Bailey loves his walks but still has a lot of work to do on his leash skills and confidence building when seeing other dogs. He is looking for a family that has experience with the breed as well as the time to dedicate to correcting some of these learned behaviors as a result of his rough start in life. Bailey would prefer a quiet home with no children. He is currently living with a small, female dog in his foster home and enjoys playing with her - in the beginning he did need a long, slow introduction period. Bailey is a handsome and smart dog with a gentle heart. He’s looking for a family that will truly understand him and help work through some of his fears. His foster mom says that with lots of love and consistency, Bailey has the potential to become a ‘model Pyr.’ If you’re the family that can give this boy a second chance at furever, apply today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can call 877-739-3582 or email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in me!  I want to make sure that it is clear, I am feral.  I was caught in a live trap.  I have only been in rescue for a little over 6 weeks and have a long way to go.  I still can not go outside but I’m amazing with pee pads.  


I have only let my foster parents pet me and still it is on my terms most of the time.  My foster mom is unable to get a collar on me because two hands near my face still scares me and I back away when I’m uncomfortable.  I retreat to my kennel when I’m unsure of the situation.  My kennel is my safe zone.  I am kenneled while my foster parents are gone at work and do great for up to 4-6 hours.  


I have made progress but I have a long way to go.  I know my name.  I do not know commands, obedience, and I’m learning English.  I have not been around children.  I try to play with the cats but they just run from me.  I love treats!  I love chew toys!  I love the occasional shoe.  I’m beginning to want my belly rubs but it’s only when I’m higher up then my foster mom.  I am still learning to trust her when she introduces new things to me.  


It takes me a day to warm up to a dog but once I do, I’m inseparable and follow them everywhere.  I would do best with another dog in the home to feel comfort and to keep learning.  I am food motivated! 


I am very excited to find the prefect forever home however I have needs.  I need a 6 ft fence so I can not jump it.  I would do best with another dog or dogs.  It helps me adjust and feel more comfortable.    I need an experience dog owner who will continue to work with me.  Please only serious inquires only.  






My name is Valora! My name's origin is Latin meaning brave, courageous and in Spanish means flower!

 
My journey hasn’t been easy.  I am feral and I was caught in a live trap.  This, along with new people and environment, has been very stressful - but I am warming up to my foster family and other dog-friends.

 
The last 3 weeks have been full of new experiences.  At the beginning of the week, I went to the vet to get spayed.  I was not a fan and was very stress due to the new environment, smells, and people.  The veterinarians did a great job!  I was mad at my foster mom and it took a day for me to feel normal again so I hid in my kennel where I felt safe.  The next day, I was back to my routine and hanging with my foster siblings.  My foster mom gave me the space and encouragement I needed to trust her again.  

 I have a routine down and I love bed time!  I dart into the room to claim my spot on the dog bed.  I share the dog bed with my foster siblings because I feel safe snuggled up to them.  Occasionally, in the middle of the night, I get on the human bed and lick my foster’s mom face. 

I bolt out of the room in the morning with my foster siblings.  They go outside and I go to the pee pad to go to the bathroom.  My foster mom thinks I will be outside soon but I need a collar on first.  I get so excited for food time that my tail doesn’t stop wagging!

 
Another JHAR dog, named Dixie, came to stay with us and I was unsure about her for the first day.  After some time and watching her from my safe place, my kennel, I got more comfortable with her movements and decided to meet her.  By the end of her visit we were inseparable.  We played and chewed on toys together.  

 
With everything my foster mom has done in the last three weeks and  giving me time and space to adjust,  I have gained her trust.  I was unsure at first but allowed her to give me scratches.  It’s been two days and I think I’m in love with scratches!!!  I have only let her scratch me standing.  I’m getting there and hopefully soon I will be ready for my forever home.  I can’t wait to get a lifetime of belly rubs!  

I am adoptable to the right environment.  I need someone who can keep building my trust and confidence up.  Someone who has time and patience to continue working with me and teaching me the house life.  I am eager to learn!  A fenced in yard is a requirement.

animal.description:
*	This is a REPEAT worth REPEATING.
*	This gorgeous girl is a staff favorite - that is NO DOUBT!
*	She is in need of A BREAK! Her name is Gracie and she is about 6.5 year old. 
*	She is terrier mix, adopted out twice and NOW has been back at the rescue 170 days post her training!
*	From her last adopter, she came back with defined triggers and HSYC invested in her life by sending her to training.
*	She went off site for a month and learned amazing skills that need to continue!!! 
*	Here is where we come to THE BREAK this vivacious beauty deserves...
o	The right person, couple or family willing and committed to continue Gracie's life-saving training and love her completely.
o	Love for a precious family pet translates to consistency, regiment and care.
*	She is ISO a home where her training will continue as a fun and joyful part of her life which could include the right dog friend but prefer she get all the attention she deserves.
*	Gracie's Joy: This girl is super joyful... She adores her walks, rides and adventures... She gets so excited her entire body shakes, rattles and roles getting her out of her kennel! 
*	So in a nutshell, HSYC is ISO that committed person, couple, family able and willing to continue Gracie's amazing training methodology. 
*	On a personal note, I absolutely love Gracie and wish my home was a little more calm but the right committed person will be so lucky to get this silly, sweet, sometimes rambunctious girl in their life!!! 
*	Call TODAY and make an appointment to meet Gracie at 803-802-0902 - remember to reference our website for adoption parameters.If you wish to meet me, please call the Humane Society of York County at (803)-802-0902 to schedule an appointment. Adoption consultations are by appointment only.

Please refer to our website for adoption requirements: https://humanesocietyofyorkcounty.org/adopt/adoption-process.html

To learn more about the HSYC, please visit our website at www.humanesocietyofyorkcounty.org, Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/HSYC.animals/, or on Instagram at HumaneSocietyofYorkCounty

Thank you for your support.

animal.description:
“BE SURE TO WATCH MY VIDEO!”

Date of birth: 5/2018

12/17/2020: Esteban is an absolute sweetheart! We think he’s possibly a Beagle/Lab mix and he’s 2 years old. He’s a cutie with those floppy ears and goofy smile! He’s extremely affectionate and he loves belly rubs!

• Esteban is very friendly and sweet natured. He likes soft toys that squeak. He also loves to play fetch and run around the yard with a toy. 

• He’s quiet when kenneled and seems to be house trained. 

• Sadly, Esteban had severe injuries when he was picked up by KCK Animal Services as a stray. We transferred him to our facility for medical care. One back leg was severely broken and had to be amputated. His other back leg required FHO surgery. He's doing incredibly well now, given how bad off he was. 

• WATCH HIS VIDEO to see just how well he is running now!  

• He is on Duralactin, a long-term joint supplement to help him going forward. It costs about $76 for a bottle of 90 chews. One of our veterinarians is also doing acupuncture once a week on Esteban to help him with muscle soreness as he heals.  

• His new home or foster home should have minimal stairs for him to have to maneuver within the house or going outdoors, and carpeted stairs would be best.  

• You could foster Esteban prior to adopting him to see if you're comfortable with his needs and if he's a good fit for you.

• We haven’t been able to thoroughly test Esteban with other dogs due to his injuries, but he seems to like the other dogs he sees and has casually met. We hope to test him more very soon. Any dog in the home would need to be a fairly laid back dog due to Esteban’s injuries. If you have a dog you could bring your dog to meet Esteban to see if they could be buddies.  

• Esteban weighs 57 lbs. He has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms. 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Babs is a senior pit bull looking for her own forever. Babs was roaming the streets and was picked up and taken to the shelter. We know at some point she had a human, but no one came for her. Babs is a big time cuddle bug and she's all about humans. She loves roaming the yard with her person and has excellent recall. Babs is very skilled at catching treats in the air. She would do best as an only dog in the home. If you are looking for your next best friend, we promise that this gal will be just that. Please see the pit bull requirements below and if you fit the criteria, send in your application today!

Pit bull & strong breed adoption criteria
- Must be over 25 years of age to adopt a Pit Bull, Pit Bull mix, or strong breed dog.
- Written landlord permission or a pet policy allowing the specific breed is required for adoption approval.
- A virtual home visit may be required. 
- Training or breed experience is required as part of the adoption.
- Agree to not take the dog to dog parks or dog daycare. 
- Pit Bull only: our values very closely aligned with Villalobos Rescue Center. Read Pit Bull Facts on their website (https://vrcpitbull.com/pit-bull-facts/). We will not match our pit bull dogs in homes who have not done their research. 

If you are interested in meeting  please fill out an application at our website www.gobeyondrescue.org/adopt. Our adoption fee is $350 and includes spay/neuter, microchipping and up to date vaccines. We Adopt in the SF Bay Area Only.

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

animal.description: We think little Maggie, the sweet 10 year old shih tzu mix will be the perfect quarantine companion for some lucky person. On her best days, she is a happy, easy dog to share your home with. On her bad days, her hips give her trouble trying to get out of bed. Maggie is friendly with everyone she meets and looks extra adorable after a trip to the groomers. Maggie weighs about 10 pounds and her favorite thing to do is mosey slowly around the neighborhood, sniffing as she goes. Car rides are no big deal for her. Maggie naps a lot and likes to be next to you on the couch or in one of her comfy dog beds. She will use a dog door to potty outside. On occasion there is an accident just inside the closed door when her foster dad doesn't hear her bark to go out late at night. Maggie likes to wander if garden gates are left open, so it will be important that she have someone to keep an eye on her and she will be sure to return the favor. We have spent the past 5 months trying to troubleshoot the various medical challenges that she arrived with so that Maggie can be placed in a loving forever home for the rest of her days. She has had a visit to the vet to clean her pearly whites. Her arthritis pain is under control with one pill a day (gabapentin). Maggie requires daily medication that reduces the frequency of her mild seizures. We are positive that this delightful little dog will make some lucky person very happy, and we acknowledge that not everyone is going to be up for the level of care that she will require on a daily basis. Maggie mostly ignores and easily coexists with the other dogs that she has been introduced to. She has been friendly when meeting kids or visiting with friends, though we believe Maggie would be happier in a calmer home without loud, young kids because her eyesight isn't the best at this stage in her life and their shenanigans may be too much at times if they arent old enough to be respectful of her space. Maggie is a good little dog who would be happy to keep someone company and enjoy a nice, relaxing life.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name - Beefcake

Nicknames - Buddy, Sweet Potato

Age - adult

Weight - 50-ish

Other dogs - would do best as an only dog. Could potentially match with a veru balanced, co-existing dog and a family that knows how to set boundaries right away.

Cats - He is OK with cats but would need to monitored and introduced with slow introductions. No aggression, just interested.

Kids - OK out & about but needs to child-free home.

Background - Stray from Compton. Picked up by the police and brought to the shelter.

Crate trained - Hates the crate. Would do best in a home with someone who works from home and a room where he can be left in a smaller area when you are away (only a couple hours a day).

Leash trained - Does fine on leash

Housebroken - Uses the doggy door, will also go to the back door and wait.

Eating Habits - Great eater

Commands known - Sit

Car rides - Fine in the car. Doesn't like to get in and out but when in no issues.

Bath time - Does fine.

Affectionate - Super affectionate. Loves every kind of touch. Wants to be right next to you at all times.

Activity level - Low, couch potatoes. Loves to go on walks but can't go far. Must be in a home without stairs as he does have hip dysplasia and 2 bad knees. Does great on Carprofen and he does run around the yard and seems to be pain free.

Play style - No real play style, more of a lounger.

Medical - He has hip dysplasia and 2 bad knees. He does not use a brace currently but it has been suggested that it could help him. These issues don't stop him from doing everything he wants to do though, but do limit his ability to be too active out & about.

Bad habits - Snoring definitely! He CANNOT HAVE squeaky toys or squeaky balls as he will guard them.

Redeeming qualities - Happy to see you always, gives you a happy dance when it's time to eat. He uses a slow feeder bowl. Doesn't let his knee and hip problems bring him down. Still trys to be the best dog he can.

Best feature - His calm loving demeanor. You can just see it in his eyes how much he loves you and how he wants to be the bestest boy!

What Foster Mom/Dad wants you to know -

He definitely needs someone that will be strict with him and lets him know he doesn't need to keep them safe but you will keep him safe. He doesn't let his hips and knees keep him from doing dog stuff but low activity is a must. He is a very smart boy and just wants to be loved all the time. Loves to give kisses. Will be right there with you for any sun tanning sessions. Enjoys getting in a kiddy pool and cooling down with you. Is fantastic with every person he meets.

Please consider sponsoring Beefcake with either a one-time or monthly tax-deductible donation. Your donation will help It's The Pits with day-to-day care, including food, vaccinations, flea treatment, treats and toys. Click on the Sponsor This Pet link above to make your donation today. Thank you!Complete an Adoption Application!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Houdini has come back to us unfortunately........in the initial first few weeks of any newly adopted dog's transition we recommend use of a crate to provide the dog a safe space and also in case the dog becomes anxious when alone initially and may chew or try and escape the home.Apparently Houdini was a bit anxious initially when crated so was left out of the crate when the adopters left the home, he was fine the first couple of days but then when left alone chewed on the couch , so is back with us.
His foster welcomed him back and he is back running and playing with his foster siblings, human and canine.

Houdini came to us from a shelter when his family didn't come for him. He is a gregarious guy--likes people of all ages, dogs and ignored the cats at the shelter !
His age is unknown as he was originally adopted as a stray ......his teeth look great and he has quite a bounce to his step so we estimate his age as around 8 but he could be older .
Houdini will make a great companion for nice walks and afternoon siestas :-) and BELLY RUBS!
His foster says he is a sweet boy and we will post more pictures as he settles in. He rode perfectly in the car, too!

If you are not yet approved to adopt from All Shepherd Rescue, please fill out our online application at www.allshepherdrescue.com. Our adoption fee is $350.00.

animal.description:
Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

This is Simba - He is 4 years old & 30-40 pounds.
He is neutered UTD on shots and good with other small dogs, mature older children and cats. He does need a fenced-in backyard does not do well on walks reacts to cars and other dogs.

Simba is a sweet, shy boy who needs patience, a fenced yard to run and a quiet home. He is well-behaved in the house with no chewing and potty trained. He takes a while to warm up for petting and is very independent. He does well with other smaller dog in home but doesn't seem to like larger dogs.
If you'd like to adopt Simba please fill out an application on the website
HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

Simba's adoption fee is $300

#fosterdog
#fosteringisfun #Fosteringsaveslives #adoptablesofTampaBay #adoptashelterpet #adoptdontshop #rescuedogs #Dogrescue

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Once this quarantine and Isolation period is over just email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt adoption, please fill out application at

HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com/adoption-application/

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. The first step is to complete this application, HeidisLegacyDogrRescue.com/adoption-application/

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

animal.description:
Hello SCOOBY!Super smart, sweet and affectionate. Scooby is a very young 8-year old German Shepherd Dog mix. He's about 45-50 pounds (medium-size), and if his precious pointy ears don't get you, his playful, clever personality will. Scooby came to us from a shelter in North Carolina. He once had a family, but turned up stray. Some very kind friends of his asked Maxx & Me to give this special darling the chance the shelter couldn't...How could we say no. Scooby's foster says he is a fantastic, laid back companion while she works during the day, a playful pup on his walks in the neighborhood and a well-behaved buddy for car rides. Scooby's a little insecure with other dogs so we would like to place him a home without any (we have lots of faith this will improve-he has a nice general disposition and no real signs of aggression). We haven't had him around children, but he'd probably do well with teens or older. Probably he would like to chase kitties since he's super smart and would regard them as entertaining...If you would like to meet this handsome fellow, please complete our adoption application: www.maxxandme.org/adopt-app<http://www.maxxandme.org/adopt-app>. If you are reading this, he is available, please complete the application and his representative will reach out to you.
Scooby is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Adoption donation is only $250.
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

Cheez is a 1-year-old Terrier mix weighing 26 pounds.  He was confiscated by animal services and was probably used as a bait dog because he has scars all over him.  He is just a big lovable baby but he is dog aggressive so he has to be the only pet.  He was probably abused too because he is so timid and cowers for any quick movement.   He has the most adorable almond-shaped brown eyes, a soft coat and adorable ears.  He is friendly and lovable to people. His adoption donation is $250 which includes his neuter, vaccinations, microchip.  He is heartworm negative and on monthly preventative.  He absolutely has to be the only pet and no children.  He has a lot of potential in the right home so please come to meet him.
http://www.aforeverhomeanimalrescue.org/Project/cheez/ 
We are only able to adopt within the state of Florida.  
We have a page on our website that explains our adoption process, and contains a link to our adoption application.  Here is the link:
http://www.aforeverhomeanimalrescue.org/adoption-information-2/

NOOKA is a very fun and sweet girl who needs daily exercise to help her release all her malamute energy. For this spry 8-year-old gal exercise is very crucial! She loves walking/hiking with a backpack as it gives her the little extra exercise she needs while on walks and helps her focus. It takes her time to warm up to new people and Nooka seems to favor females. She's not much of a snuggler, is independent and can be left alone at home for hours without causing any damage. She also loves her crate and sleeps in there all night with no problem. Nooka would do best being the only dog in the house and in an adult only home. As most malamutes do, she has a very high prey drive so no kitties or small furries. Nooka is great at telling you when she needs to go out to the bathroom. Her voice is really beautiful, and she is not afraid to use it. She loves to sing and be heard. Overall, she is a great girl who would be best in a house with people who are highly active and would get her plenty of exercise.
Approved adopters are encouraged to communicate directly with the foster to learn more. Interested in sponsoring? See our sponsorship information.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Interested in adopting? See our adoption proccess.

KANGA wants to be your adventure buddy! This fit active boy loves going places and being out in public--outdoor restaurants, walks, hikes-and adores his car rides! Kanga, once he knows you, loves giving licks and kisses and is super affectionateyou just need to let him initiate in the early days while he is building trust. This pup has had a challenging past and he just needs to know you can be count on to pay attention to his physical cues when he's feeling overwhelmed or unsure. Kanga has no issue being left alone for 3-4 hours and is happy to sleep in your bed or anywhere as long as he can be close to you. Kanga won't do well in an apartment setting with cramped stairways or elevators, so we are looking for a home setting for him with a secure yard. As far as other dogs, Kanga can be choosy so we are looking for a home where he can be Fuzzball King of the Castle! Definitely NO cats and young kids are iffy too. Dog savvy teens may be ok as long as they are aware of Kanga's "dog language" and can give him space when he needs it.
This boy just wants to love and trust somebody so badly!!

For now, we are being cautious about having Kanga in a home with other dogs. He has exhibited some guarding issues in his foster home with the resident dog so we are saying no other dogs in the home. Same for no cats and no young children. Our goal is to find the best home for Kanga and one where his chances for a successful adoption are high! To "sweeten the pot" John has agreed to provide ongoing dog training (first lesson free)!

Check out Kanga's Instagram from his time in foster @kanga_the_malamute

Interested in sponsoring? See our sponsorship information.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Tokyo is a male Hound mix rescued in Texas. Our veterinary partner estimates that Tokyo is 8 months old at the time of intake in June 2020. Tokyo is good with people of all ages and other dogs. Tokyo came to us in rough condition and suffering from a skin infection. But he has received the medical care he requires, and he is ready to set out on the path to his happy forever! Tokyo loves to be next to his humans and one of his favorite past times is cuddling. He is very sweet but is still a bit fearful of the humans in his life. He needs a patient, quiet home with very low traffic in and out or separate space that Tokyo can call his own. Tokyo will need a confident, friendly dog in his forever home who will play/interact with Tokyo. He is house trained and loves his long walks but is also content being on the couch and being snuggled. If there are children in Tokyo's forever home, they should be older children who can respect Tokyo's needs during his transition period. Tokyo loves other dogs, and is thriving with the basic training he is receiving. Tokyo listens well and wants to learn. If you have room in your heart for this special boy, please apply online to adopt Tokyo at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

Bullet had a rough life before coming the Haven. He was chained outside for the majority of his life and only saw people when they were bringing him food and water. He came to us with his nails so long and curled back into paws. Despite the lack of love he received, Bullet is a super loving boy!! He does a dance when he sees you coming to his pen. He loves his ears scratched and is a sucker for treats (hotdogs are his favorite). We've estimated Bullet's date of birth to be 06/06.2013. We've noticed that his hearing and eyesight is not the best, but this doesn't seem to bother him. Because of his special needs, he has found reading other dogs social cues a little difficult. Because of this he will need to go to a home with other friendly and patient dogs. 
Weight: 74lbs DOB 6-6-2013...All pets have lifetime sanctuary at Haven of the Ozarks. If they cannot remain with their adopter, they must be returned to the Haven.

Puppies under the age of 6 months - $125

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Bran and I am a two year old Staffordshire terrier mix.  I weigh approximately 50 pounds.  I have a sad past in that someone shot me twice and abandoned me on the streets.  Still, my love and utter resiliency wins every time and I continue to trust humans again and again. I can get a little protective of my food but can you blame me?  When you live on the streets, fighting for a daily meal it makes one kind of protective.  I just need someone to take a chance on me and show me some love.  I need to understand that I am safe from now on and that I will never have to argue about my next meal.  As long as you have some cash in that wallet to buy me plenty of kibble we will be best friends. I would also dig a comfy bed and some new plushy toys.  I am house trained, crate trained and walk well on a leash.  If you are deserving of my unconditional love please submit an application.  I will be forever grateful.  

I am current on vaccines, microchipped and neutered.

animal.description: Hi there, My name is Goldie! Thank you for checking out my profile. Here's a little about me, I'm 12 years young and still quite spry! I'm only about 65lbs. but have the biggest heart! I am currently working on my separation anxiety and also learning that I don't need to be in protective mode ALL the time. And once I'm comfortable with you I love me some belly rubs. I use to live most of my life outside and had to share, so now I'm learning to not be so possessive with my bed and food bowl when my cat roommate's come around. I'm not aggressive, just don't want to share I guess. I also have allergies and most of my fur on my stomach was gone but since my foster family keep me inside and bathe me my skin is looking much better and fur is starting to grow back. My foster family also got me a crate and I LOVE IT! It's my very own space and it's my spot when my humans run errands. I just usually end up taking a nap while they are gone, although I have been known to howl for my humans when I miss them. My foster family also lives on property and we go for walks, they even take me off leash so I can explore. I get to smell and see lots of different plants and animals. I never chase and if my humans tell me no or stay, I'm on it! They have also been working with me to take treats slowly and politely as well as sit before I get to chow down. I'm a star student! I know if I find a family that is patient and loving I will be the best companion as I am very loving and loyal.
animal.name: Goldie

Oliver is  SPECIAL NEEDS.  He is rear paralyzed.  He requires daily manual bladder expression.  He is a little moody.  He can be a challenge.  He is not for an inexperienced adopter or one who has no experience with paralysis and its financial requirements and physical requirements.  So please don't ask if you don't have qualifications to care for him.  He was taken to an open access facility because his family could not care for him.  We will not allow for that to happen again to him.

Oliver is a moody dog.  He can be super friendly or a bit nippy and introspective.  He needs a skilled adopter who has the time to work with him and his needs.  He gets along with other animals and will make a good companion for a person with patience.

Oliver is neutered and fully vaccinates and microchipped.  He will be getting a dental soon.

We are only able to adopt in our local Chicago metro area.  We are volunteers  who work full time.  If you are interested in Oliver please message us and we will try to get back to you within 48 hours.

animal.special_needs_notes:
OLIVER IS SPECIAL NEEDS.  Oliver is rear paralyzed.  He requires daily manual bladder expression.  He is a little moody.  He can be a challenge.  He is not for an inexperienced adopter or one who has no experience with paralysis and its financial requirements and physical requirements.  Oliver requires a special diet or Urinary SO food only.  His paralysis causes him to have bladder stones so his diet restrictions are mandatory.  His has had surgery for bladder stone removal and recent issues with stone recurrence which is now solved.  

He is an awesome dog but needs a skilled adopter with dogs and one with managing paralysis.  If you have no experience then please do not apply.  He is not a science experiment.

If you read this far, then you might like to know he is a nice guy that we feel had been harmed in his past and can get snappy.  We have found ways to calm him to allow us to break through his fear aggression. He is really a pretty nice guy but has certain triggers we believe from his past that cause a bit of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde in him.   He gets along with other dogs and seems to be fine with a new kitten we brought in recently.  We hope to get him a cart soon.  He has been vetted and has  his vaccinations,  neuter,  and  microchip.  We will getting him a dental soon,

He isn't an easy adopt and if you can't adopt him but wish to help by sponsoring  his care we would be grateful!  If you are interested in adopting him,  please email us at RescueTailsAnimalWelfare@gmail.com.  We adopt only in the local Chicago metro area.  We do require in home visits.  We are volunteers with full time jobs.  We try to get back to all inquiries within 48 hours.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. Here are some helpful tips:
•	All dogs listed on Petfinder are still available. 
•	Please DO NOT use the "Ask About Me" tab on this page. We DO NOT receive these inquiries.
•	We CANNOT move forward until we receive an application. Even if you're only interested, please fill out an application at mnpitbull.com. We will respond within 24-48 hours (M-F) after receiving your inquiry. 
• Adoption fees are as follows: 2-5 months old: $400, 6-9 months old: $350, 10+ months old: $250. This covers their Spay/Neuter, Vaccinations, Microchip, 4DX, Fecal Tests, and Housing Costs. ********************************************************************************************************

Tegan is 7 years old and we've had the opportunity to care for her for the last three months. We have fallen head over heels. If you don't have other pets, Tegan is the dog for you. She is gentle with people and sweet with kids. We introduced her to our friends' 6-month-old baby, and she licked his toes. She grew up with two kids in her first family, so she's great with older children too. 

Tegan is a strong dog - we lovingly call her burly babe. She pulls on walks - she likes to go after squirrels, rabbits, and birds, but her prong collar really helps (a perfect example of why Tegan would do best in a home without cats). We keep her on a short leash around other dogs, but she doesn't bark or growl at them. Tegan has some issues with her back legs, so we limit going up and down stairs and give her a boost on the sofa once in a while. We've been giving her a daily hip and joint chew that seems to be helping. 

Tegan loves to relax and hang out, but she also loves to go on walks and is very playful. Her favorite game is being chased around the house with a toy. Tegan is very smart and well-behaved. She is house trained & kennel trained. She hasn't gotten into stuff, including food, and doesn't bark much. We live in a duplex and when she used to bark and growl at our neighbors when they went to the basement, but all we had to do was yell "hey" a few times and she stopped barking at them. 

Overall, Tegan would be a great addition to any family. She's sweet, loving, gentle and goofy. 

Special Note- Tegan is on Proin for a leaky bladder and as long as she has her pill, there is no issue. It is about $50 every 6 months. 

If you would like to meet Tegan one on one, please visit www.mnpitbull.com for our adoption process and online application.

animal.description:
Bayard and another beagle sidekick were picked up as strays. Pleasantly plump at around 40#, Bayard was certainly well fed--so we suspect he'd not been on his own for long. After a brief stay as a county pound, his pal got adopted and Bayard upgraded to a room at STAF. His tail has not stopped wagging since, putting him in the running for happiest pup on the planet! (See video for demonstration.) Super friendly and calm, Bayard (est. birthday 2012) loves taking leisurely walks, sniffing everything in sight beagle-style. While he has passed evaluations for doggy daycare, he does get jealous and grumbly when it comes to sharing human attention with another dog. May be happier as an only child. Please check back for more info as we get to know Bayard better. If he makes your beagle-lovin' heart go pitter-patter, email us and let's chat!

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

Please visit www.STAF.org for visiting hours, a downloadable application, and additional information.

FOSTER THROUGH HEARTWORM TREATMENT BIO
