You see I came to the rescue with heartworms and have to go through the treatment to kill them. They say it is long and expensive and I have to stay well rested and not stressed. Can you help me get through this treatment?? The nice people here will provide everything you need to take care of me! You just have to give me love and my medicine everyday! 

If you would like to learn more about heartworm treatment, please visit this webiste https://www.heartwormsociety.org/heartworms-in-dogs

 

I am a strong guy that is going to need a handler with a dominant and strong presence to make sure I behave because I will try and get my way if I know I can.

animal.description:
Hi Angel world...I want to thank you for saving me! Even though I am a senior around 10 years old, I have lots of life and love to give! I am a tiny girl at only 10lbs. but my foster mommy said I could add a pound or two.

I am a dachshund mix but have the cutest ears that stand back making me look like the flying nun when I look up at you. I am shy at first and still take some time to warm up, but I really like getting fed on a regular basis and love my new, comfy dog bed. I absolutely LOVE my dog treats and take them with enthusiasm. My foster mommy has me separated from her other doggies right now as I have the sniffles but I am very curious to meet them soon.

I am developing into a sweet companion type dog and love to spend time with my humans. I am heartworm positive right now which means I will need to go through treatment before being ready for my new home. I could be eligible for adoption prior to starting my treatments and Angels will pay for my treatment in your home. I need a quiet environment without a lot of activity to keep my heart rate down. I also have a cherry eye that will need to be treated.

Once my foster mommy knows a little bit more about me, she will update my profile but wanted you to know I am a very sweet girl and would love to get settled into a new home prior to treatment if possible. Otherwise, once my treatment starts in about 4 weeks, my foster mommy will take care of me until I am ready to go to my new home.

Please let Angels know if you would like to hear more about me!

animal.description:
Update on Jester: October 2020 - Jester was recently diagnosed with degenerative lumbar spondylosis. What this means is that he has three to four vertebral joints in his lumbar/lumbosacral spine that are unstable and are causing bridging spondylosis, that can be painful to him, in order to try to stabilize his spine. Unfortunately, theres not too much that can be done other than getting him on some pain management medication to keep him as comfortable as possible. Pain management will be the primary and most effective treatment for him. This condition is not reversable and he will live with it for the rest of his life. 

His vet notes that hes pretty young to already have this affect so many vertebrae as its not typically seen in dogs until theyre around 8-10 years old. His hips and elbows came back nice and normal though. The vet said to keep him on low-impact activities as its in the spine and unstable so advised not to jostle it unnecessarily. Jester's potential home will need to take into account that he will not be able to participate in high impact activities, but being a Mal, he will definitely try. He will need special care and consideration for the duration of his life. 

Original Post: Jester is an approximately 4 year old male. He was originally an import malinois that was purchased to train for police work. He did not test out well and did not have the drive for scent detection or protection work. He was then crated or locked in a kennel for several years. This means he was not well socialized and has had some issues to overcome. He was then let out only to go to the bathroom. The people who would let him out would grab him by the collar and quickly close him in the crate. As a result he has a lot of negative association with this and is unsure with strangers who grab his collar. 

He has made a lot of improvements in his current foster home. He was not house trained but has since been learning house manners. He is not trustworthy to be left alone at home so he will need to be crated and Jester is crate trained. 

Over all Jester is a sweet boy who bonds well. He will test his handler so he needs a more experienced working dog or breed specific owner. Jester thrives under structure and schedule. He likes to know what will happen and what is expected of him. He will need a new owner that can continue to work with him on behavior modification. He will spin in his crate as he has been overly confined in the past. He has had vet several times. He is nervous at the vet so it is recommended to keep him muzzled to prevent any mishaps. 

Because of his lack of socialization he is nervous around new people. He is also nervous in large crowds. Upon meeting he may stiffen, lick lips, or stare. He may pace when nervous also. Given a slow introduction with people and time, he will eventually seek attention and pets. He should be allowed to do this on his own and at his own pace. 

He currently lives with 3 other dogs. 2 of these dogs are female and he gets along well and plays with the female. He does not get along well with the male. Because of these reasons it is recommended that he have a home with no other pets or only a female playmate companion. He would do best with a less dominate female. Absolutely no cats. 

Jester will not be placed in a home with children as he does not do well with unpredictable movement. His personality is more independant and cat like. He prefers to be people neutral. He has also had some minor resource guarding in the past, therefore, he is not a good candidate to sleep in bed with his owner or nearby. 

Jester loves to go on walks and hikes. He also is very content to play in his backyard on his own. His favorite toys are a ball and a larger jolly ball. 

He would best thrive in a home with no other animals, no kids, and where he will be provided with structure, clear boundaries, and kind but firm leadership as hes a sensitive boy. He prefers lower-energy households as too much activity heightens his anxiety and other unwanted behaviors. He would be best suited for a single person or couple who are able to spend a lot of time with him and work from home, are retired, or work shorter hours. Hes a good boy if given a chance but is slow-coming trying to recover from his time at the facility. He does not do well in a kennel setting. It extremely overstimulates him as it reminds him of where he lived for three years in a kennel with 100+ barking dogs.

Jester was extremely under weight when he was finally released from the facility. He has since gained 25 pounds and is now a healthy 75 pounds. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@madrescueinc.org

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog.

animal.description:
Name: Coco
Gender: Female
Age: 10 years
Weight: 6.7 lbs.
Adoption Fee: $150
Fostered in Slidell, Louisiana

8/5/20 - Coco had an appointment with the Ophthalmologist on 7/30/20.  He said she was a very good little girl.  His findings were that she has a hypermature cataract in her right eye and can only see shadows and an immature cataract in her left eye.  Her foster mom says that she gets around fine and doesn't bump into things.  They put her on two medicines.  1) Ketorolac Ophthalmic Solution (5 ml), 1 drop in each eye once daily which is for inflammation; and 2) Dorzolamide/Timolol Ophthalamic (10 ml), 1 drop in each eye once daily which is to relieve intralocular pressure.  

Coco is a sweet little girl that absolutely loves belly rubs.  If you rub her belly, she will fall fast asleep.  No lie.... out like a light.  This senior girl would make a great addition to a quiet, laid back home.

7/26/20 - I have an appointment with the doggy opthalmologist on 7/30 because the vet was concerned about the cataract in my right eye and wants me to get it checked out.  So, say a couple prayers that everything is ok, and I will update you when it's over.

Foster mom said that since we do not know when my birthday is since I was found stray, we are calling July the month I was born.  The vet estimated my age at 10, and I came to foster mom on the 5th, sooooo, my birthday is July 5, 2010.  I assumed that since we now know my birthdate, there would be a huge party for me, but foster mom said that due to this stupid COVID-19, we couldn’t have one.  I understand, but that doesn’t stop you from sending me gifts and emails wishing me a Happy 10th Birthday.

There are two other dogs here at my foster home and I’m cool with them, except when that female one gets in my face, I won’t back down.  I might not have a last name like her, but I’m not one to be bullied, so don’t start something that you don’t want me to finish.

I love all people, but since foster mom is the one that feeds me, I tend to follow her around a lot.    I have picked up a toy or two and played with them, but my favorite thing is belly rubs.  I will lay beside foster mom and will fall asleep with her rubbing my belly.  I have had a few accidents, but we have a doggy door here and I picked up on it in the first couple of days and foster mom said that I am using it pretty well.

I can jump on and off the sofa, and use the steps to the human bed.  I haven’t been scared of the bad weather we have had lately.  I do give kisses and will bark at loud noises and if my foster siblings bark I’ll chime in.  My bark is a little high-pitched and loud, so it’s a good thing I don’t do it alot.  I’m currently eating hard and soft food and love it.  Foster mom said that I am a sweetheart and pick up on things rather quickly.  The one that I do that she is not fond of is hump.  I am spayed already, so not sure this will totally go away.  Seems I’m not picky, I will hump your shoes, your arm, whatever is there.  She is letting me know that this is not very lady like and I really want to be a classy lady, so I’m trying to be better.

I’m learning to be spoiled here, but it would be nice to have a castle all to myself with parents that are ready to make me official and give me their last name.  I was in very bad shape when I was found and no one knows anything about me and my previous life.  So, even though you can’t change my past, you can help rewrite my future.  And once adopted, and all of this COVID-19 mess is over, you can throw me the biggest, baddest birthday party any diva has ever seen.  I won’t object.

Oops, there’s foster mom’s arm, gotta go!
 
7/7/20 - We were able to get Coco into the vet yesterday and she is estimated to be 10 years of age.  Her hair loss is from severe flea allergies.  Understandable since she had to have 3 baths when first found just to get all the fleas off of her.  She received shots for her skin issues and a medicated shampoo.  She will go back next week for her shots and then can have her dental done.  She was heartworm negative which was awesome to hear.  Her foster mom says she is a sweetheart.

Thanks to everyone who donated and had Coco in their thoughts.  We will keep you updated about her and will update her bio once we learn more about her personality.  Coco hopes everyone has a great day!

7/5/20 - Coco is the newest throwaway, hot mess to our program.

She was found on the streets in this condition. Attempts have been made to try and locate an owner, but no one seems to be looking for her. 

We will hopefully get a vet appointment soon to find out what is going on with her skin and to check her heartworm status along with getting her shots up-to-date. We are sure she will need a dental and possibly be spayed at that point.  We will also get an estimate on her age and get her weight at that time as well.

The main thing right now is to keep her comfortable, give her love, good food and treat her the way that she’s obviously not been treated before.

animal.description:
HONEY (blonde Corgi-Chihuahua mix about 15 pounds) and COCO (black/tan Chihauaha about 11 pounds) are a bonded pair and must be adopted together.  They are both neutered males, approximately 8 years old and have been together their whole lives.  Their owner died and they were left behind.  They are extremely LOW energy, do not like to walk on a leash and are trained to use wee wee pads.  They re happiest sitting side by side next to each other.  Coco has bad knees so walks very slowly.  They would be great lap dogs or quiet companions for a quiet home.

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Weezy was an owner surrender with three other small dogs. The wife had died. He knew they deserved better. They never left his camper. They definitely didn't have proper vet care either. We're thankful he asked for help. 

Weezy is a 12 year old female long haired chihuahua.  She knows her name and will run to you when called. She is super affectionate and her favorite thing is to snuggle next to her human. When she's really happy or excited her tail spins around like a pinwheel. It's adorable. She loves belly rubs and back scratches.  She likes to be picked up and held.  She will pretty much follow you wherever you go.  After she got comfortable at my place, she discovered her “bark” and will bark if someone knocks at the door and sometimes barks at people walking by if we’re on the porch, but it isn’t very loud and really kind of cute.  She gets along with my medium sized dog and doesn’t seem to notice or care about my cat but was afraid of bigger dogs at the rescue. The only negative is that she is not housetrained.  She mostly uses the pee pads, but not always.  She loves to go on walks but only pees during walks occasionally.

She is spayed, heartworm negative, and microchipped. She had a negative fecal. She is up to date on vaccinations, heartworm prevention and flea prevention. She's had several great exams. She had a dental with bone grafts. She will have to have yearly dentals to prevent the few left from further decaying. She will be required to go to a vet with dental xrays. We prefer Dr Hill at Maple Small. Her lower canine are holding the jaw together so they cannot be pulled. She had some teeth pulled. She is 6 lbs. Her bloodwork is perfect. Her adoption fee is $200. 

 She is located in New Orleans LA. Email animalhelperneworleans@gmail.com for an application

animal.description:
Wilson is a handsome 5-year-old! He is neutered, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and crate trained. 

When Wilson first arrived in the MLBR program, he had to be moved from his foster home because he was just not adjusting to, or accepting of, having a fur-sister. Wilson will do best in a single-dog home as the one-and-only dog; no cats, no critters, no chickens, no exceptions. 

If Wilson’s forever family has friends or other family members with dogs, we would recommend taking advantage of the fact that Wilson is crate-trained because meeting or playing with other dogs is definitely not on his like-list and not in his best interests given his prior altercations. He is perfectly content to sit-it-out until fur-guests have left the building though.

Wilson is quite content to be an only-dog. He loves the affection and attention of his human family. He has a little difficulty meeting new and unfamiliar people, but he does warm up if not pushed. The ideal adopter for Wilson would have a household that has less frequent traffic of friends and family.

Wilson can potentially be a jogging companion! He started jog-training while in his first foster home and did well. With a little bit of refresher training, he should get right back into the jogging routine without great difficulty. Walks would be very beneficial for Wilson if you don’t jog; at this point, he still needs reminders not to pull or exhibit reactive behaviors and is mindful when told to mind his own business. Wilson also enjoys yard-zooming, so a fully fenced yard (6-feet minimum) is a must, no exceptions. 

This special boy needs a special home. If you have that home, you’ll be well-rewarded with the loving companionship of handsome Wilson! Just click here to submit your adoption application – https://www.mustluvboxersrescue.com/adopt.

animal.description:
Berlin Mannlich T. (or just Berlin for short) is a strikingly handsome 9-year-old male German Shepherd Dog (GSD) that arrived at a Southern California shelter as a stray. On his arrival, t he had several medical conditions that had been neglected by his prior owner. He seemed to have spent much of his time outdoors and likely did not have too many comforts of a loving home. 

Berlin T. Summary:
- Berlin is a Male, 9 yrs old, weighs 84lbs, current on shots, neutered, house-trained
- Good with Adults, kids (middle-school aged or over), dogs (small and large), cats, and travel in the car

Because he was a stray there were little or no details of his prior life that we could directly confirm. There was one substantial source of feedback on his history, however... and that was Berlin himself. By observing his condition and behavior it does give us some insights. Without looking too hard we can tell that Berlin was likely an outside dog. We suspect this because the tips of his ears show evidence of "flystrike". Flystrike is an irritation of a dog's ear tips caused by biting flies. This is most commonly seen in warm weather areas (like S. California) and primarily affects dogs confined to the outdoors in the summer and fall. Flystrike is most often caused by the common stable fly, however, many other fly types are sometimes involved. The end result is that the tips of the dog's ears are somewhat scared and often devoid of hair where they were constantly being bitten.

The most pronounced medical needs that were evident when Berlin arrived at the shelter were the visible masses that protruded from his left front forearm and on his right rear hip. You can see these masses in his included photo and video collection. The right hip mass is the most noticeable and the forearm mass shows evidence that Berlin had been licking or possibly scratching it. The masses by themselves are not so alarming in a senior-aged dog since many of these turn out to be fatty masses or are otherwise static and harmless. In this case, however, the shelter examined Berlin and determined the proper course of treatment was to surgically remove the masses and since Berlin had not yet been neutered this would also be done while he was under anesthesia.

Unfortunately, what must have seemed like a straight forward surgery did not turn out to be so simple. The larger of the masses on Berlin's hip was removed without complication but the mass on his forearm could not be dissected away from the cephalic vein so it was only partially removed. Tissue samples were taken and did show that both masses were benign however so the focus of his post-op treatment was centered on pain control and surgical wound care. As these activities were beyond the shelter's limited resources a call went out to Animal Welfare Organizations that might be suited to assist. Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) answered the call and has rescued Berlin from the shelter. A TSGSR specialized foster home in N. California stepped in to provide his post-surgical and recovery care.

Berlin made good progress after surgery but his mobility is still limited. He loves to walk short distances each day and it is clear that he really looks forward to going out but he does have difficulty getting into and out of cars without help and his size can make it difficult to offer help. When he is at home Berlin is quite happy relaxing in the house. His main thing is he wants to chill with his people. He also loves his play toys and mealtime is his favorite time of day. 

One of the side effects of the prior shelter surgeries was that they left Berlin with a medical condition where he needs a little help when it is time to poop. About an hour or so after a meal he will likely need to poop and he will then look to his person to "push a button" (or really a spot around his hip) that allows him to successfully defecate. This may sound difficult but it is not messy or complicated. He also needs medications daily with each meal. 

The best home for Berlin will have a small yard with easy access from the house and a family that sees his abilities rather than his challenges. We continue to work on Berlins recovery and will update this bio as he progresses. He is one of those dogs that you soon realize makes your home a much warmer place just by being there. 

Please join us in welcoming Berlin to TSGSR. 

What's Next for Berlin T.:
Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will continue to see that Berlin is well cared for and receives all medical care needed for his well being. In addition, TSGSR is beginning a search for an adoptive home that will care for him for the rest of his life. Berlin will come to his new home with a supply of food, a cushy pad if wanted, and other goodies such as toys. 

Berlins medical expenses will be covered for the rest of his life by Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR)!

If you want to learn more about Berlin, or are possibly interested in providing an adoptive or foster home, please send us a message by clicking on the "Ask About Me" button. We will often get feedback or "updates" from a dog's foster home and as any updates become available they will be included here.

If you are reading about Berlin on Petfinder.com sometimes an available YouTube video is not listed. If this occurs you can still view the video by pasting its URL into a new browser window or tab.
Available Video URL(s): https://youtu.be/AsiMe9pA0W0

Saving one dog wont change the world. It will change the world for that one dog.

animal.description:
Mowgli is a very Zen guy who prefers the companionship of smaller female dogs. Male dogs do not bring out the best in his personality for some reason, but he does fine in a play group of smaller female dogs. Despite his size, he's pretty sure he's a lap dog. If you're not sitting down, he's just as happy leaning against your leg. Being close to you is favorite place. We've noticed he has some resource guarding tendencies, no doubt from going a long time without food or care. Our trainers will work with adopters to resolve this issue.

Mowgli was brought into Dallas Animal Services as a stray and his condition was deplorable; he had mange and severe hair loss and flies had eaten away all the hair on his ears. Since being with us, he's a perfect gentleman in his crate, waits his turn to go outside, but is not a fan of the outdoors, now that he knows and appreciates air-conditioning. Mowgli would much prefer to be inside and lying peacefully in his crate. He'll make a great companion for the right family who's willing to give him the time and attention he's never known.

She does have resource guarding issues, so she needs to be fed and given treats in her own space.  She was diagnosed with Immuno-mediated Poly-arthritis and has been taking medications to remedy it. She is anxious in new situations and will need some time to adjust in a new home (like any dog!).  She is a Pyr/German Shepherd/Husky mix.  She has the long nose of a GSD, and the Pyr double dews.  Her coat is shorter than that of a Pyr and has light tan spots in places.  She would do best in a home where her people are home more often than not and as an only dog, or with a calmer dog. Motto :: two “normal" legs, ain’t no thang. paralyzed is perfect. Different is delightful. broken back, clearly we can work with that. Incontinence, the world is her toilet :: special needs is splendidly spectacular & Murphy Brown Moon Shadow is absolutely magical fantastical.



---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Murphy Brown hails from the streets of MexiCali, Mexico. While her full background is unknown, what we do know is she was paralyzed for quite a while, surviving on the streets until a rescue Samaritan saw her immediate need and took her for emergency medical care in January 2020. Thus started Murphy Brown’s journey of healing in mind, body, and spirit and her becoming the dog she was supposed to be under her wounds and emaciated body. 
(medical) Murphy Brown is permanently paralyzed due to her broken spine at L1-L2, most likely sustained from being hit in the streets in Mexicali. Her rear legs are without use and they have muscle atrophy, making them small and thin, but she doesn’t mind if you call them ballerina feets. Without medical care or walking assistance, upon being rescued she had severe open wounds on her rear legs going down so far as the bone on her toes due to chronic dragging. Her private parts are well were one large lesion due to the friction of dragging. Since she is paralyzed, she cannot feel past the break in her spine, so thankfully she was unable to feel the wounds, which is a blessing, but also it means she could reinjure herself without feeling it. 
Murphy Brown in also incontinent, which just means the world is her toilet, and she goes where she pleases (oh, to have such freedom!). While she can do some business on her own, she does require a caregiver to express her bladder multiple times a day to ensure no urine is sitting in her bladder and to prevent UTI’s, which can become very serious in her paralyzed state. Murphy Brown can easily walk on her front legs (and by walk, we mean RUN just as fast as any 4 legged dog) and “scoot” with lightning speed. Precautions should be taken when she is scooting to make sure her legs and private areas don’t get too beat up, as the dragging friction can create wounds that take a bit to heal. One bonus to this is her added wardrobe; she has a rotating closet of fun bandage colors, Velcro booties, and an assortment of leg covering options to give each day a little more accessories. Like most gals, this girls loves her accessories, and the best one of them all are her wheels. Animal Synergy immediately recognized the need for wheelchair that could give Murphy Brown the freedom she craved. They were able to get her an Eddies Wheels wheelchair, perfectly customized for her body, so she can stand or off-road to her heart’s desire with limited weight on her front end. While her wheels are a complete game-changer, she cannot lay down or sleep in her chair, so it should only be used a few hours at a time at max. Murphy Brown being able to be off the ground, and run effortlessly, gives her the freedom of mobility that inspires her confidence and creativity. Her wheels are made for walking, and that’s just what they’ll do, but watch out because some of the days, those wheels will run all over you.  
Through months of physical and medical rehabilitation under the direction of Animal Synergy, this skinny caterpillar has become a full-bodied butterfly, flying on her custom wheels with a zest for life and adventure that is infectious to everyone who meets her. 
(Behavior) Murphy Brown has no idea she is paralyzed, and that’s exactly how we aim for everyone to see her as well. Instead of paralyzed and incontinent, Animal Synergy sees a light brown dog who LOVES exploring, playing, and with boundless energy. She is paralyzed and perfect, 2 legs ain’t no thang, and normal is boring anyhow. She can be thought of a super athlete, and if there was a dog Special Olympics, she would win gold to match her heart of gold. 
She has illimitable endurance and stamina. There are two Murphy Brown versions of “tired”, standing tired and mouth tired. Just because she is tired of standing, don’t be fooled, she still has plenty of energy to play on ground level, chew, destroy, make you laugh till your sides hurt, and find every pair of shoes hidden from her mouth. Murphy Brown is very mouth-oriented, and really enjoys a good chew toy, but she is a super athlete in more than just her front end, she also has a very strong mouth and jaw grip and lives to shred toys that companies say no dog can shred. As her behaviorist noted, she has more endurance and is stronger than dogs 3 times her size, and balls tend to die a messy death in her presence. Murphy Brown can walk miles in her chair and still have plenty of energy to kill a dozen tennis balls after a full day of exploring and playing. 
But who needs balls and chew toys when you have friends around to chase, fellow snouts to paw, and a warm friend to cuddle up with? Murphy Brown does everything with intensity, and that extends to play… and love. She loves with her whole heart and her tiny feets. She loves her dog friends and family, and does well with dogs of all sizes and temperaments, but does best when not challenged by another dog. Being from the streets, she ain’t no faker, she is still a strong, independent, alpha dog needing to project strength and control. With Animal Synergy, she has let the dogs lead her and show her the ropes of living in a home. She is genuinely curious of other dogs, and engages in play frequently and does not exhibit any “aggression” but does try and be top dog {maybe this is just at my house because I have a bunch of weak, fake-alphas lol}. 
For kitties, she has laser like focus, and while she has not tried to eat any animal friends, she definitely stalks them (cats, gophers, chickens, fish…) and should not be trusted to not try and take a small bite unsupervised… the faster they move, the faster she wants to move her mouth in their direction. While her breed is unknown, her behavior is all ball-obsessive lab mixed with street savvy, feeling good as hell, flower garden predator. While she is quite energetic, active, and playful, she is every bit as loyal, loving, and attached to her person as she is stealth killer of fuzzy toys. 
Murphy Brown only knows how to grab life by the front legs and give it all her intensity. This is evident in her vast happiness, her play, and her ability to love. While she has no separation anxiety and is fine to be alone for a while (with a friend or chew toy preferably) she very much prefers to be around people. She will love back harder than you could ever love her, and she thinks her fur is made of Velcro (it’s not) and her paws are made of butter (they aren’t) but she still wants to attach herself to humans and paw them into love submission (she does). 
Murphy Brown would do best in a home that understands her needs, but also knows she is not needy. She is consistently the happiest dog you can find. She loves learning new things, has no fear or reservations, and her only limit in life is the ones we put on her, as her body has no idea it has limits. She would do well with some canine friends because you always need a tribe that speaks your own language. Her ideal human family would be someone with a lot of patience, and willing to take a back seat on occasion and allow her to continue the healing momentum Animal Synergy has given her on the next upward and onward phase of her life.
animal.name: Murphy Brown Moon Shadow

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.LADIES, MEET WYATT. If you have been looking for the perfect guy to hang out with and snuggle with THIS IS YOUR GUY!!!! He tends to like women more than men but will warm up to men if they are willing to give him a few days. At first he may bark and act a fool but after a few cookies are given, and when he knows you are not a threat, he will be your best friend. Because of his anxiety, kids are not recommended. Out of all the fosters that I have had, Wyatt is definitely the most snuggly. He wants to be with you at all times and always has to be touching your body while he sleeps. If you work from home he will lay beside you on the chair the whole day. He does have some anxiety at first, thinking you will leave him and never come back, but that goes away once he knows the routine and knows you will be back.
Wyatt likes most dogs, but he is an alpha if he is around a shy dog. He probably would prefer to be an only dog, but he does fine with all small dogs in the house. He is OK with cats, but will chase them sometimes, so it's best not to have cats for him to annoy.
Wyatt is 2-3 years old and weighs about 30 pounds. He would love to have a friend who will take him hiking or running and play ball in the backyard. Because Wyatt can be spooked easily at first, I would like him to go to a home with a fence so he can't run off. He is housebroken and does not like crates. He loves to ride in the car. He is neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, heartworm negative, microchipped, and has had a 1-year heartworm prevention shot. Available through Tired Dog Rescue, Gulfport, MS. Fee: $125. Apply at tireddogrescue.org

Atilla is a beautiful boy with a sad story.  He was found on the rooftop of an abandoned house- no idea how he got there. 

He was skin and bones, with several medical issues that needed attention.  He is heartworm positive, but has already started his treatment for that, and will only need quarterly antibiotics and monthly Heartgard for a year before re-testing. 

He has a slightly deformed rear foot, but it causes him no trouble at all. He loves to take long walks with his foster. 

Atilla has done PHENOMENALLY with kids at our adoption events, and loves everyone he meets! He is a big hit!

Atilla does fine with other friendly dogs with PROPER INTRODUCTIONS.

Atilla is UTD on vaccines, neutered, and has healed up from all the problems he had when we rescued him. (With the exception of his HW treatment that will continue for about a year or so)

If you can give this handsome boy a loving, stable home, please contact us today! He is waiting for you!

"I know of no greater genius than the genius of hard work." My name is Turner and I am hard at work learning all of the things that will make me your new best friend. I am a 2 year old, 55 pound Mountain Cur mix. I am already house trained and kennel trained, and am even a graduate of the Pups 4 Parole training program, so I know lots of basic obedience commands. I am good with other dogs with proper introductions and would do well with dog savvy cats who won't be scared by my energy and playfulness. Human kids make me nervous, so I would not like to share my home with any of those please. I am looking for a lowkey home with a dog savvy owner who is able to keep up with my training and help build my confidence with new people. I love to run and stretch my long legs, so I need a 6ft privacy fenced yard in which to get some exercise, and an active owner who likes to go for runs, walks, or hikes. I will keep up my hard work of preparing to be your new best friend if you promise to fill out that application so we can get started on our adventures together. 

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard


My name is Smokie and my sisters name is Nicole but our foster mom calls her Nikki. We are a bonded pair of Chihuahuas that have spent our lives in a kennel. Now that we are too old to do that we get to find our very first home and we would like that to be together,  We are tiny as you will read and we are both about 7 years old. My sissy has some heart problems that require her to be on daily medicine but don’t tell her. She has no symptoms of anything so as far as she’s concerned she’s fine and we think she is too. The medicine will make her stay that way.

This is what our foster mom says about both of us...

Howdy!  My name is Smokie and I am a 5 ½ pound bundle of love.  You see, I have spent my life helping a breeder instead of getting to live the life I deserve. Now that I know what love and caring can be, I am livin’ the dream.  I absolutely love to cuddle with my foster mom, foster sister and resident dogs.  I follow my foster mom everywhere because I don’t want to miss an opportunity to be loved.  My foster mom also calls me Smokie the Adventurer.  I love to explore the back yard and have even tangled with a bee and won. Everything is new and I can’t explore enough.

I am crate trained, and mostly house trained. You see I never had to ask permission before so still learning. But if you take me out regularly and frequently, I will do just fine as I learn the rules. I will do best with calmer smaller dogs as I don’t see my tiny size as limiting. A stable environment with not a lot of excitement is best where I can be provided with all the attention I deserve.   I don’t know about cats, haven’t met one to know if I will like cats.

Hello!  My name is Nicole (aka Nikki) and I am 5 ½ pounds of pure love.  I have spent my life making puppies for a breeder so I didn’t really know what being loved was all about. Now that I know, I am making the most of it.  I am timid, but once I found out what being in a loving and caring home is like, I am thriving.  I don’t think I have ever barked for my foster mom, so I am really quiet. I am the perfect lapdog, I will let you hold me for as long as you want. I love to cuddle with my foster mom, foster brother and resident dogs. I am such a cutie, I even have a brown spot on my back to show how special I am. You can even find me watching TV.

I am crate trained, and mostly house trained.  I am learning so if you take me out regularly and frequently, I will do great as I learn the rules. I will do best in a house with calmer smaller dogs. A calm environment with not a lot of excitement is best as I adjust to my new dream life. I don’t know about cats, haven’t met one to know if I will like cats.

We have come to love each other a lot and if someone would want to adopt both of us, our lives would be complete.
animal.name: 5483 Smokie and Nikki

animal.description:
We would like you to meet the incredibly handsome, Mark! He is a 4 1/2 year old lab looking for a very special home. Mark came to us after living for nearly a year in a southern shelter. He instantly stole our hearts with his shy demeanor and soulful eyes. Mark was quickly adopted, but ran away as he can get spooked easily. After being trapped, Mark was relinquished back to us and adopted again. After Mark settled in his new home, he developed anxiety whenever his mom left her home. Mark was returned again and spent time with our trainer to learn more about him. Mark will need a very dedicated home with lots of patience. He will always be a flight risk, so a secure 6 foot fence is required for him. Mark would also do best in a home without other dogs or children. Mark has so much love to give, he just needs the right home to settle into. 

*We are closed to the public for viewing. Please email adoptions@pawstinleypark.org if you are interested in adopting Mark.

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please visit our website to check on their current availability: http://www.pawstinleypark.org.. Adoptions are limited to 50 miles from the shelter. We do not ship animals. Adoption fees for dogs are $125-$275 based on age. While we do our best, we cannot make guarantees on breed, exact age and house training of our dogs. Peoples Animal Welfare Society (P.A.W.S.) of Tinley Park, IL is a no-kill non-profit 501(c) (3) organization.

animal.description: Hi, I’m Onyx, a beautiful 3 year old girl. I was found roaming the streets as a stray so I’m learning all kinds of new things in my foster home. I’m a very sweet but extremely nervous around new people. I am still very uncomfortable and scared on a leash so a home with a fenced yard is a MUST. My foster mom says I need someone who is very patient to be my forever person.  I absolutely hate crates and will fight to not go into one and then will be very afraid to come out.  Once I trust you, all I wants to do is to sit in your lap and snuggle. At night, I will cuddle up to you to sleep. I start under the covers then during the night will get on top of covers so I can be closer to you.  Love, Love, love belly rubs…. I will lay on my back and sleep while my belly is being rubbed, then I will thank you with lots of kisses.  I am fine going outside as long as you hang with me; I don’t want you too far away at any given time. I enjoy my fenced back yard as I like to run and chase my K9 fosters siblings and squirrels so a playmate would be great.  I can climb a chain-link fence so I need a wood or a vinyl fence to keep me secure in the yard. Since I am still nervous of new people and situations a home with young kids is not ideal for me.  I’m doing Ok with car rides as long as they are not too long. If you have the time and the heart to help me be all that I can be please consider me for your fur-ever girl.  Onyx is spayed, up to date on all vaccines, had a heart worm test, on heartworm preventative, had a fecal, and microchipped. Onyx’s adoption fee is $300.00. Out of state adopters are responsible for arranging transport, WE DO NOT SHIP DOGS. For events calendar and adoption application please go to our website at aaprescue.org. A young dog is a 10-15 year commitment. Many dogs are surrendered to us because their owners are no longer able to care for them due to their health. We try to place young dogs and puppies in active, busy families. We encourage seniors to look at age appropriate dogs

animal.description:
Breed:  Dachshund / Labrador Retriever mix
Age:  1 yr.
Weight:  18 lbs.
Good with dogs:  yes
Good with cats:  unsure
Good with kids:  no
Energy level:  medium
Good with men/strangers:  yes
Hypoallergenic:  no

Special home requirements or medical:  bonded pair with Halo and must be the only pets; they prefer a yard

Additional info:

Halo and Willow are the perfect bonded duo! Willow is more confident so her sister Halo definitely looks to her for guidance. These little ladies are glued at the hip but love their people just as equally as each other, Halo is a little nervous and unsure in a new environment but it doesn't take long for her to open up and make herself at home. They are very calm indoors and you'll find them either sharing a toy at playtime or snoozing with each other, where one is the other is sure to follow. They are also pretty active in terms of the outdoors and love going on walks, they also love to do zoomies in the backyard so having a secure yard to play in is definitely a plus, they do bark at outside noises but are great at following direction and will stop when told to. They are good with other dogs but would prefer to be in a home as only dogs or only one other well adjusted dog. They are both eager to please, cuddly and learn very quickly. They are both so well behaved, crate trained and house trained.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ THE DOG'S INFORMATION CAREFULLY.  ONCE YOU HAVE DONE SO, PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING:
1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.
4.       To learn more about our adoption process, please look up our Adoption FAQ’s. - http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-faq/

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Gunner is a male Shepherd mix rescued in Texas. Our veterinary partner estimates that Gunner is 2 years old at the time of intake in July 2020. Gunner is good with people of all ages and other dogs. All this handsome guy knew of life was the short wire he was tied to in someone's backyard, without a human word or touch, suffering with no shelter from the rain, heat and cold, eating only sporadic meals and water oftentimes placed out of his reach. But on the 4th of July, Gunner's independence was finally won and he was rescued from that life! Gunner is now a Rescue Dogs Rock NYC pup and that means his life will be something to celebrate. Gunner spent his entire life watching the world pass by without him, and he is now learning how to live in that world inside a home where he is loved and cherished. Gunner will need a patient, understanding family that is willing to work with Gunner and continue the training Gunner is currently receiving as he acclimates to life off of a chain. If you can open your heart and home to Gunner, please apply online to adopt Gunner at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

Used for breeding and having never been an only dog an older male that is calm and respectful she may do well.

animal.description: Meet Freckles, the best friend that you never knew you needed. Freckles is a young, energetic Pointer mix who comes in close to two years old. Freckles will do best in a house with a yard, so that he can patrol and make sure all of the rodents have cleared the property. He enjoys walking, running, fetching, jumping and playing. He is active dog extraordinaire, so if you are looking for a hiking/running/biking buddy, Freckles could be your guy. It is recommended that Freckles be the only dog in the house, as his loyalty, energy, and toy drive can make him difficult to coexist with for other dogs. Freckles is also extremely treat and ball motivated, so perhaps you are looking for a dog to hide treats in the house from or you need to work on the shoulder strength with throwing balls all day for him. Freckles cannot be in a home with cats. Freckles is ready to be someone's best friend as he clings to his human very loyally, is he the right fit for you? If you are interested in Freckles, please fill out an application on our website, www.highsierraanimalrescue.org. We do not discuss potential adoptions without an already submitted application.

She loves to take walks and does well on the leash. Peaches is current on her vaccines, been spayed and started on her monthly heartworm, prevention. for more info on giving this sweet girl a home call 478 231 6942. P.O. Box 5014
Eastman, GA 31023478-231-6942
https://www.faithfulheartsrescue.org/

Our mission is to provide safe and humane shelter and to relieve pain and suffering for unwanted, stray and abused animals. Further, to facilitate the placement of these animals in desirable homes and promote responsible pet ownership.Faithful Hearts Animal Shelter is a 501(c)(3) public charity. Our organization was incorporated for the prevention of cruelty to animals and to eliminate the causes of animal suffering. animal.description:
Welcome our new orphan Flash. If you are looking for a sweet, mellow, handsome akita, Flash is your guy. He is an AKC registered 5 1/2 year old from championship lines, with a few points of his own no less! 

Our volunteers already love this big boy, and can’t wait to see him have a family of his own. He was rescued from a puppy mill auction where he had been repeatedly bred for profit. Now Flash is ready for his first loving forever home. He loves to go for walks, and he is an easy walk. He likes sniffing smells along the trail, greeting people. He shows little prey drive but is protective of his humans. He seems undisturbed by the presence of other dogs, so with work he might be able to abide a female canine. Everyone who meets him loves his manners. Hurry, this boy won’t last!

For more information on Flash,  please contact Deanna O’Brien at marsakita@sbcglobal.net or 773-594-9302. MARS has akitas available for fostering and adoption at several midwest locations. Visit our website, akitas.org, for more details on this and all our other akitas.

animal.description:
Nibble is a Pit Bull/Terrier Mix.  Nibble is Red and White in color, she is 3 – 6 years old and weighs about 65 lbs.  Nibble also seems to be house trained.
We got Nibble from our dog pound about 3 years ago.  When she arrived at our rescue, she was so thin and appeared to have been bred many times, by the previous owner, having several litters of puppies.  She either escaped from them or they decided they had enough puppies and dumped her. 
When Nibble first came to us she was food aggressive but not now.  She now has as much food as she wants.  She has gained weight, maybe too much, and is now a rather good looking young lady. 
She loves any attention she can get.  She loves belly rubs and hugs.  She likes to play with her toys and has a couple of favorites.  She gets excited when we go into her kennel to clean and play a bit with her.
Nibble likes to be loved and is very lovable.  She is great with people but not so good with other dogs so should be an only dog in your home.  Nibble would love to finally have a family that loves her and shows her she is special.  Would you be that person for Nibble?

animal.description:
MAGNIFICENT MAPLE

PLEASE READ MAPLE’S BIO FULLY TO INSURE YOU MEET ALL OF THE REQUIREMENTS!  We will NOT be returning emails to anyone that does NOT meet all of the requirements for Maple that are listed below.

Breed: German Shepherd
Sex: Female
Age: 2 year old
Size: Medium
Health: Good Health, vet checked, fully vaccinated including rabies, flea treatments, fully dewormed, spayed, heart worm negative (currently on preventatives) and micro chipped
Adoption Fee: $750.00

Maple is an 2 year old female purebred German Shepherd Dog.  She has been fully vetted including spay and is up to date on vaccinations as well as microchipped.

Maple had a very sad life until she was taken into AARF 1 year ago.  Her humans failed her by not giving her proper manners and self confidence to live a happy life.   Her original family did not spend the time to exercise her body and her mind and show Maple how to behave properly in their home. 

She has few manners and will jump up on people (especially upon meeting), counter surf, chew items left on the floor such as shoes, throw rugs, etc. if she is not exercised daily and taught rules of the house.

Ironically, Maple is excellently trained with her obedience commands such as heel, sit, down, left paw/right paw, stay/wait, etc. and is highly
 motivated to learn new skills.

Maple is very intelligent and catches on easily to new things and is highly food motivated which makes training VERY easy!

A trainer has been working daily with Maple over the last few months to brush up on all of Maple’s awesome obedience skills, boost her confidence and teach her how to relax and behave in an appropriate way with people and kids.

This girl is desperate for daily physical exercise and psychological stimulation. Maple LOVES to play ball and is easily exercised by using a Chuck It and a ball a few times a day.  Maple would be capable of learning any competitive dog sport such as Flyball, Agility or Disc and could easily be a running/jogging or hiking companion as she is very physically fit and has amazing stamina.

Once Maple catches on to how to behave and use house manners, builds some confidence and bonds with a human she will be an amazing addition to a lucky person.

YOU MUST MEET ALL OF THE FOLLOWING REQUIREMENTS:

• No children under 18 years of age
• Previous dog experience with behavioural issues along with obedience training/obedience classes/competitive dog sports, police work, etc.
• No other dogs in the home
• Someone that works from home/retired to give Maple her physical/emotional needs – someone who will NOT be returning to a workplace after COVID 
• Fully fenced in yard
- Must be 25 years of age and live in the Province of Ontario

If you are interested in adopting Maple please send us an email outlining your interest in Maple and tell us about yourself, your situation, your dog experience, where you live, your phone # and any other information you wish to tell us.  Please send email to deannaaarfrescue@yahoo.ca and we will give you a call to talk about Maple before moving on to the application process.

***Please note: we require a completed application prior to meeting Maple, who is currently living in the Owen Sound area***

AARF Rescue does not have a facility; dogs are in foster homes, vet clinics or boarding facilities.

animal.description:
Meet Winnie -

As so many of our pups - she has a sad story.   This beautiful girl was pulled out of a local pound in Cincinnati.   We won't go into all the details here -  

Winnie is extremely timid and shy.  She is not aggressive, and will cower if she things other dogs may attack her.   She does get along with other dogs when properly introduced and enjoys their company.

Winnie is scared of most things -  loud noises, yelling, traffic noises...

We are looking for a special adopter for her -  once she loves you and trust you, it is with all her heart and soul - and she is worth the effort.

She needs a home where she can feel loved, safe, secure and valued.

We hope to find her a home with a patient owner who will work with her and show her that she is loved. Because it does take her a long time to bond, a home with no kids, no cats and preferable no other fur kids would be best for this sweet girl.

She is an amazing girl and deserves a good life.

Fenced yard and home check will be required on this sweet girl.

animal.description: Sunshine is a 2-year-old, 50lb, Terrier mix.  She has had a rough 2 years but is on the road to recovery. The words that describe Sunshine best are:  Silly, happy, playful.  Sunshine would love to go for walks and explore the world of all those nice people she has not yet seen.  She absolutely loves car rides, also.  Sunshine is looking for a fantastic foster or a fabulous forever family.   Sunshine is heartworm negative.  She still needs to be spay once the vet gives us the OK in relation to her skin infection.

animal.description:
AT PEPPERMINT PIG ANIMAL RESCUE, WE UPDATE ALL OF OUR PETS ON A REGULAR BASIS. 

IF YOU SEE ME HERE, I AM AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION. PLEASE READ MY BIO BELOW TO LEARN MORE ABOUT ME AND HOW TO APPLY TO ADOPT :)

Meet Rowan aka Earnest:: 4.5 years old, 60 pounds, Neutered male Pyrenees/Shepherd/Chow type/mix.

Available for Adoption!

Rowan, who we are now calling Earnest, has found himself homeless after his family raised him from a puppy and he was loving and loyal to them for over 4 years before they abandoned him over their own neglect to provide proper supervision in their invisible fenced yard and had a very minor incident with someone who came into the yard unannounced. Earnest loved his family so much and he has been depressed and sad ever since they left him, with only fleeting moments of playfulness here and there. Earnest takes some significant time to warm up to his new people, but he does love to be pet and loved once he knows you're his friend. Earnest would do best as an only dog in the home, in a one person household with no children. 

$145 Adoption Fee. Please consider sponsoring Earnest's adoption fee by going to the DONATE tab on our website, here: https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/donate/

A $10.00 non-refundable application fee is required to submit your adoption application and will be deducted from your adoption fee if you are selected to adopt.

All Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue dogs are spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations, heartworm tested, current on heartworm and flea prevention, and microchipped.

Along with other criteria evaluated in the adoption application, a Fenced Yard is required to adopt. 

Please see our Fenced Yard Requirements tab on our website for more information, here:
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/fenced-yard-requirements/

Our adoption area, unless otherwise specified in their bio, is within a two hour radius of Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue for adult dogs, and within a one hour radius for puppies. 

Please see our Adoption Radius tab on our website for more info, here:
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/adoption-radius/

TO CHECK AVAILABILITY of any of our adoptable animals, please go to our available pets tab, here: https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/available-pets-for-adoption/

All pets listed here are CURRENTLY AVAILABLE.

ADOPTION APPLICATION INSTRUCTIONS FOR PEPPERMINT PIG ANIMAL RESCUE:

Before completing the application, please read our ADOPTION PROCESS tab on our website, here: 
https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/how-our-adoptions-work/

To complete our easy online adoption application, please visit our website at PeppermintPigAnimalRescue.org.

All adoption information and applications can be found under the ADOPTION CENTER tab.

Adoption events are held every Saturday in our thrift store from 1:00pm to 4:00pm. Please complete your adoption application in advance so our volunteers have time to screen and contact potential adopters.

IMPORTANT: All applications are reviewed in the order they are received and qualifications are based on best fit for each individual pet. A volunteer will contact you if you are selected for a meet with adoptable pet. Final approval is always made in person.

Peppermint Pig Animal Rescue is a no-kill rescue. Please consider sponsoring a pet or donating to our cause. Click the DONATE tab on our website to learn more about how you can help. THANK YOU !

For questions or inquiries on our adoptable pets, please feel free to contact our volunteer rescue team directly by submitting a Contact Form from our website, here: https://peppermintpiganimalrescue.org/contact-us/

animal.description:
Please note - - Fenced yard mandatory, established homeownership mandatory. Recommended no children under 12 due to his size and how agile he is and likes to jump up and run and play.

Meet Thor
Age Apx 12
Breed GP possibly Lab or Chessie Mix
94 lbs
Neutered
DOB 10/15/2009

A split with Thor's two legged guardians has left this very spry 12 years young boy in need of finding a soft spot to land. Thor's in excellent shape for his age.

Thor is a happy, happy boy and gets along with dogs big and small, cats and doesn't pay attention to the chickens.  He loves being a house dog and laying on a cool floor when it's too hot.   Because of his size I recommend kids over 12. or parents with kids who are used to large breeds. Thor uses the dog door is perfect in the house.  I've never heard him bark.  

He LOVES to go for rides and can get in my Rav4 and the back seat (floor) of my 1/2 T Chevy PU.   Thor would love someone who would walk him regularly and does decent on lead.  He likes for you to play with him with his toy duck or chicken.  His recall is good, but he does have a bit of a stubborn streak when he doesn't want to come back into the yard.   He does know sit, down, stay.  

He likes the water, but only up to his belly, not a swimmer.  He likes to stand in it. 

 He has no food aggression with his regular food, treats or old femur bones with other dogs, but is protective if you give him a new bone.  . 

Thor loves being with his people but does fine when he's left alone also.    He spent his entire life outside in a fenced yard and  now he's a house dog.  He has no interest going outside other than to go potty or with his person.  He adjusted to being a house dog right away, uses the dog dog and is perfect in the house and lays on his plush bed.  The only thing negative he does is jump up on the door when he wants to go with you.  

He just had his veterinarian visit and his blood work is perfect.  His ALT is very, very slighted elevated, but the veterinarian said that's normal for his age.  He does have an old CCL injury and occasionally favors a rear leg, but doesn't seem to cause him discomfort and there's no treatment needed. I have him on a joint supplement.

He's current on vaccinations and had a skin tag removed on the back of one knee.  His teeth are in perfect shape.  

If you believe this big happy go lucky boy is the perfect fit for your family, please contact us @ nutsforpets@yahoo.com or by inquiring on here and I'll send you a matchmaking form.  Home ownership and fenced yard required.  

Please note, if you can't tolerate a hairy, large breed dog who wants to hang out in the house and be with his person(s), then Thor isn't the dog for you.

animal.description:
Hi there, I'm Josie! I'm a 3 year old female GSD possible malinois mix. I am on the smaller and leaner side for my breed, weighing in at about 65 lbs. I may be tiny but I sure am mighty. I am currently working on my impulse control and separation anxiety, and I am learning that I do not need to protect my Humans ALL the time. With strangers, I am known to be protective and can take my time to warm up to people. However, once I am well acquainted with people, I am quite a love bug and am very loyal! I am an eager and fast learner, and quite active. I will do best in an outgoing, active family who has recent and continued experience with GSD's. And I'm looking for that family or person to contnue my training and socializaion. I would do well in a home with teenagers, but would not do well in a home where children live or regularly visit. Having another young male dog to play with would be ideal, as I love to play and can run around for hours. I will not do well with cats and other small prey animals. I'm great with dogs and love to play with both small and large dogs, but can be a bit overwhelming for small and older dogs as my play style is more malinois than GSD. I would do best in a home with another young, active male dog to play with. I am house-trained and will do my business outside, or will whine to let you know when it is my time to go. I am an excellent companion in the car and I will occasionally like to weasel my way to the front. When I want something, I like to come up to you and lay my head on your lap and quietly whine to get you to play with me. If I seem like the right fit for your family, I assure that once I am acclimated in your home, there will never be a dull moment when I am around. I will be a loving, silly, sweet, and smart family member. Could I be the young lady you're looking for? I'm spayed, current on all vaccinations, heartworm negative, and microchipped. Mimimum adoption fee: $400.00

If you're interested in adopting Josie, please copy and paste the URL below to fill out an application. 

https://petstablished.com/adoptions/personal-information?application_type=Adopt&pet_id=759194

animal.description:
*** Josie is currently in a trial adoption! ***

This pretty young thing (PYT!) is Josie, a 2 year old female Labrador/pointer mix.  She has a smooth white coat with cool black markings that make her very unique looking.  

Josie is a good size dog weighing 47 pounds and this is full grown.  Josie was pulled from our local animal shelter where she had been picked up as a stray and no one came to claim her.  

She is a very social butterfly and just loves to love on you!  She is a pretty active dog so she will make a great running/walking buddy to get you outside.  She may be too active for an apartment unless you give her plenty of daily exercise.  

We do know she is a CLIMBER and can scale a 6 foot chain link fence!  Yep impressive but guess we know why she was a stray!!  So she will need a privacy fence or always be on a leash when taken outside.  She has hound/pointer in her so she may take off after a scent if left outside unattended.  

Josie did ok with calmer older dogs but not ones that were hyper and got in her space.  She should be fine with children 12 and up.  She does like to gentle jump on you to give you a hug!  We have started on her crate training.  

Josie is up to date on her vet care, spayed, heartworm negative and is microchipped.  She is on heartworm and flea/tick prevention.  Looking for a loving, happy dog – Josie is the one!!

All HSWA dogs are either at our Dog Adoption Facility or in foster homes. All dogs require an appointment to meet.  Please call us at 205-554-0011 or email humaneswa@yahoo.com to request an appointment to see the dog/puppy and to check availability.

Visit us on Facebook! www.facebook.com/humaneswa

Our adoption fee is $75.  Read more information on our adoption process at www.humanesocietyofwa.org/howtoadopt.html.  Then, if you feel your home might be the right forever home and you would like to adopt a dog, submit an online adoption application. The online applications may not work on mobile devices. If the online application does not work on your device, look to the right side of the forms page for a downloadable .PDF copy of the application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Mini the sweet 10 year old dachshund mix who is waiting for a loving family who will accept her for who she is. She is partially paralyzed when she first came to us was dragging her rear end. She also was very overweight at18 pounds and should be more like 12. Since mid July in her foster home she's gone down to 14 pounds and started walking. Her walk is a bit funny and she occasionally falls to the side but can get back up again. She also can go up and down a couple of steps but her ideal home has no stairs.

Mini has been doing physical therapy and has greatly improved. Her adopter will get a special harness to support her back end on walks, an EMS machine to stimulate her muscles, and a balance disc to continue her exercises.

Because she is paralyzed that means she can not control her bladder and needs it expressed often plus frequent potty breaks. She needs someone who is absolutely understanding and is dedicated to giving her the best quality of life.

Check out this cute video one of her friends made to help her find a forever home. https://youtu.be/CF_jclLbNs4

animal.description:
I know what you are thinking..."she's not a Pyr".  Well, you are somewhat correct!  My name is Cynder.  One of my volunteer girlfriends decided to do a DNA test on me.  And then we had a guessing game while waiting for the results.  I'm not quite half Great Pyrenees with some St. Bernard, German Shepherd and Akita.  Who knew???

I arrived at AGPR early December (2019) and gave birth to nine adorable pups a week later.  After fulfilling my maternal duties, COVID-19 came along.  A lovely family offered to foster me and I had a chance to experience the good life.  But now I am back at the kennels because my foster dad had to go back to work.

We've learned a lot from my foster experience.  I learned to play tag with an energetic four year old boy (I even let him win once or twice), love my cuddle time with my foster dad, and enjoyed taking naps on the sofa and LazyBoy.  

If there is one thing that is not "pyrfect" about me it is that I like to be around my people all the time.  If left alone in the backyard, I'm known to escape and go looking for my people or substitutes (kind neighbors will do). So we are all guessing that city life would not be a good thing for me.

I do love my walks...my foster dad took me out at least once or twice a day.  And now I love when the AGPR volunteers take me out exploring.  My dream is to find a forever family with tons of time and love for me!

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). Since I'm special, we may consider an invisible fence IF you have demonstrated experience in training an independent thinking girl on how to obey the boundary.  If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org.  There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/  Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization.  We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Meet Benny (5Yr) and Digger (4Yr) They have been fostered together for 3 yrs. They are both potty ,leash and crate trained. They love to play with each other and other dogs their size. Their only fault is they are both timid dogs. Digger is a bit more shy then Benny. At their foster home they act like normal dogs. Once adjusted to a new home they should acclimate the same . Due to their shyness no one has given them a chance. At this point we would like to find Benny and Digger a home together. It would be more traumatic to separate. We think they will adjust to a new environment quicker as a pair. They need a quiet adult home with people who have time to continue their socialization. They are currently fostered north of Chico. 

Animal Rescue Recon makes sure that each dog is current on its vaccinations, has been or will be spayed or neutered, and is microchipped to help keep pets out of the shelters and get them back home where they belong. For more information or to schedule an appointment contact Animal Rescue Recon (925) 392-7654

-----
Please tell us a bit about yourself/family
•  What city do you live in?
•  Do you rent or own?
•  Any children in the home?  What ages? List all family members living in home
•  What is your work schedule?  Family schedule?
•  How many hours per day would pet be left alone? 
•  Where is pet kept when left alone? 
•  Where does pet sleep?
•  Any other pets in the home?  If so, what type?
•  Provide detailed pictures or video of your fenced yard - entire perimeter including gates and the bottom of the fencing.  Yard must be free of foxtails and fully secured.
•  Home check may be performed
•  If "meet & greet" is scheduled, all household members, dogs included, must be present

Most of our available dogs can be seen at Pet Food Express in Antioch on Saturdays from 10 AM to 1 PM

Our adoption fee is $300 for Dogs and $350 for puppies (under 6 months). The fee covers the cost of having the dog fully vaccinated, spayed/neutered, and microchipped.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
YES, WE'RE STILL ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS FOR CARLY.

**
Carly will be placed in the Phoenix metro area, for proximity to our rescue (home checks, follow up visits, visit to finalize adoption) and for access to our veterinarian. Sorry, no exceptions.

**

Carly's adoption begins with a Foster-To-Adopt arrangement that continues until she completes Basic and Intermediate Obedience.

**

Carly is beautiful, funny, and very intelligent! She loves humans who are lighthearted and let her know they enjoy her company! She loooves snacks and attention, and is an accomplished fetch artist... she brings the ball or toy right back to us in eager anticipation of more playtime.

Carly needs a playful, friendly, similar-size dog friend who's approximately her age. (Preference will be given to placement opportunities with at least one friendly similar-side playful adult dog - not a senior or a puppy - in the home.)

Like her cousins and her sister, Mina, Carly came from a situation of far too many dogs and not enough resources or attention. She starts out shy with new people, but soon warms up and shows that she is a happy soul who's a delight to know. She is an expert at the "submissive grin" (google it, it's a thing!)

Carly is young and needs adult humans who are home most of the time; she cannot be crated for long periods and she plenty of activity. (Preference will be given to adopters who work from home and/or will use doggie daycare.) Carly thinks middle-school aged children are a blast!

If you believe you may be a match for Carly, please complete our online adoption application.

"Companion animal" means, needs at least one other friendly, playful dog that lives full-time in the same household.
"Fenced yard" means, a backyard that is adjacent to and connected with your residence. (It does not mean a nearby fenced area/dog park.)
Gates must have padlocks and thresholds (cement or buried pavers to prevent digging.)
Yard and patio must be free of debris and have room for dogs to run and play *on a lawn and/or in a very shaded area.* Please do not invite us to your home if you have not yet landscaped your yard!
"Swimming pool" means a private, in-ground, year-round pool that is available to the dog daily or multiple times per week.
We do not place dogs in situations where there are "drained" or empty swimming pools, which are a fall hazard and contribute to the propogation of mosquitos.
Last and not least, we DO NOT adopt to students as we have found that they often do not know or anticipate where life will take them.

Discussion about a dog - including scheduling of a home check or other dialogue - cannot occur until we have received your completed adoption application. NO EXCEPTIONS. Thank you!

Archie had been dumped on the streets of TJ after he had been used as a bait dog.   When we got him, he was hungry, with bad skin and lots of scars and open wounds.  Despite everything he has been through, Archie is a loving, sweet, playful, dog who really enjoys going on walks and playing with toys.  He needs to go to a home where there are no dogs or cats and his person has experience as an alpha with large dogs.  He loves to play and will quickly bond with his human. 
 When he's on the leash, he's frightened of other dogs he sees.  But, when he's off the leash, he enjoys playing with other dogs.  Archie comes with an hour of free private training.  He would do best in a home where the children are over 15.

Archie is 3 years old, 65 pounds, has been neutered, given shots, dewormed, and deflead.  If you'd like to meet him in La Mesa, email me (NO CALLS), and I'll email you an application.

Meet Benji!

He's a 15 month old Lab/Hound mix looking for his forever home! Benji is all puppy and ready to play, play play! He will need a patient and active family to give him the structure and physical stimulation he needs. Benji is eager to please and food motivated and should pick up commands easily. He does well with most dogs after a proper introduction. However, he can be a little overzealous with play and will need an equally patient doggie friend. Benji would be best with older dog savvy children. We are unsure of how he would do in a home with kitties or other small animals. 

Benji will need a refresher in potty training 101 as he has been in a shelter environment for quite some time. We would recommend crate training to help with potty training and keep him out of trouble. 

Benji is neutered, up to date in vaccinations and on heartworm and flea preventative, Stop by and meet him, 9-1, Mon thru Sat!

animal.description: Meet Carmen. Carmen is a big, strong girl who needs to have a competent handler. She is a stubborn girl who does not like any other animals so the abilitly to be able to control her if she sees another animal is key to keeping everyone safe. Some basic training in 'wait' and 'stay' would likely help with that situation. She would do best in a home with a yard where she is able to run around and play. She enjoys the company of children and would love to spend time having them play with her. Rolling in the grass is one of her most favorite things to do. Although animals may not be her thing, she adores people and loves one-on-one attention - you can't beat belly rubs and back scratches! Carmen likes squeaky toys and all kinds of chews. She's not overly active but plays hard for a short time - then sleeps even harder. She likes to have her nap times and would love to have your company while she drifts off to sleep. If you are interested in meeting Carmen, please complete the adoption application (no commitment) found on our website, www.satchelslastresort.org, and an adoption counselor will be in touch with you.
