animal.description:
Angus (or Gus for short) is a sweet Boxer mix that was born on October 30, 2018. Gus is a very affectionate boy who knows basic commands and is potty trained. Gus does fine in a kennel but can also be left out as he just likes to sleep when his foster mom is gone. He is great with older kids, adults, and dogs his size (50 pounds). Gus requires exercise and a lot of attention. He is a HUGE snuggler and loves to cuddle in bed and on the couch. Gus would do best in a calm home with a set daily routine. He seems to know his schedule better than his foster mom! Gus has a high prey drive, so NO CATS or small dogs. Gus does suffer from some anxiety and is on a daily medication to help with that. Due to this he also needs someone home more often or q resident dog his size to keep him company. Changes are difficult for him so he would probably need a couple of visits with his adopter to get to know them prior to adoption.

If you are interested in giving Angus his happily ever after, please fill out an application today!

The suggested adoption donation for Angus is $350, which is TAX
DEDUCTIBLE, and goes toward providing supportive services to animals in
the home, as well as the high cost of vetting our dogs in rescue. If you would
like to welcome Angus into your home, please begin by submitting our Adoption
Application. The adoptions for all of our dogs will take place in the Omaha,
NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship
or deliver the dogs. If you would like to learn more about Muddy Paws
Second Chance Rescue, or donate to our dogs, please visit our website at
MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com. We invite you to visit our Facebook
Page, and when you visit, please don't forget to Like our Facebook page so
that you wont miss any information about our dogs and events!

animal.description:
Our girl Jocelyn cannot catch a break 

She came into our care in December of 2019 with a wound on her head and one on her leg. The head wound was from a dog and the leg wound was from a gun shot. We initially thought she would have to have her leg amputated, but she was able to keep it. Then she tested heartworm positive.

Jocelyn went through heartworm treatment and spent some time in several different foster homes and is now back at the shelter. Sadly, she has tested positive again for heartworms and will have her first injection after a month of doxycycline. 

She is THE sweetest dog who just wants to cuddle with her people. 

Jocelyn is looking for an experienced foster who has a quiet house and fenced-in yard where she can go out for short potty breaks during her treatment. She is reactive to other dogs, so a low-traffic neighborhood is best. She is also available for adoption. We will continue to treat her heartworms post-adoption.

3 y/o, 60 pounds, S U R V I V O R
Dogs: no
Cats: no
Kids: 12+

ARCBCR is a 501(c)3 organization making your donation eligible as a tax deduction. 

PLEASE NOTE THAT WE DO NOT DO MEET AND GREETS UNTIL AN APPLICATION HAS BEEN SUBMITTED, PROCESSED AND APPROVED. 

Adoption Application: http://www.arcbcr.org/apply-to-adopt/Adoption 

This handsome 3.5 year  guy is Ollie! Also known as Oliver when he is up to no good, which is only a few times a week. True to his aussie self, he is very energetic but loves his down time too. He is very smart, loves swimming, hiking, and jogging. He fears other dogs when he’s on a leash and is reactive if dogs (especially unleashed dogs) or people come running up to him. We have made great improvements on this and he is able to enjoy most of his walks with no issues. His favorite way to get his energy out is by playing frisbee in the yard. He has made plenty of dog friends but they are typically introduced off leash in a yard.

 Ollie is very cuddly once he gets his energy out and his favorite seat in the house is typically my lap. He is uncertain of new people and takes a while to warm up. Ollie needs a little time and space to allow him to meet new people on his own terms. Once he warms up to you, all he wants is to be pet!

He’s interested in what his people are doing and usually wants to be in on the action. He is crate trained and content to hang out in his crate for a few hours if needed. He is not a big chewer and has been left out of the crate in the house for a few hours with no issues.

Ollie’s ideal home is with an experienced herding dog owner where he can be given lots of attention or a job (mental stimulation), plenty of physical exercise, large fenced yard with space to run, no small children (older teenagers are okay) and a calm household without a lot of visitors. Ollie would love to have dogs to play with in his new home.

If you would like more information about Ollie you can email carlsocaro@gmail.com or apply to adopt below

Her favorite thing to do is play fetch. Although she isn't small enough to be considered a lap dog, she feels very differently about that when you sit down.
Mitzi is around 7 months old and is a ball of energy! She loves playing with other dogs. Mitzi is her foster family's shadow and loves to be by their side. Mitzi loves to cuddle and snuggle under the covers at bedtime. Looking to add two loving, playful pups into your home, then look no further! Marge & Mitzi are waiting for you! Apply to adopt these two sweethearts today!! Marge & Mitzi's adoption fee is $350. They are up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, spayed, and microchipped.
All of our dogs are spayed or neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped and if over 6 months of age, heartworm tested and on heartworm preventative in their foster home.

We require an approved application to meet any of our dogs. We do not have a shelter location and will not arrange a meeting without an approved application.

We strive to make sure the bios provided for our dogs are complete and accurate; we do understand that mistakes happen, however, so if you absolutely cannot find the answer to your question in the dog's bio, you can contact us for more information.

We require a home visit for each dog we adopt out, so we adopt within a 2 hour radius of Dayton, OH. If you are outside of this radius, we encourage you to contact your local rescue or shelter.

animal.description: Are you looking for the champion cuddler? Do you want a super-smart dog who's a total people pleaser? How about the goofiest little pittiepotamus anyone has ever laid eyes on? If you answered 'yes' to any of the above, Hattie may just be the dog for you. Hattie loves people so, so much! Young or old, it doesn't matter to her. She loves to give out her signature Hattie Hugs: placing her front legs on your waist or shoulders and just standing there, soaking in the cuddles. Because of this, she may be too strong for a toddler. Anyone else is just fine! She's very tolerant, and doesn't snap or growl even if you take her favorite toy from right under her nose or hold her on her back like a baby. She's just glad to be included. Hattie is very much a couch dog, but she loves to go sniff around the great outdoors, too. Yeah, she's a bit of a diva, and will dramatically drop to the ground when she gets hot. Don't worry about that, though, because she forgets all about that sass when she's in an interesting environment with new people, dogs, sights, or smells. Speaking of dogs, Hattie would like to be an only dog, please! She's not a huge fan of cats, either- we can't blame her, they just taunt her for being on a leash! Hattie thinks that's just rude. Miss Hattie already knows sit, down, and roll over, and she'd love to show off her tricks to you- or just give you alllll the kisses. Whichever you prefer, she's down either way. Hattie weighs approximately 50 lbs. Click here to view my paperwork.

animal.description:
Max is a healthy 10-year-old with a sad, lonely past, and he's ready for a future full of companionship. Max was a backyard dog, then he was surrendered to a shelter where he was in danger, and now he lives in a boarding kennel. Despite his tough life, Max is a happy guy. He takes just a little time to warm up to new people, and then he is a good friend. He likes being with his person, but he's also fine by himself. He loves tennis balls, watching for squirrels and lizards, hanging out on the couch or in the kitchen, and splashing in any kind of water. 

Max needs to be an only pet, and he's such good company, he's the only pet you'll need. He would like a home with a fenced yard, please, and someone who has a soft spot for a senior dog who is ready to retire in comfort.

animal.description:
Introducing Colt!

Colt was saved from a Craigs List post along with Sally. Colt is a beautiful 70 lb, 2.5-year-old mix with eyes to melt your heart. He loves spending time with people and playing with his toys. He could spend all day napping in bed with you but also loves any opportunity to run around and play fetch! He's housebroken, well-mannered and an extremely gentle pup.

Colt does well with other dogs and cats, and he loves kids. He seems to be a little slow warming up to men, but once he gets used to you and you give him some love, then you'll be best friends! Just spend five minutes with him and you're guaranteed to fall in love with his sweet smile and goofy personality. Before coming to Heidi's Legacy, Colt and another dog were found in inhospitable conditions, which lead to some hair loss along his lower back. It's all grown back now, and he's got a nice soft coat perfect for petting!

Colt had surgery on his back knee, but he's now cleared to get back to running and playing like usual. He may get tired a little quickly or need to take breaks, but soon he'll be fully back to his fun loving, adventurous self! Colt is ready to find his forever home. He'd be a great buddy to go on nature walks, tag along on car rides, keep you company working from home, or cuddle up in bed all night. Let him show you his 10/10 cuddle skills!

Colt's adoption fee is $300 - Obedience training is required after adoption
Obedience training is required to adopt.

Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Once this quarantine and Isolation period is over just email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt adoption, please fill out application at

HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com/adoption-application/

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. The first step is to complete this application, HeidisLegacyDogrRescue.com/adoption-application/

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

animal.description:
Nora was captured in a live animal trap set out to catch another dog in the area who was injured in July of 2020. We estimate she was born in February of 2019.   She came into rescue unsocialized, scared and emaciated when she was found in a rural area.   Nora does best with male dogs.  She loves to romp,  play and run with them.  She is unproven with cats. She has grown to love human attention, and seeks you out for hugs and loves to give "the paw."  Nora will need to be fed separately from other dogs, she can be food protective, not uncommon in this breed or dogs that were not fed on a regular basis.  We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are no t as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 12 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Nora will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

Vinny is the classic example of "gentle giant."  This sweet boy weighs in at 77 pounds, and if invited, would love to be a lap dog!  

Although he was a stray, Vinny has quickly claimed the hearts of staff and volunteers with his even temperament and happy disposition.  In the yard, he will chase toys (although he doesn't return them yet), lean in for a quick pet, or investigate new scents.  His favorite thing, though is take a quick dip in the baby pool or stand under the hose,  Vinny has good leash skills and is building his stamina for longer walks. Although Vinny is very social and enjoys people he is a loyal companion, therefore a single adult home would be best.

animal.description:
BONDED PAIR

IN NEED OF LOCAL FOSTER OR ADOPTER/ AVAILABLE FOR FOSTER TO ADOPT FOR LOCAL ADOPTERS

Meet Rachel (right) and Tonya (left)! Here is their video (more to come):
https://youtu.be/cpKqn2dtsxU

Rachel is 2 years old (to be verified) (approx. DOB 6-17-18), female, 54 lbs., vetted, is or will be spayed, and micro-chipped.

Tonya we believe is also about 2 years old (to be verified) (approx. DOB 6-17-18), female, 60 lbs., vetted, is or will be spayed, and micro-chipped.

Rachel and Tonya were found homeless after being dumped off in a rural heavily wooded area. They were loaded with ticks and had porcupine quills around their mouth. they would do best in a home with a yard and outside of a City environment (no apartments please). They are being fostered in a more rural area and have been doing very well. Rachel and Tonya's ideal home is one that is active and experienced to help them with training, they are both very smart. No cats as they do demonstrate a prey drive and a home without very young children would be ideal as they do jump. A secure fenced in yard would be ideal as these girls love to run and play! Stay tuned for more information as Rachel and Tonya are a new rescues!

If you are interested in fostering or adopting Rachel and Tonya please fill out an Application at www.Passion-4-Paws.org (please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out their Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

PLEASE NOTE: Because it will take some time to help these girls become comfortable in their new home we will only be accepting applications from the Sequim area. Thank you.

Dany and Catelyn are a bonded mother/daughter pair that we rescued from a hoarding situation in May 2019. It's been a long journey for these two, but they are ready to go to a forever home that will continue building their trust and confidence.

Dany is our beautiful merle mama dog. She continues to be shy and timid, but now walks on a leash and will allow you to pet and brush her. She is just the sweetest girl, and we want her to have a safe, loving forever home.

Catelyn is a little spitfire. She is wicked smart, very curious, loves to play in the water and is an excellent escape artist. She's playful and loves going on walks with Dany. This girl will bring lots of joy and laughter to your life.

These two absolutely must have a securely fenced yard to run and play in. They will run if they escape. They need a quiet home with no other dogs, no cats and no children. 

Our dogs are fed a nutrient rich dog food named NutriSource.  Our experience is a high quality dog food keeps vet bills down and well-being high.

If you have any questions please email: claudiaatwag@gmail.com

Visit our website to fill out an Adoption Application  http://www.wagsequimwa.com

Adoption donation fee $500 for the pair. (Please understand this adoption donation goes towards helping all the dogs we rescue)

Shemp is a good dog that needs and lives for his person. Although he watches for his previous owner, unfortunately, Shemp's person never came for him. animal.description:
Spot is a beautiful 2 1/2 year old pitt/heeler mix.   He weighs approx 50 lbs.   He is a big teddy bear and loves to run and play with other pups and humans.  Spot especially loves kids.  He is kennel and leash trained.  Spot is quiet and funny.  He can also be a bit clumsy and very playful.     Every kid needs a dog named "Spot" and it's easy to see where his name comes from.  He's solid white (except for an occasional black "ticking" of a cattle dog on his undercoat) but he's got an angel kisson the top of his head that shows up as a black "Spot".   He is super cute! . 

Like most rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).    All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

animal.description:
Juno is amazing.  She loves to sunbathe and absolutely LIVES for her daily walks. She's such a sweet, good girl and loves giving kisses and getting belly rubs. She's so loyal and would truly make the best one-on-one or two-on-one companion. She has some anxiety when she is in chaotic, busy environments where there is a lot going on and gets nervous when she feels surrounded or overwhelmed, and loud noises tend to scare her.  But when she’s at home, all of that goes away.
 
Juno has had some fear aggression with other dogs, and so she needs to be the only animal in the home. She shared a home and played well with other dogs for 6 years and there were no majors incidents, but there was a fairly bad situation last year that led to her needing to be separated from her four-legged brother, and while she is being cared for where she's at now, she is not getting the love she truly deserves. Because it's unclear what caused the issue, she needs to be the only dog in the home for everyone's safety. She has never shown aggression towards a human, but given her anxiety and the fact that kids tend to do the unexpected :), it would be better if she is not in a home with children either.
 
Juno is so loving and low-maintenance. She's not all that interested in toys and doesn't have the need for constant attention (though she'll take it if you're giving it!). She's happy just being able to run around outside and chase squirrels. She also loves to just lean on you and be petted for hours if you want her to, especially if you rub her belly! She's great on a leash, knows basic commands like sit, paw, lay down, come (usually lol) and is super smart. She is house broken and is fine being left alone loose in the house. The ideal home for Juno is one with one or two adults who live a low-key life, have the time and energy to take her on walks most days, and really just want a four-legged companion to have as their family.

animal.description:
This girl with the loveliest smile is our precious Cake, and she is looking for a furever family of her own. This gorgeous Pyr girl specializes in cuddling, and she even comes with the softest fur that is pyrfect for snuggling! Cake is a very polite girl, she takes treats ever so delicately that it is adorable to watch. Although Cake gets along well with other dogs, we think this beautiful girl will also thrive as an only dog where she can take things at her own pace, and enjoy all the love her people can give. Her favorite activities are hanging out with her favorite people, and going on walks around the neighborhood. Cake is a rather shy girl, and she is very cautious about new people. However, if you are patient during your first few weeks in her new home by giving her the time and space to process things on her own terms, you will be surprised by the lovely transformation. Once she gets to know and trust you, she is the most affectionate, loyal, and loving pooch you have ever met!  As long as you are willing to spend some quality time with her every day, she is rather content with chilling indoors with you as you work, or binge on your TV shows. She would do best in a lower-activity environment, so we are recommending a child-free home. Cake will be pyrfect for a patient family who will have time to dote on her and let this girl be an essential part of their family.

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Ciki is a female white Bull Terrier. She is 6 years old and she weighs 60 pounds. Ciki is spayed and vaccinated including rabies. She tested light heartworm positive and is undergoing the slow-kill method of treatment using heartworm prevention medication. She has had a Proheart shot to provide 6 more months of treatment. She is ready for adoption. 

Ciki is sweet girl who loves her people...all of them. She is dog friendly with easy-going dog companions. She has lived with dogs as small as 10 lbs and as large as 80 lbs...temperament is the key and we would want her to meet potential canine family members prior to adoption. Ciki is aggressive about dogs she can hear but not see and dogs she meets when leashed or across a fence. She also should not be around livestock. Ciki needs a strong handler when out and about. But in the home she is a cool cookie and enjoys her family. Ciki is crate, potty and leash trained (with the note above). Ciki also enjoys car rides. 

Ciki was with us last year and was adopted in the fall, living happily in a new home for several months. Ciki had to return to us due to problems in the home unrelated to Ciki but meaning it was no longer the right home for her. We know quite a bit about her and what kind of home she needs.

animal.description:
#ClintDeservesThe Best

This sweet boy loves other dogs, has shown no prey drive, and loves everyone he meets. He has a condition from birth, so he's a little uncoordinated and lacks some cognitive and social skills - so he has a hard time understanding that mouthiness/light biting on you does not equal love (not hurtful). But with the right parent who has time to love him and work on his quirks - he's going to be the perfect dog.

This boy needs a special person with a special heart. He is believed to have cerebellar hypoplasia, which is a disease that effects how the cerebellum develops. Which means he doesn't have good depth perception and stumbles some. He is a love bug who has no idea he doesn't walk or run quite like the other dogs - and we are not going to tell him! He is a smart and silly boy with a heart of gold. 

Clint is a loyal companion who loves to snuggle next to his person. He is a happy, playful pup and we can't get enough of him! He loves being part of a pack and would love a canine friend in his furever home - a confident dog that can show him the ropes would be good. He likes to be involved in any fun going on and when we are inside he wants to follow you around. 

He is an Anatolian Shepard who loves water, people, other pups and squeaky toys! He weighs around 55 pounds. He is still a puppy and is learning the ropes of the big boys but still needs a little training but he is 100% worth it and is still a lap dog! 

Treatment for him is TLC with an emphasis on L. He is not in pain. He will always be like this and that's what makes him the special boy he is. 

All Dallas DogRRR adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon finalizing adoption. The standard minimum donation for puppies is $325 + 8.25% tax = $351.81, for dogs over 12 months the adoption fee is $225 + 8.25% tax = $243.66 and for our senior dogs 8 years and up is $100 + 8.25% tax = $108.25; this increase includes sales tax recently required by the State of Texas to collect. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. 

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process.

animal.description:
Hello -  My name's Bernie.   I am about four years old and kind of a rolly polly pit bull.  I'm a lot of fun and have a big fan club, including the rescue where I was raised, the staff and volunteers at Sammie's Friends and even the Animal Control Officers are on my fan club list.

I do have a past, however, that I need to fully disclose and hope that you will love me anyway, as my fan club does.  Here goes I was raised at a rescue and got along with everyone, the other dogs, chickens and other farm animals.  I swam in a pond for hours and life was good.   Then I got adopted by a fairly irresponsible person who taught me nothing and let me run wild.  I got into trouble.  On one of my escapades I attacked another dog.  That dog was injured (not too severely) and had to go to the vet.  I shouldn't have done that.   Animal Control came to my rescue and brought me to the shelter where I could get the education and love and care that I needed.  Here's the rap - When you attack another dog you get the label "Potentially Dangerous Dog".   For three years my owner has to meet certain requirements.  It's not as onerous as it sounds.  Don't let this scare you off.   When you come to the shelter to meet me ask a staff member for full details on what is required. 

While I was once good with other dogs, I am not these days.  There is one very mild mannered dog that I have been O.K. with.  I am very loving to humans and would make someone a great companion.   I am not a high energy dog and do not require a huge amount of exercise.   I'm looking for a not high energy person, who is dog savvy and wants a pal to love and watch TV with. 

I am neutered, micro-chipped, UTD on shots.  Come meet me and give me a try.   I know, and so does my fan club, that the right person has to come along that will see that my winning qualities outweigh my past problems.

Love you all,   

Bernie

animal.description:
Note: Due to COVID-19 precautions, the facility is currently closed to the public, but we are making appointments with pre-approved potential adopters. Email fortleavenworthstrayfacility@gmail.com for an adoption application.

Axle was relinquished in summer 2020 because he did not get along with the family's other dog. We aren't sure if he doesn't get along with most dogs or if that was a fluke, but we do know he is great with people. He was adopted shortly after arriving with us, but now he's back again to find a better match.

Friendly guy, pretty submissive, starts off a little shy but is soon eager to make friends with new people. Axle has been doing great on walks with volunteers and loves playtime in the yard. He knows basic commands, comes when called, kennels up beautifully, etc. He rides like a polite gentleman in the car and enjoys going on adventures. 

He's pretty darn awesome, but he'd probably do best:
-- with a dog savvy owner to continue his training and exercise, someone who can help him in situations where he is uncomfortable to ensure a good outcome and continued improvement
-- in a home with no kids or older kids (he was startled from sleep in his last home by a little human and he nipped at the kiddo, but he enjoys playing with kids and might do OK with older, respectful kids who left him alone when sleeping)
-- as an only pet or with pets he "chooses" or is carefully worked into the mix with. We are told he fought with the chihuahua-like dog at his former home and that he has a fear of cats as well. We are still learning about him but haven't witnessed these issues to the extent that living as an only pet is an absolute requirement for him.

Bonus tidbits: 
-- He has extra dew claws on his back feet, so he's got a little bit of Anatolian shepherd, Norwegian lundehund or some other breed in his makeup that is known for that trait.
-- He talks! If he wants you to throw his toy "One More Time!" he'll do his best hound-dog-like impression of the expression. 
-- He's a great retriever and can sometimes even catch a tossed toy in the air before it hits the ground.

The facility is currently closed but we are still accepting adoption applications and making appointments for pre-approved adopters. For an adoption application, email fortleavenworthstrayfacility@gmail.com. Thanks!

Featured as the Pet of the Week in the July 9, 2020, and July 23, 2020, issues of the Fort Leavenworth Lamp.

Adopted August 2020 but returned January 2021 to find a better match.

animal.description: DAISY MAE came to us after she bit her owner in the face. It was a one-time incident however the family was afraid of her after the incident. We were her last hope as an alternative to euthanasia. In our care, Daisy has befriended a couple of our volunteers and is sweet as pie. However, we don’t trust her completely, even with people she knows because she can’t control herself when she gets overstimulated. The original incident happened when they had moved into a new home and Daisy was over excited/stressed and a delivery man came to the door. Her mom attempted to put her into a crate and she resisted and jumped up alligator-style. We are committed to help Daisy even though we understand she may never find a forever home. For the present time being, we are her family and are continuing to try to help her make progress. We will accept applications from exceptional families who have dealt with similar dogs in the past successfully. Daisy needs to be an only pet and although she was fine with the children in her home, because of the bite she needs to be in an adult only home! If you would like to love Daisy from afar, please visit out website and use the PayPal link to support us in her care. www.CompAnimals.org. Thank you!

animal.description:
From the owner...

Coco (the white one) is a male. *blind*

Is literally a live teddy bear, and would cuddle/lay on your lap all day if possible. He tends to still think he is a tiny little puppy and loves to climb all over you and give you kisses.All he needs to get him to him going is a tiny attention and he is all over you. He loves belly rubs and to play with toys. They usually don’t last with him, as he chews through all his toys. But he has lots of fun while the last. He does not like to play fetch, instead he likes to be chased. He likes to show you a toy so you can try and take it from him. He is potty trained but if he has to go he will go inside occasionally. Before he went blind he was over protective with me and did not do well with other dogs. But since he can no longer see I haven’t noticed the same. He tends to do well with kids, so long as they do not hurt him.

Daisy (the black one) is a female. Shes a total princess, she is sassy, loyal, spoiled and always ends up getting what she wants. In her eyes all stuffed animals and toys/balls are hers. She loves to play fetch, she could play fetch all day if possible, never gets tired. She loves car rides, to eat meat and lay in bed under the blankets where she is most cozy. She is potty trained and would never go inside. She is as loyal as a dog can get, she has never so much growled at me. Such a good girl, but is not good with little kids or other dogs. (Until they play fetch with her) Once she knows you and is familiar with you, she is very loyal.

Both are 6 years old spayed/neutered. All of their shots are up to date. During their entire lifetime they have lived indoors, and have never gone an entire day outside, so they are Not outside dogs.

I mostly speak Spanish to them so technically they speak Spanish.

Meet Tucker!

This sweet boy was pulled from the Berkeley County, SC animal shelter in late April 2020. Tucker is estimated to be 7 years old, is fully vetted, neutered and microchipped. He absolutely loves people.

Tucker is currently being fostered in Summerville, SC. While Tucker is wonderful with all people, he is not a fan of other dogs or cats and will need a home without other animals. He absolutely loves being outside and running, and will need a fenced yard.

Tucker can't wait to find his perfect hooman to call his own. He is extremely sweet and deserves a wonderful life! He is very chill, and absolutely adores love and attention from his people.

If you are interested in adopting Tucker, please visit the Adoption Process page on our website – http://carolinasrescue.com/Adoption_Process.html. You can download our Adoption Questionnaire there, then email it to us at adoptions@carolinasrescue.com. That will start the process.

animal.description: We couldn't think of a more fitting name for Twister because once you befriend him, you'll get caught up in a whirlwind of love! If you're a solo person looking for an awesome companion, Twister is your man. This sweet boy will happily sit quietly by your side and lend a listening ear. It's hard not to fall in love when you look into those soulful brown eyes that say, 'Come sit down with me and tell me all about your day.' Want to play? Well, Twister is a puppy at heart! His joy is contagious when he's chasing after balls or playing tug with his rope toy. He is always up for fun and games, and he will sweep you up into a spin of laughs for years to come. While he has great leash manners, Twister prefers to stay in and play as he has a chronic, non-contagious skin condition that flares up with too much exposure to the great outdoors. His foster mom says he looooooves playing brain games and is happy as a clam entertaining himself with puzzles. Plus, he's well-mannered in the house and crate-trained to boot! A gentle soul, and a quiet companion, Twister is happiest in a home with just one best friend. He also wants to be the only animal in the home. He's the kind of guy that you can pour your heart out to - and he really listens. He's super easy to have in the home, and everyone says the same thing about him.... 'He's just so sweet'! Twister is loved by all at APA!, and we are waiting for his one true friend to come along and scoop him up. With his outstanding obedience skills and those heart-melting eyes, he will quickly find his way into your heart and fill it up. Twister enjoys learning new things (as long as there are snacks involved) and is in the Total Obedience Program. Check out a video on APA's CGC program to learn more: https://vimeo.com/89434193. Follow Twister on Instagram @adopt_twister

animal.description:
Meet Griffin!

Griffin is a 2-4 year old male yellow lab! He was brought into Mutt Misfits through a partner program with a local shelter. We pulled him because we believed he had an upper respiratory infection, but we later learned it was actually Distemper! Griffin was rendered immobile from having distemper and has been working to regain mobility in his back legs for a few months! He is now close to being able to walk on his own due to water therapy and exercising in his foster home! Griffin is neutered, up to date on all age appropriate vaccinations, preventatives, and he's microchipped. 

Griffin is crate trained and potty trained. He does well on and off leash and rides happily in the car.

Griffin is friendly with dogs of all sizes, genders, and ages! He likes to use his front paws to bat and joust with his foster siblings. Griffin hasn't been around cats or children, but with slow introductions he could do well with them.

Griffin is a playful and friendly lab! He is on the smaller side with being under 50lbs, but he makes up for it in personality! He loves to sunbathe on the patio with his foster siblings and snuggle up on the couch with everyone for a good movie night! Griffin will need continued exercise to maintain the muscles and strength in his hind legs. Griffin will make a great addition to any family!

Baxter is an approx. 4-5 year old, tri-colored, purebred, male Beagle.  He is 20 lbs., full grown and super sweet.  He is great with other dogs and loves everyone he meets.  He needs a farm to call his own, or a family that has other dogs and a huge fenced in yard.  He was not happy living without a fenced in yard and other dogs to play with.  He is very housebroken, leash trained and crate trained too.  He is very affectionate and spoiled.  He's used to the good life and needs the right family to come along and fall in love with him.

He is heartworm negative, has been dewormed, had all of his vaccinations for the year, is neutered, and on monthly heartworm and flea prevention.   His adoption fee is $200.00.

If you're interested in adopting, please send us a completed dog adoption application back to us digitally:

http://jenniferspetrescue.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/CanineAdoption.pdf

We go in the order in which we received completed (and approved) adoption applications and not by Petfinder inquiries.  Once your application has been approved, then we will answer any questions you may have.  Also you must be LOCAL to Dallas, GA; within an hour or so to adopt from us.  We apologize in advance, but we just don’t have the resources to get back to every single person that inquires to adopt from us during COVID-19, but know that we do try.  You’ll hear from us ASAP if you are picked to adopt!

P.S.	Petsmart adoptions are a thing of the past for now, so no we will not be there this weekend.  All adoptions are done by appt. only now in Dallas, GA and if you see this animal listed on Petfinder, then YES he or she is still available for adoption.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Johnny Cash, the singing dog! He bursts into song on a whim, out of the blue. If you sing, he will raise his head way up and join you in his best opera voice. Impress your friends on a group call! He also sings to his favorite music on tv or radio. He is selective about his song choices, but once he starts, he might give you an entire concert. It's hilarious!

This baby-faced sweetheart wants nothing more than to be adored and loved by you. He is a happy, affectionate boy.

When sweet Johnny was born in early 2014, he had a genetic defect with femurs that are bowed and twisted, giving his knees an awkward angle and giving him a wonky stance where he walks on his tippy-toes. Unfortunately, there is nothing that can be done to fix this, but it doesn't slow him down. He can climb steps and get up on the couch or in to the recliner with no problems.

Johnny is a good-sized boy at 95 pounds. He needs to keep his weight there or a little less, so he can remain agile. He still likes to play!

Johnny needs to be the only dog in his family. Placing him with other dogs could lead to disaster. When other dogs near him get up to move, he jumps up and growls at them. Maybe he feels compromised by his unstable legs and is afraid of being hurt; he goes on offense. He is equally uncomfortable around dogs in day care.

He is totally fine with cats.

He hopes for people who spend most of their time at home with him. He is a homebody - happiest being cozy with his people and taking an occasional romp around the yard. He wants to be included in everything you do.

He needs help getting into a car, but he is a fantastic rider! He is house trained and crate trained.

The only thing Johnny asks of you is if you will please run the vacuum cleaner while he is outside for the moment? That wild contraption is the scariest thing in the world!

People in the home should always be aware that his balance isn't the best, so they shouldn't lean on him or rough-house with him. If there are children in the home, they should be old enough to understand how to be polite with him.

Johnny really is a pleasure to have around. Who can resist a singing dog? Karaoke anyone? Duet with your best buddy?

SPIN Pyrs are all in foster homes in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. Potential adopters are asked to make travel arrangements if they live elsewhere. All SPIN dogs are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and on heartworm prevention. Please go to our website www.SpinRescue.org and fill out an application for this great Great Pyrenees!

Additional info:

Muffin is initially very shy and nervous when she meets someone new. She is especially fearful of men so it takes her a lot longer to open up to them. 

She is great with other dogs in the home and does need another dog.  She still has some minor leash aggression.  Muffin is not house trained but is working on it, so needs someone around often to continue working with her. 

She does bond very quickly to her person and will bark to get your attention. She is not too fond of her crate, but goes in without a fuss and once she's in she settles down and doesn't make a peep. 
 She knows basic commands like "sit and "stay".   She loves to play fetch and will be good in a home with older kids.  She'll make a great family dog.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

animal.description: Rescue date 6/15/17 SHELBY is a cute little PUREBRED Chihuahua who is about 4 years. old and weighs 9 lbs. She was one of several dogs who were rescued from the backyard of someone who was unable to provide them with proper care. She loves other dogs but is a bit on the unsure side when interacting with humans. She's a sweet girl who just needs to continue working on building her confidence. She is best suited for a quiet adult family in which someone can be with her throughout most of the day. Having a well-adjusted companion dog to follow and learn from would be extremely helpful to her as well. She just needs someone to believe in her and help her to blossom into the happy, confident little fur-kid who she deserves to be. The Adoption Fee for SHELBY is $225 and includes spay, up-to-date vaccines, and microchip with registration. Please NOTE that she is AVAILABLE for ADOPTION in CA ONLY! Please understand also that we are a non-profit organization that operates on a small number of volunteers. We are, therefore, UNABLE to ACCEPT PHONE CALLS at this time. If you'd like more information about SHELBY, please send an EMAIL to us at www.saveasmalldogrescue@gmail.com. To submit an online ADOPTION APPLICATION, please go to the SASDR website at www.saveasmalldogrescue.org. We receive numerous applications. If you are among the finalists in the selection process for SHELBY, you will be contacted by phone from SASDR for a phone visit. If you are not available at the time of our call, we will leave a message that includes a time at which we will try later to reach you. SASDR is located in Phelan, CA (San Bernardino County in southern CA). ThanksWe are located in the High Desert, Phelan, next to Victorville and Hesperia.

animal.description: Eleven-year-old Kirk is an older gentlemen with a heart of gold. This happy guy wants nothing more than to love and be loved in return. Snuggles, leisurely strolls, and cozy naps are among his favorite things. As a senior pup, Kirk has some medical needs and requires a little extra TLC, so hes looking for someone who will offer him patient nurturing in exchange for unconditional love and devotion. Kirk has a positive history with other dogs. We recommend he does not go into a home that has cats or small animals. He currently weighs 66 pounds.Kirk's adoption fee has been prepaid by a generous donor. Kirk is being cared for in a foster home, so is available by appointment only. Please submit an application if you are interested in adopting this animal. Kirk's adopter must be at least 18 years old with valid state-issued identification. ARF encourages family members to participate in the adoption process, especially children and family dogs. Please visit ARF's web site for information on adoption and to view more cute canines.
